<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at Midnight EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Tuesday, April 18, 2000
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
130 Fear Dead in Philippine Jet Crash
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   MANILA, Philippines (AP) -- An Air Philippines jetliner carrying 130 people
crashed in the southern Philippines Wednesday and rescuers said there were no
signs of survivors. The Boeing 737-200, which began its flight in Manila,
circled its destination city of Davao, 625 miles southeast of Manila, before
going down in a coconut grove on nearby Samal island, officials said. Emergency
crews arriving at the site of the still-smoldering plane said there were no
signs of survivors. If that turns out to be the case, it would the worst plane
crash in Philippine history.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Miramax To Distribute Films on Web
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- A major Hollywood studio is joining the ranks of small,
independent filmmakers who make their movies available over the Internet.
Miramax Films, a unit of the Walt Disney Co., has signed an agreement with
SightSound.com to offer 12 full-length feature films on the Web. The studio's
films include such critical and commercial successes as ''Shakespeare in Love,''
''The Cider House Rules'' and ''Pulp Fiction,'' but the company said Tuesday it
hasn't been decided yet which titles would be made available, how soon or at
what cost.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Japan Banks Agree on Merger
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- The Bank of Tokyo-Mitsubishi Ltd. and Mitsubishi Trust and
Banking Corp. agreed Wednesday to set up a joint holding company, which would be
the world's fifth-largest financial group. The two banks will form the holding
company and integrate their operations by April next year, officials said. The
alliance would have $837 billion in deposits and other assets. The move will
enable the banks involved to compete against other planned megagroups in the
financial industry. The new firm will also manage $433 billion in pension and
other trusts, since it combines two BOT-Mitsubishi subsidiaries -- Nippon Trust
Bank and Tokyo Trust Bank -- with Mitsubishi Trust.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
McCain To Back S.C. Flag Removal
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Sen. John McCain intends to tell an audience in South
Carolina Wednesday he favors removing the Confederate flag from atop the state
Capitol in Columbia, and regrets failing to say so while campaigning for the
White House, according to Republican officials. The flag issue flared briefly
during the presidential campaign, when Bush and McCain were competing for votes
in the South Carolina Republican primary in February. The state is home to
thousands of veterans and has a strong conservative streak.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Cops Probe Cuban Mission Attack
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- District police said Tuesday they have launched a criminal
investigation into allegations that some 15 people from the Cuban diplomatic
mission here assaulted Cuban-American protesters who were demanding that
6-year-old Elian Gonzalez remain in the United States. Some of the protesters
suffered minor injuries in the fracas just before nightfall last Friday and were
treated at local hospitals. The disclosure came as the State Department summoned
a top Cuban diplomat here to express ''extreme concern'' over the beatings.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Fed Court Shuts Down Megan's Law
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) -- A federal appeals court has ordered a freeze on sex
offender notifications in New Jersey until it has time to review the fairness of
procedures being used by officials who issue the warnings. U.S. District Judge
Joseph Irenas last week ruled that the state's Megan's Law guidelines, as
revised by Attorney General John Farmer, provided a reasonable system for
warning neighbors about sex offenders while making sure the privileged
information was not leaked to the community at large. But the 3rd U.S. Circuit
Court of Appeals in Philadelphia issued an order Tuesday saying it wanted to
review these facts for itself.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Japan Stocks Slip
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- The Nikkei shed 8.21 points to 18,961.31 in early trading. The
Dow rose 179 to closed Tuesday at 10,762.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Sabres 3, Flyers 2, OT
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   BUFFALO, N.Y. (AP) -- Stu Barnes scored on an off-balance shot 4:42 into
overtime as the Buffalo Sabres stayed alive with a 3-2 victory over the
Philadelphia Flyers on Tuesday night. Curtis Brown and Miroslav Satan each had a
goal and assist for the Sabres, who cut the Flyers' best-of-7 series lead to
3-1. Game 5 of the first-round Eastern Conference playoff series is Thursday at
Philadelphia.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Devils 2, Panthers 1
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   SUNRISE, Fla. (AP) -- Brian Rafalski had a goal and an assist and the New
Jersey Devils moved within one victory of advancing to the second round for the
first time in three years with a 2-1 win over the Florida Panthers on Tuesday
night. The Devils took a 3-0 lead in the best-of-7 series. Game 4 in the Eastern
Conference playoff series is Thursday at Florida.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
AP NewsBrief By VINCENT K. WILLIS
</SUBHEAD>
