<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Leaders acknowledge that budget will not be done this week  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- State legislative leaders say disagreement
between the Legislature and Gov. George Pataki over spending, debt
reform and other issues means a new budget will not be in place by
their self-imposed deadline.
</P>
<P>
   While deals were made on most aspects of the $78 billion
spending plan for fiscal 2000-01, negotiations bogged down late
Monday and little progress was apparent Tuesday at untying the
knot.
</P>
<P>
   As it was, the wall the bargaining process hit Monday night
caused enough of a delay to prevent legislators from being
presented with the budget for passage by sundown today, when
Passover begins. Legislative leaders had wanted to use that
deadline to compel lawmakers to approve a new budget.
</P>
<P>
   The most significant problem in negotiations, at least from the
governor's perspective, appeared to be the questioning by Pataki's
Budget Division whether longer-term spending estimates of some
legislative programs were accurate.
</P>
<P>
   ''The numbers that came out were different from different
perspectives,'' state Assembly Speaker Sheldon Silver said Tuesday.
''Right now, the Budget Division doesn't seem to agree with
legislative (fiscal committee) secretaries.''
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic Assembly charged that Pataki, a Republican, had
gummed up the talks by insisting on a proposal he made in January
to have homeowners get their rebate checks directly from the state
instead of from school districts under the ''STAR'' property tax
reduction program.
</P>
<P>
   The other player in the budget negotiations, Senate Republican
Leader Joseph Bruno, said Tuesday he agreed with the change because
it would make it harder for school districts to conceal tax
increases from local residents.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's much more honest,'' Bruno said on radio station WROW-AM
in Albany. ''It's much more upfront. It's what the Legislature and
the governor originally intended when they put that (STAR program)
in place.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats accused Pataki, however, of wanting to get credit more
directly for the STAR program, which the governor championed before
it became law.
</P>
<P>
   The governor was also pushing for debt reform measures.
</P>
<P>
   The budget is for the fiscal year which began April 1. This is
the 16th straight year that budget adoption has been late.
</P>
<P>
   Not approving a budget this week will delay the process until
May 1. Legislative leaders say they will not have their members
work between Passover and Easter, and lawmakers planned to take
next week off for their annual spring vacation.
</P>
<P>
   The Legislature is not scheduled to be back in session until May
1. Lawmakers earlier this month passed a temporary spending bill
which will keep the state solvent through April 30.
</P>
<P>
   Despite this week's failure, both Silver and Bruno insisted
Tuesday that virtually all of the budget had been negotiated and
agreed to.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think most of the work has been done,'' Silver said.
''Drafting has to take place over the next week or two. Some of the
differences have to be ironed out.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
