<HEADLINE> New York City philanthropist a possible Conservative Partycandidate  </HEADLINE>
By ANNY KUO, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- A New York City philanthropist is emerging
as a possible Conservative candidate in the U.S. Senate race that
now pits Hillary Rodham Clinton against Mayor Rudolph Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   Virginia Gilder said state Conservative Party Chairman Michael
Long approached her last week to discuss a possible run as a
third-party candidate.
</P>
<P>
   ''It has not been my life ambition to run for office, but on the
other hand, nobody seems want to run for office anymore except
people who seem to make a profession of it. We citizens kind of get
left in the dust,'' Gilder said.
</P>
<P>
   ''She possesses conservative principles,'' Long said. ''She
could turn this into a three-way race.''
</P>
<P>
   The Conservative Party has said Republican Giuliani is not
conservative enough. The mayor supports abortion and gay rights and
refuses to denounce what critics call ''partial-birth'' abortion.
</P>
<P>
   No Republican has won statewide office in New York without
Conservative Party backing since 1974.
</P>
<P>
   Gilder, a private investor, co-founded the anti-tax group Change
New York with her husband Richard and currently serves as
chairwoman of the group. The couple were major contributors to Gov.
George Pataki's 1994 campaign.
</P>
<P>
   She said it would take ''a few weeks'' before she reaches a
decision.
</P>
<P>
   ''We've got a lot of evaluating to do,'' she said. ''This is a
very preliminary discussion to a possible 'yes' decision.''
</P>
<P>
   If she does run, Gilder said she would focus on education
reform. She is a staunch proponent of school vouchers and in 1997
put up $1 million of her own money to offer private-school
scholarships for students who attended the Giffen Memorial
Elementary School in Albany.
</P>
<P>
   Gilder also said she supports congressional term limits and tax
reform and opposes abortion.
</P>
<P>
   She said her beliefs are ''totally at odds'' with the first lady
but added that Conservatives are ''unclear about just how committed
and in what specific way (Giuliani) is about some issues that
concern us.''
</P>
<P>
   Gilder said she would be able to make a ''considerable
contribution'' to financing her campaign but said it is still
premature to discuss that.
</P>
<P>
   Long said his party is also looking at other possible candidates
but refused to identify them.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
