<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-19 00:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Colombian Guerrillas Free Hostages  </HEADLINE>
By MARGARITA MARTINEZ, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) -- In a move the government said will help
promote peace talks, Colombia's second-largest rebel army on
Tuesday freed eight hostages seized a year ago in the hijacking of
domestic airliner. Five people are still being held.
</P>
<P>
   ''This deed is very important,'' peace commissioner Victor G.
Ricardo was quoted as saying by the official government news agency
ANCOL. ''In this way we are getting closer to promptly initiating
the (peace) process'' with the National Liberation Army.
</P>
<P>
   The seizure of the Avianca airlines Fokker 50 by guerrillas of
the leftist ELN was widely seen as an attempt to pressure President
Andres Pastrana's government into opening a peace dialogue with the
rebel group.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 46 people kidnapped on April 12, 1999, all but five have
now been freed. One died in captivity.
</P>
<P>
   ELN leaders had said they would seek ransom for at least some of
the kidnap victims, but it could not be determined whether any
money was paid to secure Tuesday's releases.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is like coming back to life,'' said Leslie Kally, who
turned 18 during her captivity. She carried a wooden staff painted
with 372 rings, one for every day she was held.
</P>
<P>
   ''But no one is free here,'' Kally said of her country, where
much of the countryside is controlled by armed outlaws --
principally leftist rebels and right-wing paramilitary fighters.
''In Colombia we are all prisoners.''
</P>
<P>
   The handover occurred in an area known as Zona Azul in the
remote northeastern region that the ELN is demanding the government
clear of troops as a condition for peace negotiations.
</P>
<P>
   The ELN, with an estimated 5,000 fighters, is one-third the
strength of the main rebel band, the Revolutionary Armed Forces of
Colombia, or FARC. Pastrana withdrew troops from a huge swath of
southern Colombia in November 1998 as a condition for peace talks
with the FARC that have moved glacially.
</P>
<P>
   Pressuring for a government troop pullout in its traditional
stronghold in the northern state of Bolivar, the ELN has also
dynamited dozens of electrical pylons in recent months, forcing
rationing for millions of Colombians.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
