<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-19 01:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> TLC mandates partitions or cameras for livery cars  </HEADLINE>
By DONNA DE LA CRUZ, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- The recent rash of livery cab driver murders has
spurred the Taxi and Limousine Commission to require all drivers to
install bulletproof partitions or digital security cameras in their
cars.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think the tragedies over the last couple of months show us
we have to move and we have to move quickly to protect the
drivers,'' commission chairwoman Diane McGrath McKechnie said
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   This year, seven livery drivers have been killed. In 1999, 11
were murdered. None of the drivers killed this year had a
partition, police said.
</P>
<P>
   Another driver was injured Tuesday when a passenger attacked him
with a machete, police said.
</P>
<P>
   The commission convened a special meeting to vote on the rule,
which it adopted on an emergency basis for the next 60 days. Before
the temporary measure expires, the commission will hold public
hearings to make it permanent. Drivers have 30 days to comply.
</P>
<P>
   Fernando Mateo, president of the New York State Federation of
Taxi Drivers, said the TLC's ruling was a victory for the industry.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's what the federation asked the mayor to do, and the mayor
has granted us our wish,'' Mateo said. ''I think it's a step in the
right direction.''
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Rudolph Giuliani has pledged $5 million in a grant program
to help pay for the security devices.
</P>
<P>
   McGrath McKechnie, the TLC commissioner, said the grant will pay
for drivers to buy partitions, which cost between $250 and $350,
but will pay only up to $350 for cameras, which start at $600. She
estimated that about half the 41,000 livery drivers currently have
neither of the security devices.
</P>
<P>
   The only exception to the new rule will be for livery cars owned
by companies that cater to corporate clients and take only vouchers
or credit cards.
</P>
<P>
   The TLC also stressed to livery drivers that they must stop
picking up street fares. Only yellow-cab drivers are allowed to do
so. Livery drivers must be dispatched to passengers, but many flout
the rule and take street hails to make extra money.
</P>
<P>
   Of the seven drivers killed this year, six were murdered by
passengers they picked up on the street, police said.
</P>
<P>
   A street passenger fatally shot livery driver Luis Francisco
Perez once in the back of his head Friday, making the 29-year-old
the sixth driver killed this year. On Tuesday, a huge funeral
procession made up of livery cars accompanied Perez's body from a
funeral home in the Washington Heights neighborhood where he lived
to the site of his death in the Bronx.
</P>
<P>
   The procession then headed for John F. Kennedy International
Airport for the flight to Perez's native Dominican Republic, where
he was to be buried.
</P>
<P>
   Also Tuesday, two police officers on patrol in the Bronx saw
livery driver George Radhaes running after a man around 3:15 p.m.
at 190th Street and Grand Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   Radhaes told the officers that he had picked the man up at
another Bronx location and that the suspect had pulled out a
machete and demanded money. There was a struggle, and Radhaes was
cut on the hand. He was taken to Montefiore Medical Center for
treatment.
</P>
<P>
   The officers chased the suspect, who was identified as Ignancio
Molina, 43, of the Bronx. He was in custody this morning.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Taxi and Limousine Commission: http://www.ci.nyc.ny.us/html/tlc
</P>
</TEXT>
