<HEADLINE> Knights of Columbus building $10 million museum  </HEADLINE>
By DIANE SCARPONI, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW HAVEN, Conn. (AP) -- The Knights of Columbus are building a
$10 million museum near their headquarters to showcase religious
art and teach people about the history of the 118-year-old group
and Roman Catholicism in the region.
</P>
<P>
   Also on display will be personal items and correspondence of the
Rev. Michael J. McGivney, a candidate for sainthood, who founded
the Knights of Columbus in New Haven.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers will have access to archives, a library and rare
books. A theater and a gallery for touring art exhibits also are
planned.
</P>
<P>
   The museum will be free and open to the public, including area
school groups, Supreme Knight Virgil C. Dechant, the leader of the
1.6 million-member organization, said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ''We really want to appeal to the public at large,'' Dechant
said.
</P>
<P>
   Arts organizations in the area welcome the new attraction, said
Lisa Rovello, director of development and communication for The
Arts Council of Greater New Haven.
</P>
<P>
   The city already attracts about 2 million visitors a year to its
museums, galleries, theaters, concert halls, festivals and historic
attractions, Rovello said.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think this is going to be an exciting addition to the great
range of cultural attractions greater New Haven has to offer,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Renovations of a three-story office building are underway, with
an opening planned for the fall and a grand opening ceremony
planned for next spring.
</P>
<P>
   Many exhibits will be relocated from a small museum in the
headquarters building that was inadequate to display the group's
holdings. Other items will be put on public display for the first
time.
</P>
<P>
   Dechant said he hoped the museum would increase the number of
art works, artifacts and memorabilia donated to the group.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor John DeStefano said the museum will form a trinity of
attractions for visitors to New Haven who want to learn about the
Knights. Each year, Knights from all over the world come to the
city to see the headquarters building and St. Mary's Church, where
McGivney founded the organization and where he is entombed.
</P>
<P>
   The museum plan ''adds a sense of excitement about the city,''
DeStefano said.
</P>
<P>
   The Knights of Columbus are paying for the whole project. The
nonprofit service organization for Roman Catholic families does
charity work and runs an insurance program for members.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
