<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Researchers meet to look for answers in lobster dieoff  </HEADLINE>
By DENISE LAVOIE, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   STAMFORD, Conn. (AP) -- A group of environmentalists and
scientists has come up with an action plan as they try to discover
why a record numbers of lobsters are dying in the western portion
of Long Island Sound.
</P>
<P>
   According to lobstermen's estimates, about 90 percent of their
catch has been lost since September.
</P>
<P>
   The lobstermen traded ideas and suggestions during a two-day
''lobster health symposium'' that ended Tuesday. Both the
lobstermen and the scientists who attended the conference said
there is no readily identifiable single cause for the lobster
deaths.
</P>
<P>
   The action plan developed by those who attended the conference
includes:
</P>
<P>
   --collecting more data on the lobsters
</P>
<P>
   --establishing a timeline to determine exactly when they began
dying, in what areas of the sound and in what numbers
</P>
<P>
   --implimenting a tagging program so lobsters can be tracked to
see if they are moving to the eastern part of the sound.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the lobstermen suggested their catch was killed by
pesticides that were sprayed in Connecticut and New York last fall
to combat the outbreak of the West Nile virus spread by mosquitoes.
The lobsters began dying in large numbers in September, just after
the spraying.
</P>
<P>
   Others suggested that the high mortality was caused by hypoxia --
low oxygen content in the water -- which has been a long-standing
problem in the sound. Still others said the lobsters may have
suffered from thermal stress because the waters may have been too
warm.
</P>
<P>
   Richard French, a veterinary pathologist at the University of
Connecticut, said testing done on about 300 lobsters since October
has shown that a parasite called a paramoeba is infecting the
lobsters. But UConn scientists are checking whether other factors,
such as pesticides, sewage treatment plant discharge, other
contamination, thermal stress or hypoxia are contributing to the
dieoff.
</P>
<P>
   ''What we don't know is what role those factors play in the
overall health of the lobsters ... so we don't have all the
answers,'' French said.
</P>
<P>
   French said healthy lobsters normally are able to fight off the
parasite, and scientists still don't what is making lobsters
susceptible to the parasite this time, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Bayer, executive director of the Lobster Institute at the
University of Maine, said the lobster population in Maine has not
been affected by the parasite. Even lobstermen in the eastern
portion of Long Island Sound have also been largely unaffected,
although they have reported an increase in the number of lobsters
with shell disease.
</P>
<P>
   Bayer, who also tested some of the dead lobsters taken from the
western portion of the sound, said he found an assortment of
bacteria in the blood of many of the lobsters, but not all.
</P>
<P>
   ''At this point, finding the cause is partly a process of
elimination,'' he said. ''We want to know what is different about
what happened in Long Island Sound this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Five lobstermen's associations also plan to collect dead
lobsters and sediment from the sound to submit to an independent
lab for additional testing. The testing is being funded by a New
York-based fisheries conservation group, FISH Unlimited Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Long Island Sound is the nation's No. 3 lobster market behind
Maine and Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   Connecticut brings in about 3.5 million pounds a year, while New
York brings in about 8.5 million pounds.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-04-19-00 0134 </TRAILER>
