<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Scott Smith files motion claiming jury misconduct  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   LITCHFIELD, Conn. (AP) -- The New Milford police officer
convicted of manslaughter for killing an unarmed suspect has asked
the trial judge to overturn the verdict because of alleged juror
misconduct.
</P>
<P>
   In his motion Tuesday, Scott Smith's attorney, John Kelly, cited
nine instances of alleged juror misconduct during the trial.
</P>
<P>
   Waterbury State's Attorney John Connelly, who tried the case,
said he was confident the conviction would stand. Smith is
scheduled to be sentenced on May 5.
</P>
<P>
   Smith originally was charged with murder after fatally shooting
Franklyn Reid, 27, in the back at point-blank range. He claimed the
shooting was in self defense. Kelly said the jury never reached a
unanimous verdict on the murder charge before discussing and voting
to find Smith guilty of manslaughter.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Kelly said:
</P>
<P>
   --One juror displayed a badge to the jurors, stated that he had
law enforcement experience, that he knew about training police
officers received, and that the manner in which the defendant shot
and killed Franklyn Reid was improper and was not consistent with
police training.
</P>
<P>
   --One or more of the jurors stated they had served in the
military, had been in combat, that the defendant's shooting
Franklyn Reid was like being in combat but was not justified.
</P>
<P>
   -- Several jurors stated to the other jurors that they wanted to
have the court reporter re-read the defendant's testimony. The
other jurors refused to let the several jurors prepare a written
request to the trial judge to have the defendant's testimony read
to them.
</P>
<P>
   --Upon entering the jury room to begin deliberations, and before
deliberations had begun, one juror stated to the other jurors that
he had made up his mind that the defendant was guilty of murder. He
further stated he doubted that the other jurors would agree to find
the defendant guilty of murder so he would instead vote for a
manslaughter conviction and urged them to do the same.
</P>
<P>
   --One or more jurors brought notes or pieces of paper into the
jury deliberation room and either read or consulted these notes or
pieces of paper during deliberations.
</P>
<P>
   --One juror drove by the location where the defendant shot and
killed Franklyn Reid. The juror did this is an effort to determine
whether a witness who testified for the State and who was located
in a Sunoco Gas Station in close proximity to the scene of the
shooting could observe where the defendant and Franklyn Reid were
located prior to and after the shooting.
</P>
<P>
   --One juror stated that he had shot and killed deer and that a
deer's legs were positioned in a certain way when it fell. The
juror compared the position of the deer's legs to the position of
Franklyn Reid's arms when he fell after he was shot and killed.
</P>
<P>
   --One juror, referred to as ''Rambo'', caused other jurors to be
fearful and intimidated them into a compromised manslaughter
verdict.
</P>
<P>
   Litchfield Superior Court Judge Charles D. Gill could grant
Smith a new trial, or rule that the alleged statements were proper
in the context of heated deliberations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-04-19-00 0135 </TRAILER>
