<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-19 01:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sheriffs fate to be decided by voters  </HEADLINE>
By ADAM GORLICK, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) -- Connecticut voters will decide if the
jobs now overseen by the eight county sheriffs should be controlled
by the state.
</P>
<P>
   The House voted 147-2 Tuesday to place an amendment to the state
Constitution on the November ballot that would do away with the
sheriff system. The Senate overwhelmingly passed the measure last
week, and it does not need the governor's approval.
</P>
<P>
   On a 143-4 vote, the House also passed a bill that would put the
jobs done by sheriffs and their deputies under state agency
control. Those reforms would go into effect Dec. 1, but would be
contingent upon voter approval of the constitutional amendment.
</P>
<P>
   The reform bill, which also needs approval by the Senate and
Gov. John G. Rowland, would prohibit county sheriffs from raising
money from their employees and pressuring them to campaign against
the constitutional amendment.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Michael Lawlor, D-East Haven, said he's confident the
referendum will pass and the reforms will be in place by the end of
the year.
</P>
<P>
   ''The sheriffs are finished -- over. Game over,'' Lawlor said.
</P>
<P>
   But the eight county sheriffs may be swept into the new system,
which would be overseen by the state's Judicial Department.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Judicial Branch, six of the eight county
sheriffs have been sworn in as Hartford County deputies.
</P>
<P>
   ''That's like having the governor appoint himself as a judge in
the middle of an election campaign,'' said Rowland spokesman Dean
Pagani. Rowland began pushing for the abolition of the sheriffs
system last year.
</P>
<P>
   New Haven County Sheriff Frank Kinney said sheriffs are
traditionally deputized in other counties.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't look at that as an auspicious occasion,'' Kinney said.
''It's just a tradition of the system. I have no intention of
moving to Hartford County or any other county.''
</P>
<P>
   Critics of the sheriff system say it is rife with corruption,
mismanagement and patronage.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is important we eliminate the office of high sheriff as
soon as possible,'' Lawlor said. ''The office has outlived its
usefulness in this state.''
</P>
<P>
   But Rep. Annette Carter, D-Hartford, said the high sheriffs
aren't the ones creating the problems. She said reforms are needed,
but they could be done by keeping the current system in tact.
</P>
<P>
   ''We pass more laws up here that don't take care of the
problem,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Carter's son-in-law served as a supervisor in the Hartford
County sheriffs department.
</P>
<P>
   Under the reform bill, special deputies who now guard
courthouses and transport prisoners would be grandfathered into a
new system as judicial marshals. The deputies currently serving
legal papers such as subpoenas and summonses would be called state
marshals and work for the state as private contractors.
</P>
<P>
   Both judicial marshals and state marshals would maintain their
power of arrest.
</P>
<P>
   The reforms would cost the state as much as $3.6 million,
according to the non-partisan Office of Fiscal Analysis.
</P>
<P>
   Several scandals have shaken the sheriffs system in the past
year, including the alleged rape of a female prisoner being
transported in a New Haven County sheriffs van. In addition, two
county sheriffs have pleaded innocent to criminal charges. The
sheriff system is also under investigation by state and federal
agencies.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-04-19-00 0135 </TRAILER>
