<HEADLINE> Dodgers 5, Astros 3  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Todd Hundley hit a go-ahead two-run homer and
Adrian Beltre and Devon White also homered as the Los Angeles
Dodgers beat the Houston Astros 5-3 on Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Darren Dreifort (1-1) pitched six innings, allowing three runs
and three hits, including Jeff Bagwell's tiebreaking solo homer in
the top of the sixth and Richard Hidalgo's two-run single in the
fourth. Dreifort struck out eight and walked two.
</P>
<P>
   Eric Karros started the winning rally in the sixth with a
one-out ground-rule double against Houston starter Octavio Dotel
(0-2). Hundley, played extremely shallow by center fielder Roger
Cedeno, cleared the fence with the next pitch just as Cedeno
arrived at the wall.
</P>
<P>
   White greeted Doug Henry with his third homer of the season
leading off the seventh to make it 5-3.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Shaw pitched the ninth for his fifth save.
</P>
<P>
   Beltre drove in the Dodgers' first two runs with a sacrifice fly
and a two-out homer that tied the score at 2 in the fourth. Before
that, Beltre had only three RBIs in 40 career at-bats against
Houston pitching.
</P>
<P>
   Hidalgo gave the Astros a 2-1 lead in the top of the fourth,
singling to center on a 3-2 pitch for the only hit of the inning.
Dreifort issued a leadoff walk to Cedeno, who took second on
Dreifort's wild pickoff throw. Bagwell, whose fourth homer extended
his hitting streak to 10 games, was hit by a pitch before Ken
Caminiti advanced both runners with a groundout to first base.
</P>
<P>
   Dotel (1-1) allowed four runs and seven hits in six innings and
struck out 10, tying the career high he established last Aug. 6
against the Dodgers while with the New York Mets.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Sheffield of the Dodgers went 0-for-3 with two strikeouts
and was hit by a pitch, as he failed to get a hit for the first
time in 13 games this season. He had hit in 18 consecutive games,
including the final six last season.
</P>
<P>
Notes: The Dodgers have not had consecutive games rained out at
Dodger Stadium since April 19-21, 1988, when their three-game
series with San Diego was postponed. ... With the AL and NL umpires
now operating under the same umbrella, longtime AL ump Joe Brinkman
worked his first game at Dodger Stadium since the 1978 World
Series. Derryl Cousins, in his 22nd season as a big-league umpire,
made his Chavez Ravine debut at third base.
</P>
