<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-19 02:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 2 Disqualified in Wheelchair Race  </HEADLINE>
By JIMMY GOLEN, AP Sports Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON (AP) -- It doesn't bother Jean Driscoll that two people
who don't need wheelchairs tried to compete in the Boston Marathon
wheelchair race. After all, they didn't get in her way.
</P>
<P>
   ''Certainly, if they had come forward and won prize money, a few
of us would be up in arms,'' Driscoll said Tuesday, a day after she
won her eighth Boston wheelchair race.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty years after Rosie Ruiz was stripped of her title because
she used a trolley as a shortcut, Marathon organizers disqualified
two able-bodied racers from the wheelchair competition. ''To the
best of my knowledge, that's never happened before,'' said Marja
Bakker, a member of the Boston Athletic Association's adjudication
committee.
</P>
<P>
   Organizers don't release the names of those disqualified unless
they finish in the money. Neither is contesting the
disqualification, and B.A.A. spokesman Jack Fleming said it may
have been more a misunderstanding than an attempt to deceive.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't think it was done with any sort of bad intent,'' he
said. ''I would hate, for the sake of these people, if the
impression was that they were trying to pull something over on the
disabled community.''
</P>
<P>
   The two apparently did not give an explanation, but they may not
have known it was not allowed. In Canada, for example, it is
neither uncommon nor against the rules for able-bodied athletes to
participate in wheelchair sports -- a ''reverse integration'' that
fills up leagues and helps the ambulatory understand what
wheelchair athletes experience.
</P>
<P>
   ''A lot of your elite wheelchair athletes say, 'Bring 'em on,'''
said Todd Hatfield, the program manager of Wheelchair Sports USA,
the national governing body. ''If they're willing to work that hard
-- typically they're carrying some extra weight, because of the legs
and so forth -- they might want the competition.
</P>
<P>
   ''But I just can't imagine an A.B. (able-bodied) wanting to get
in and push a racing chair. I cannot see it. Those people must have
been very hardcore.''
</P>
<P>
   In the United States, wheelchair sports are limited to those
with ''any lower limb impairment that prevents you from competing
in the able-bodied analog sport,'' Hatfield said. Those who qualify
are further classified based on the degree of impairment.
</P>
<P>
   In Boston, those who apply to enter the wheelchair race are
interviewed so they can be put into the right classification. ''The
people who work on that aspect really get to know them,'' Fleming
said.
</P>
<P>
   Six to 12 people are disqualified from the Marathon in a typical
year -- none more notorious than Ruiz, who was the top female
finisher in 1980 with a time that was then the third-fastest in
women's history. Officials determined she skipped part of the race
and, eight days after crowning her champion, stripped her of the
victory.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, a California couple finished first in their respective
age divisions -- seconds away from record times -- but they didn't
look tired or sweaty enough to have run a marathon. When they
didn't show up on surveillance videotapes that had been added
because of Ruiz, they were disqualified.
</P>
<P>
   This year, race judges noticed the two wheelchair racers moving
around the starting line without any apparent impairment. The two
were allowed to race before being approached after they finished;
Bakker said one immediately acknowledged, ''I am not disabled.''
</P>
<P>
   ''The wheelchair division is for people with an impaired range
of motion. That's what it's for,'' Fleming said. ''We have a
division for people who can run.''
</P>
<P>
   Driscoll said she wasn't so much offended as surprised that
someone would choose to scrunch into a racing chair for more than
two hours.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't think they're making light of (disabilities). I think
it's kind of funny they would want to cramp their legs up for 26
miles,'' she said. ''There's a level of comfort you need to be able
to do that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-19-00 0201 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000419.0026 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-19 02:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IOC Doesn't Expect Sydney Protests  </HEADLINE>
By STEPHEN WILSON, AP Sports Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAUSANNE, Switzerland (AP) -- The International Olympic Committee
has played down the possibility of violent protests by Aboriginal
activists during the Sydney Games.
</P>
<P>
   Aboriginal leaders recently threatened violent demonstrations
following the leak of an Australian government report that
minimized the harm caused by a policy of taking Aboriginal children
from their families.
</P>
<P>
   The controversy over what is known as the ''stolen generation''
was discussed Tuesday as Sydney organizers briefed the IOC
executive board on preparations for the Sept. 15-Oct. 1 games.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are not expecting violent demonstrations,'' said Australian
IOC vice president Kevan Gosper. ''There may be some (nonviolent)
demonstrations. We hope not too many.''
</P>
<P>
   IOC leaders expressed confidence in Sydney organizers, who have
been under fire in Australia following a series of ticketing and
budget problems.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are pretty confident the organization is really
excellent,'' said IOC executive Jacques Rogge, who heads the
committee's oversight panel for Sydney. ''Overall, I'm confident
that everything that humanly could have been done has been done.''
</P>
<P>
   With less than five months before the opening ceremony, Sydney
still has to sell more than $120 million worth of tickets in
Australia to meet its budget.
</P>
<P>
   Knight said the next round of sales would begin in May.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are very confident,'' Rogge said. ''We know there is great
interest from the Australian public.''
</P>
<P>
   Sydney and the IOC moved Tuesday to defuse the dispute over
television access to Homebush, a public area that is the site for
most of the marquee sports for the Olympics, including track and
field, swimming, basketball and gymnastics.
</P>
<P>
   Knight announced a compromise plan -- approved by the IOC -- to
allow a restricted number of non-rights-holding broadcasters to
film inside Homebush.
</P>
<P>
   Under the new rules, Olympic officials will issue eight permits
per day to international non-rights-holders and eight to Australian
non-rights-holders.
</P>
<P>
   The permits will be issued on a rotating basis by the Olympic
Coordination Authority, a body of the New South Wales government
that controls the Homebush site.
</P>
<P>
   The broadcasters will be prohibited from filming inside the
stadiums, filing live reports or interviewing athletes outside the
venues.
</P>
<P>
   Sydney officials have cited crowd control as a main reason for
their decision to restrict TV access to the area.
</P>
<P>
   Under previously announced guidelines, all non-rights-holders
would have been banned from the entire Sydney Olympic Park area.
Among those affected were CNN, ESPN, Fox, Associated Press
Television News and Reuters Television.
</P>
<P>
   The rule would have restricted access to local Australian
rights-holders and NBC, which paid $705 million for exclusive U.S.
rights to the games.
</P>
<P>
   The ban led to official protests by TV companies and the threat
of possible legal action against Sydney Olympic officials.
</P>
<P>
   APTN managing editor Sandy MacIntyre welcomed Tuesday's
compromise.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is a victory for common sense and enables the
international news organizations to report the news events that
surround every Olympic Games in a proper manner,'' he said. ''It's
the Olympic ideal that there should be access for all.''
</P>
<P>
   The IOC has accredited 140 non-right-holders for Sydney,
suggesting the competition will be fierce for the daily permits.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are trying to balance crowd management and the legitimate
interests of news media, while protecting our rights holders,''
Knight said. ''They have paid a lot of money for the rights and
don't deserve to be ambushed.''
</P>
<P>
   Knight acknowledged the plan won't satisfy everybody.
</P>
<P>
   ''We think it's a fair compromise,'' he said. ''It's always a
balancing act. When you reach a compromise, you usually don't make
everybody happy. But it's almost always the best result.''
</P>
<P>
   Also Tuesday, Ninian Stephen, a former High Court justice and
governor-general of Australia, was appointed a member of the IOC
ethics commission.
</P>
<P>
   Stephen fills the seat vacated by Gosper, who resigned from the
ethics panel last month amid allegations he accepted excessive
hospitality from Salt Lake City bidders.
</P>
<P>
   The ethics panel was created last year to enforce a code of
conduct for IOC members following the bribery scandal centering on
Salt Lake's winning bid for the 2002 Winter Games. Stephen becomes
the fifth non-IOC member on the eight-man commission.
</P>
<P>
   Gosper, who denies any wrongdoing, remains under investigation
by the ethics panel for a ski trip his wife and two children made
to Utah in 1993 at the invitation of bid chief Tom Welch.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-19-00 0203 </TRAILER>
