<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-19 02:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> No Dress Rehearsal for Barkley  </HEADLINE>
By BOB BAUM, AP Sports Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX (AP) -- Charles Barkley's big farewell will be in Houston
on Wednesday. There was no dress rehearsal in Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   Barkley had flirted with the idea of making a cameo appearance
in the Rockets' game Tuesday night against the Suns, a team he led
to the NBA Finals in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   After Tuesday's shoot-around, he said he would be in uniform but
wouldn't play. But the Rockets never even activated Barkley, and he
wasn't in uniform when the team took the court.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, when the lights were out for the introduction of the
Suns, he walked onto the court, hardly noticed by the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't want to take away from the game,'' Barkley said.
''I've been in the limelight really for 19, 20 years now. I wasn't
playing tonight. It wasn't about me. That's why I waited until the
lights went out.''
</P>
<P>
   Between the third and fourth quarters of Tuesday's game, Barkley
was introduced to the crowd, which responded with a huge ovation.
He tossed a basketball to the Suns' mascot, The Gorilla, who
performed one of his trademark dunks from a trampoline. Barkley
signed the ball and waved to the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   But there were no gifts, and no serious ceremony. When Barkley
left the Suns in 1996, there were bitter feelings between him and
owner Jerry Colangelo, and that hasn't changed.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think the fans have always been terrific here,'' Barkley
said, ''but I don't ever think the Suns organization appreciated
what I brought to the table.''
</P>
<P>
   Barkley said earlier Tuesday that doctors believe because his
injured knee is only at about 70 percent its normal strength, it
would be too risky for him to play on consecutive nights, even for
just a minute or two.
</P>
<P>
   ''Charles doesn't have to prove anything,'' Houston coach Rudy
Tomjanovich said. ''The guy's one of the greatest players to ever
play the game. We love what he's done for us.
</P>
<P>
   ''To me what makes sense is to have one final tribute at home.
Why take the chance of getting him loose here and then having a
back-to-back situation? That just doesn't make sense to me.''
</P>
<P>
   Barkley called an end to his 16-year career after he ruptured a
knee tendon Dec. 8 in Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   But, after rehabilitation, he will make a final appearance in
the Rockets' last game Wednesday at home against Vancouver. He
wants to end his career by walking off the court, not being carried
off.
</P>
<P>
   A brief appearance in Phoenix had seemed fitting. That would
have allowed him to play his last three games in cities where he
played -- Philadelphia, Phoenix and Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Barkley has a home in Phoenix, and he played four seasons with
the Suns when he was in his prime. His first season with the Suns,
he averaged 25.6 points and 12.2 rebounds as Phoenix reached the
NBA Finals, where they lost to Chicago. It was as close as Barkley
would get to a championship ring.
</P>
<P>
   He said the injury has allowed him time to face life after
basketball.
</P>
<P>
   ''Even though I had great sadness that I got hurt, it's kind of
been preparing me for what my life is going to be like next year,''
Barkley said. ''If I had played the entire season, I can honestly
say it would have been really hard and difficult the last month.''
</P>
<P>
   So now he goes back to Houston, to end it on his own terms.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's just been fun. That's the only way to explain it,'' he
said. ''Not many people get to do something they really like to do
for a living. I'm so blessed to do that.
</P>
<P>
   ''When I first started, I said I want to make a million dollars
a year and play for 10 years. My only goal was to take care of my
mother and my grandmother and obviously I've done that. Everything
else has been, 'Wow! Unbelievable!'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-19-00 0203 </TRAILER>
