<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Columbine Gifts Estimated at $9 Mil  </HEADLINE>
By STEVE GUTTERMAN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   LITTLETON, Colo. (AP) -- Three $1 bills in an envelope from Los
Angeles. Stock from a strip-club owner that may be worth several
hundred thousand dollars. A $25,000 check from an elderly woman in
New York.
</P>
<P>
   From a child writing ''here's my allowance'' to a bank cutting a
$128,000 check, the money came rolling in after the Columbine
massacre, the nation's deadliest school shooting.
</P>
<P>
   Estimates of the amount given to charities to benefit the
victims of the massacre at Columbine High School and the bereaved
community range from $6 million to $9 million, possibly more. And
money is still coming in.
</P>
<P>
   ''Because these were children in a sense and because the images
being broadcast out of Columbine were so compelling -- that's the
only explanation I have for the response,'' said Kelley Cahill, a
vice president of Mile High United Way.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, school officials plan a private assembly, a public
memorial service and a candlelight vigil to mark the anniversary of
the rampage, in which two Columbine seniors fatally shot 12
students and a teacher and wounded 23 before killing themselves.
</P>
<P>
   United Way operated the Healing Fund, which was set up a few
hours after the April 20 attack to channel Columbine-related
donations. It took in $4.6 million, much of it accompanied by
sympathetic letters of donors from Colorado to Puerto Rico, Peru,
Japan and Ukraine.
</P>
<P>
   Millions watched on television as students fled the school and
as shocked teen-agers and authorities struggled for answers that
weren't there.
</P>
<P>
   ''When these people were speaking for our community they were so
eloquent, and when you combine that with images like Pat Ireland
being pulled from the window -- it really reached people,'' Cahill
said. ''Many of the letters referred to the images and the
impression they made.''
</P>
<P>
   Cahill said about 80 percent of the donations to the Healing
Fund came from corporations and 20 percent from individuals. Half
came from Colorado and half from out of state.
</P>
<P>
   Where has the money gone?
</P>
<P>
   Of the Healing Fund's $4.6 million, half went to the two dozen
people injured and to other victims. The families of the slain
victims each received $50,000.
</P>
<P>
   Four students with spinal-cord or brain injuries received
$150,000 each, and the families of the 21 other physically injured
children got $10,000 each.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly $900,000 went to outreach programs and other services
aimed to help the community around Columbine, including $755,000 to
the Jefferson Center for Mental Health and more than $21,000 to the
school district.
</P>
<P>
   Community programs received nearly $712,000. The largest Healing
Fund grant was $425,000 for the mental-health needs of Columbine
students, staff and the surrounding community. It pays for nine
full-time counselors for Columbine and its feeder schools.
</P>
<P>
   The Healing Fund wrapped up its work last fall, Cahill said,
clearing the way for a host of more specialized funds accepting
money donated with specific goals in mind, including individual
funds in victims' names.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-19-00 0212 </TRAILER>
