<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UN Warns on Angola Rebel Violations  </HEADLINE>
By NICOLE WINFIELD, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- The Security Council is giving countries
accused of violating sanctions against Angola's UNITA rebels six
months to improve their records before deciding whether to impose
any U.N. penalties on them.
</P>
<P>
   In a unanimously adopted resolution, the council warned Tuesday
that it would consider ''appropriate action'' against violators
based on accusations in a blunt report on breaches of the sanctions
and a continuing investigation by a new monitoring panel.
</P>
<P>
   While vague and lacking actual punitive measures, the resolution
marked the first time the council has formally suggested applying
''secondary sanctions'' for violators of U.N. embargoes, diplomats
said.
</P>
<P>
   In a groundbreaking report issued last month, an independent
investigation outlined the violations of the U.N. fuel and arms
embargo and ban on rebel diamond sales that enabled UNITA to
restart a 20-year-old war with the government in December 1998,
shattering a U.N.-brokered cease-fire.
</P>
<P>
   The report alleged that two African presidents, Blaise Compaore
of Burkina Faso and Gnassingbe Eyadema of Togo, helped UNITA leader
Jonas Savimbi with arms and fuel shipments in exchange for
diamonds.
</P>
<P>
   The report also accused Belgium of having such lax standards at
its Antwerp diamond market that rogue dealers were able to trade
UNITA gems with virtually no obstacles.
</P>
<P>
   The countries implicated have denied the allegations, defended
their records and challenged the report's evidence, noting that it
relied heavily on information provided by rebel defectors.
</P>
<P>
   Several, however, told the council on Tuesday that they had
taken measures to investigate the allegations by setting up
government commissions and committees.
</P>
<P>
   The independent panel report recommended a host of measures to
tighten the grip of sanctions around UNITA, including a three-year
arms embargo on countries that violated the weapons ban.
</P>
<P>
   The chairman of the sanctions committee for Angola, Ambassador
Robert Fowler of Canada, said the absence in the resolution of any
new embargoes shouldn't be seen as a lack of resolve by the
council.
</P>
<P>
   ''My own hope is that the Security Council will not need to
adopt such measures,'' Fowler said. ''That said, the draft
resolution before us makes clear the council's willingness to adopt
such measures if necessary.''
</P>
<P>
   The resolution authorizes a five-person monitoring group to
continue to gather information about alleged violations and allow
implicated countries to report back on ways they are upholding the
sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   By mid-November, the council would review the monitors' reports
and ''consider appropriate action'' against violators.
</P>
<P>
   Diplomats said the vague phrasing would allow ambassadors to
take less punitive measures than sanctions, such as censure or
other diplomatic action -- or no action at all.
</P>
<P>
   Canada had wanted a tougher resolution, as did Namibia, which is
helping the Congolese government fight rebels who are reportedly
supported by UNITA.
</P>
<P>
   But France sought to weaken the call for sanctions on the
sanctions violators, concerned about its former colonies and the
precedent that so-called secondary sanctions would set, diplomats
said.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is not by multiplying the pariah states that we will give
incentives to these to return to the straight and narrow,'' French
Ambassador Jean-David Levitte said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
