<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Democrats Woo an Industry at Odds  </HEADLINE>
By JONATHAN D. SALANT, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- In the hunt for campaign cash, the Democratic
Party is looking to the high-technology sector, an industry at odds
with traditional party allies such as labor unions and trial
lawyers on some key issues.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans hope to use the split to hinder Democratic fund
raising from companies in the technology focused, northern
California region known as Silicon Valley, which, unlike most
business groups, has divided its loyalties between the two parties.
</P>
<P>
   The growth in high-tech companies has turned the industry into a
fertile source of campaign contributions. Already, computer
companies have made $8.5 million in campaign contributions since
Jan. 1, 1999, according to an Associated Press computer analysis of
data from the Campaign Study Group, a research organization that
provides data to the news media. These companies donated more than
the $8.1 million in 1997-98.
</P>
<P>
   And while most business groups lean Republican, the high-tech
industry has given slightly more than half of its money to
Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Democrats find themselves caught between the industry and
their labor allies on the issues of permanent normal trade
relations with China and more visas for foreign, high-tech workers.
Labor opposes these measures; the high-tech industry supports them.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the legal community fought unsuccessful battles
against limits on investor lawsuits, when Congress overturned
President Clinton's veto of legislation in 1995, and more recent
legislation imposing caps on lawsuits filed as a result of the Y2K
computer conversion.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's no question that Democratic relations with high tech
are a concern,'' said Jon Cuneo of the National Association of
Securities and Commercial Law Attorneys, whose political action
committee gave $13,607 to Democrats and none to Republicans last
year.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats from Clinton and Vice President Al Gore to the party's
House and Senate fund-raising committees are making sure they know
the way to San Jose, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Last weekend, Gore, the all-but-certain Democratic presidential
nominee, helped raise $2.6 million for the Democratic National
Committee and $100,000 for his own campaign.
</P>
<P>
   During the first three months of 1999, the DNC took in $250,000
from Netscape co-founder Marc Andreessen and $100,000 from Douglas
Carlston, chairman of Broderbund Software.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton headlined a $1.5 million Democratic Congressional
Campaign Committee fund-raiser this month at the Palo Alto, Calif.,
home of AllAdvantage.com co-founder Jim Jorgensen.
</P>
<P>
   The DCCC, which raises money for Democratic House candidates,
received $66,542 from Microsoft -- including $56,542 worth of
software -- and $10,000 from AllAdvantage.com between January and
March. The National Republican Congressional Committee, which
supports GOP candidates for the House and plans its own Silicon
Valley fund-raiser this spring, got $160,000 from Cisco President
John Chambers, $80,000 from Microsoft and $10,000 from America
Online.
</P>
<P>
   Joel Hyatt, the DNC finance co-chairman who organized last
weekend's Silicon Valley affair, said the high-tech industry and
Democrats may not see eye to eye on everything, but do agree on
non-economic issues such as abortion, education and gun control.
</P>
<P>
   ''There is a legitimate difference of opinion, but let's not let
the few things on which we disagree outweigh the far greater number
of issues on which we agree,'' Hyatt said.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, George W. Bush's liaison to the high-tech community
mentions Gore's links to labor and lawyers while touting the Texas
governor's support of education and tax cuts, a spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   ''The likelihood is the vice president will pander to both and
try to get away with it,'' said Ari Fleischer, a spokesman for the
presumptive Republican presidential nominee. ''We'll be there to
remind them of his pander in the other direction.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore spokesman Douglas Hattaway acknowledged Gore's support from
disparate interests. But he said: ''They all agree that Al Gore
will be better for working people and consumers and the economy
than George Bush with his irresponsible tax scheme.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Democrats' traditional constituencies don't want the
party to get caught up in the Internet frenzy that has driven up
the stock prices of some dot-com companies -- a position they have
willingly backed with campaign contributions.
</P>
<P>
   Between Jan. 1, 1999, and Feb. 29, 2000, the Association of
Trial Lawyers of America doubled its donations from the same period
two years earlier, giving $1.9 million to candidates, compared with
$985,300 in 1997-98, Federal Election Commission records show.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats received more than $8 of every $10, according to the
Center for Responsive Politics, a nonpartisan group that studies
political donations.
</P>
<P>
   Labor unions, meanwhile, have given Democrats 93 percent of
their $31.3 million in campaign contributions in the 1999-00
election cycle, records show.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
