<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-19 02:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines Jet Crashes, 131 Aboard  </HEADLINE>
By JIM GOMEZ, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAVAO, Philippines (AP) -- An Air Philippines jetliner carrying
131 people crashed Wednesday in the southern Philippines, and
officials said all aboard were believed killed.
</P>
<P>
   The Boeing 737-200 left Manila and was unable to land on its
first approach to Davao city because another plane was on the
runway, air traffic controllers said.
</P>
<P>
   It crashed into a coconut grove on nearby Samal Island as it
prepared to make another approach from the opposite direction, they
said.
</P>
<P>
   The pilot had not reported any problems, but it was foggy over
Samal, officials told The Associated Press. The Davao airport does
not have equipment for instrument landings.
</P>
<P>
   Emergency crews arriving at the site of the still-smoldering
plane said there were no signs of survivors. If that turns out to
be the case, it would the worst plane crash in Philippine history.
</P>
<P>
   Defense Secretary Orlando Mercado also said there appeared to be
no survivors. He added it was ''too early'' to determine the cause
of the crash, but said ''there were indications there was cloud
cover in the area, a low ceiling.''
</P>
<P>
   The plane was completely destroyed except for a small portion of
its tail section. A priest sprinkled water over charred bodies as
he delivered last rites.
</P>
<P>
   Smoke from the crash could be seen from Davao, a thriving
commercial center 625 miles southeast of Manila.
</P>
<P>
   The airline said the plane left Manila carrying 131 people -- 124
passengers, including four babies, and six crew members and one
mechanic. A mechanic normally rides on the flight because the
airline does not have one in Davao.
</P>
<P>
   The airline said a maintenance check before takeoff found no
problems.
</P>
<P>
   At Davao's airport, relatives cried and hugged each other as Red
Cross personnel tried to comfort them.
</P>
<P>
   Planes, buses and ferries throughout the Philippines were jammed
Wednesday because of the start of Easter holidays, in which many
Filipinos return to their hometowns.
</P>
<P>
   The crash appeared to be the most serious in the Philippines
since a twin-engine plane slammed into the hills in the northern
part of the country on Dec. 7, killing all 17 people aboard.
</P>
<P>
   In the country's worst air disaster ever, a Cebu Pacific DC-9
jet crashed in 1998 near the top of a fog-shrouded mountain in the
southern Philippines, killing all 104 people aboard.
</P>
<P>
   Several of the country's airlines created since the industry was
deregulated several years ago have been dogged with safety- and
maintenance-related problems.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing began producing the 200 model of the 737 in 1966,
building more than 1,000 over the next 22 years before ending
production. The plane can carry up to 130 passengers.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing spokesman Sean Griffin said this plane was first put into
service 22 years ago. He said he didn't know when the 4-year-old
airline acquired it or whether this specific jet had any problems
previously.
</P>
<P>
   The crash was the third major transportation accident in the
Philippines in a week. April 12, an overloaded cargo ship carrying
more than 200 illegal passengers capsized after leaving Jolo in
southern Sulu province, killing at least 133 people.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, a passenger ship struck an underwater fish trap and
sank south of Manila. All 137 people aboard were rescued.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: http://www.airphilippines.com
</P>
<P>
   http://boeing.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-19-00 0224 </TRAILER>
