<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-19 02:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bush Eyes McCain for No. 2 Spot  </HEADLINE>
By MIKE GLOVER, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   DEARBORN, Mich. (AP) -- George W. Bush has John McCain on his
mind, and is thinking about adding his former rival to the
Republican presidential ticket.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'll give John McCain consideration,'' the Texas governor said
Tuesday, adding that the two may discuss the issue when they meet
next month. McCain aides instantly ruled out the idea, but it
renewed interest in who Bush will choose as his running mate.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from the speculation about the Arizona senator, Bush's
theme of the day was affordable housing. He went to a rebuilt home
in Battle Creek to unveil a proposal for $1.7 billion tax break for
developers who build single-family homes for low-income residents.
Then he traveled to Dearborn for a panel discussion on housing
issues with experts in the field.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, the talk shifted to politics.
</P>
<P>
   ''I know he's said he's not interested, but until I talk to him
and find out how interested or not interested he is, I'll give him
consideration,'' said Bush of McCain.
</P>
<P>
   ''Talk like this is always flattering whether it's from Governor
Bush or (Minnesota Gov.) Jesse Ventura,'' said McCain spokesman
Todd Harris. ''However, Senator McCain has made it more than clear
that he is not interested in being vice president.''
</P>
<P>
   Some in the GOP argue that McCain would be an ideal match for
Bush, since his seven primary wins came largely from luring
independents and Democrats to the polls, which helped set turnout
records.
</P>
<P>
   McCain has always said he has no interest in being No. 2 and
would prefer to stay in the Senate.
</P>
<P>
   Despite that insistence, Bush said the topic may come up May 9
in Pittsburgh when the two have their first meeting since the
primary season cooled.
</P>
<P>
   ''As I walk into the meeting, I'll take him for his word, but I
do want to visit with him,'' Bush said at a news conference. ''He's
been pretty outspoken about his opinions, but I really want to look
him in the eye and visit with him.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush added that ''there will be a lot of people who will be
given consideration.''
</P>
<P>
   One of them, Michigan Gov. John Engler, was standing next to
Bush, who said that ''of course'' he would consider his fellow
governor.
</P>
<P>
   Bush is routinely asked about a running mate and usually
deflects those questions. But when asked about Engler, he declared
on his own that, ''I'll give John McCain consideration.''
</P>
<P>
   Before the politics, Bush offered his newest housing initiative,
a five-year program of tax credits worth up to 10 percent year on
the cost of building homes in low-income areas.
</P>
<P>
   ''The purpose of the program is not just to provide shelter, but
shelter that somebody can say 'this is mine,''' Bush said on the
lawn of a rebuilt home in Battle Creek. ''When you own a home, it
not only enhances the community, it makes the schools better
because you have a certain sense of stability.''
</P>
<P>
   Aides to Democratic rival Al Gore dismissed the new proposal,
arguing it was yet another example of Bush promising something he
hasn't delivered as governor of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ''He keeps making promises he can't pay for'' because of Bush's
proposed $483 billion tax cut, said Gore spokesman Doug Hattaway.
''This is yet another issue where Bush has done nothing in Texas
but expects us to believe he would do as president.''
</P>
<P>
   Documents furnished by Bush's campaign said competition among
developers for the credits probably would drive the value lower
than the total of 50 percent over five years. Up to 20,000 homes a
year could be developed because of the incentives, the papers said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush wrapped up his Michigan campaign swing with a $400,000
fund-raiser.
</P>
<P>
   Both he and Gore were taking today off.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
