<HEADLINE> Reform Party Press Secretary Quits  </HEADLINE>
By LAURIE KELLMAN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Reform Party's press secretary has
resigned, signaling a widening rift between presidential hopeful
Pat Buchanan and allies of party founder Ross Perot, officials
said.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think she resigned because she feels that the Buchanan
campaign is attempting to take over the party and is preventing her
from being able to do her job,'' said party secretary Jim Mangia,
who as a member of the party's ruling board was informed of Donna
Donovan's resignation Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Donovan will remain chairman of the Connecticut Reform Party and
active in other leadership roles, Mangia and other senior party
officials told The Associated Press on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   But her resignation was emblematic of deepening problems between
Buchanan, who joined the party last year, and longtime officials
just as it was recovering from other infighting.
</P>
<P>
   ''I hope we can still sit down and work things out with the
Buchanan campaign,'' Mangia said. ''This is an example of a
deteriorating situation that we have to start to try to remedy soon
or it will be too late,'' Mangia said.
</P>
<P>
   Donovan declined to comment, but officials said her resignation
would be effective Friday. Buchanan's campaign did not respond to a
request for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Following a party meeting in Nashville, Tenn., that turned into
a televised wrestling match between factions, a federal judge in
Virginia last month settled some of the party's infighting by
ousting Jack Gargan as chairman and replacing him with Pat Choate,
Perot's running mate in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan and Choate have known each other for years and are
allies on trade and other foreign policies. Earlier this year,
Choate appeared at Buchanan's side during a press conference in
which the two urged the Clinton administration and Congress to
reject normal trade status for China.
</P>
<P>
   In a move that may have permanently inflamed Perot's allies on
the ruling committee, Choate also sided with Buchanan on the
location of the party's presidential nominating convention.
</P>
<P>
   Perot's supporters wanted it in Long Beach, Calif. Buchanan and
Choate, citing a competing religious convention and a lack of hotel
space there, pushed for Nashville. Perot's allies overruled that,
and the meeting is set for Aug. 10-13 in Long Beach.
</P>
<P>
   Almost immediately, Buchanan reached out to the group and
invited them to his house for a peacemaking session, but a time and
place have yet to be established.
</P>
<P>
   Several Reform Party leaders said that peace may be far away.
</P>
<P>
   Donovan felt Buchanan was usurping her job of talking with
reporters and setting up media events. She also was one of several
leaders who have become uncomfortable with Buchanan's cross-country
drive to get on the ballot in dozens of states and control the
delegates admitted to the convention who will pick the nominee,
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan was in Texas on Tuesday to begin a three-week drive to
get on the ballot there.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-19-00 0225 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000419.0048 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-19 02:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philly, LA Study D.C. Protests  </HEADLINE>
By JEFF WILSON, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Saying they don't want any surprises when
presidential conventions come to their respective cities this
summer, Los Angeles and Philadelphia police officers attended the
World Bank demonstrations in Washington to learn firsthand the
latest tactics employed by protesters.
</P>
<P>
   The demonstrators represented at least 100 groups allied to
protest the International Monetary Fund and World Bank loans to
Third World countries. There were more than 1,000 arrests on
Saturday, Sunday and Monday as demonstrators shut down parts of the
nation's capital but failed to halt the meetings.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, a representative of Global Exchange, a leader of the
Washington demonstrations, said the protest grapevine was
''abuzz,'' with rumors of plans for the Republican National
Convention in Philadelphia and the Democratic National Convention
in Los Angeles this summer.
</P>
<P>
   Representatives of the city's respective police departments say
they will be ready.
</P>
<P>
   ''We did gather some intelligence down there regarding the
methods and means of the protesters,'' said Philadelphia Police
Commissioner John F. Timoney. ''We think we will be fully prepared
for any eventualities.''
</P>
<P>
   He declined to elaborate.
</P>
<P>
   ''We do not anticipate any problems here, however, we clearly
will be prepared for whatever develops,'' said Los Angeles Police
Department Cmdr. David Kalish.
</P>
<P>
   The LAPD decided to take no chances after watching World Trade
Organization protesters overrun Seattle earlier this year. All
police officer vacations and discretionary days off have been
canceled during the convention period and officers have been
undergoing special training.
</P>
<P>
   The 9,600-officer LAPD is the lead agency in charge of keeping
the peace during the Aug. 14-17 Democratic convention at the
downtown Staples Center.
</P>
<P>
   ''Yes, we are concerned,'' Kalish said. ''Therefore we have been
planning for well over a year for the DNC. We have a task force
that has been assembled to coordinate all planning efforts on
behalf of the Police Department.''
</P>
<P>
   A security perimeter will be established around the Staples
Center during the convention, but downtown will not be sealed off
and become an armed encampment, Kalish said. In fact, a protest
area will be set up a block away, and downtown workers will be able
to move about freely and conduct their business, Kalish said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-19-00 0226 </TRAILER>
