<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-19 02:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Uncovers Trade in Women, Kids  </HEADLINE>
By ELAINE KURTENBACH, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING (AP) -- A police campaign to rescue kidnapped women and
children and punish those who snatch and sell them is shedding
light on a massive flesh trade stretching from remote villages to
modern cities, including Beijing and Shanghai.
</P>
<P>
   Some Chinese farmers desperate for brides buy them. Families
purchase sons to carry on the family line because birth control
policies restrict many couples to one child.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking to the Communist Party newspaper, People's Daily,
police assistant director of criminal investigation Bai Jingfu said
widening gaps between rich and poor and inadequate law enforcement
were partly to blame.
</P>
<P>
   ''In some places, the masses have a weak understanding of the
law and do not believe that selling women and children is a
crime,'' Bai said.
</P>
<P>
   After taking power in 1949, the communists virtually eliminated
the flesh trade. Travel and residence controls helped, but they
have loosened over the past 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, 6,802 woman and 1,662 children were reported abducted
or missing in China, while police rescued 7,660 women and 1,814
children, according to government reports.
</P>
<P>
   Police busted a ring operating in the northern provinces of
Shanxi, Inner Mongolia and Hebei that involved an extended family
of 14 people suspected of stealing and selling almost 1,000 babies
over the past three years, state media said.
</P>
<P>
   Thousands of women and hundreds of children have been rescued
since late March, according to media reports. Unknown numbers
remain hidden in villages, either forcibly confined or simply
resigned to their fates. Many children were too small when
kidnapped to remember their original parents or even know they were
''adopted.''
</P>
<P>
   After failing to find a bride by traditional means, Pan Jinshan,
an itinerant mine worker, bought his wife for $436, the state-run
Yangcheng Evening News said. His family managed for more than a
year to keep the woman hidden in Guwang, a village 55 miles from
the nearest town in the impoverished southwestern region of
Guangxi.
</P>
<P>
   Once the woman discovered she had been duped into a life of
virtual slavery, she tried to escape and the family locked her in a
windowless concrete shed, the report said.
</P>
<P>
   When the woman, whom the newspaper did not name, didn't become
pregnant quickly, Pan told his father to also have sex with her to
continue the family name. Thus began a nightmare of constant rape
that continued until villagers informed the authorities, the
newspaper said. Officials surrounded the farmstead, rescued the
woman and arrested Pan and his father.
</P>
<P>
   Many kidnap victims are young rural women tricked into leaving
home with offers of work as housemaids, waitresses or factory
workers.
</P>
<P>
   One of the most widely reported cases was that of Kang Ming'e,
who was orphaned at age 8, abducted and sold to a gold mine boss at
age 12 and became a mother at age 13.
</P>
<P>
   Another woman, a middle school English teacher identified as
Miss Huang, was grabbed in a train station in Zhengzhou in central
Henan province in 1997. Kidnapper Li Xiuzhong, who has been
arrested and convicted, sold her to three different men before she
was rescued on April 1, the Beijing Daily reported.
</P>
<P>
   Jin Yi was snatched at age 13 on the way home from school in
Beijing. Sold for $338 as a future bride for a farmer's son in
eastern Anhui province, she spent seven years doing farm work,
laundry and cooking before informants tipped off police, the China
Women's News reported.
</P>
<P>
   Police and the government-affiliated Women's Federation did not
respond to requests for interviews on the anti-kidnapping drive.
</P>
<P>
   The scale of kidnappings, the use of violence and sometimes
murder to steal children from their parents, and the tendency of
gangs to be well organized and ruthless are all cause for alarm,
Bai said.
</P>
<P>
   In northern Inner Mongolia, a man who bought an abducted woman
from southwestern Sichuan province fatally stabbed a policeman
attempting to rescue her, the Xinhua News Agency said.
</P>
<P>
   The crackdown on kidnapping rings has coincided with recent
advances in police technology, particularly the use of DNA
databanks to identify suspects and match children with parents.
</P>
<P>
   The first reported success in using DNA analysis to match a
rescued child to his parents involved a little boy named Zeng Chao,
a migrant worker's son stolen at knifepoint by a gang from his
family's shanty dwelling in a Beijing suburb.
</P>
<P>
   Chao was sold to villagers in neighboring Hebei province.
</P>
<P>
   Migrant families make easy targets for kidnappers because they
often run stalls in crowded markets and are too busy to watch over
children playing or napping nearby.
</P>
<P>
   When police rescued 42 kidnapped children in Guizhou province in
January, hundreds of migrant families turned up looking for missing
sons and daughters. Police used DNA analysis to match family
members.
</P>
<P>
   One migrant worker from northwestern Gansu province got a
suspended three-year sentence in 1997 after his wife informed on
him for selling their 5-year-old son to a factory owner.
</P>
<P>
   After the mother died of illness last year, the father sold his
3-year-old daughter for $181 and his now 8-year-old son for $483 to
raise money to buy another wife.
</P>
<P>
   ''His future will be the law's wrath,'' the China Women's News
reported.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
