<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-19 02:32 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Panel Seeks Judge's Testimony  </HEADLINE>
By KAREN GULLO, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- Congressional investigators want U.S. District
Judge Norma Holloway Johnson to ''clear the record once and for
all'' and explain why she assigned six Whitewater and Democratic
fund-raising cases to judges appointed by President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Dan Burton, R-Ind., chairman of the House Government Reform
Committee, asked Johnson to testify at a hearing about her decision
to bypass the traditional computerized random selection system and
make the assignments herself.
</P>
<P>
   ''We would like to give Judge Johnson an opportunity to clear
the record once and for all,'' Burton said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter to Johnson delivered Tuesday, Burton said, ''The
committee's objective is to learn why the random selection process
was not used.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson has said politics played no role in her decision to
assign the cases to expedite their disposition.
</P>
<P>
   Legal experts said it's unusual for federal judges to testify
before Congress. Under the constitutional separation of powers,
Congress can't meddle in what courts do. But Johnson is not immune
from inquiries on administrative matters, in the opinion of Stephen
Gillers, a New York University law professor.
</P>
<P>
   ''She has both a judicial function and an administrative
function as a chief judge, so I don't think the decisions she makes
are immune from inquiry by another branch of government,'' Gillers
said.
</P>
<P>
   Burton said the committee, which has scheduled a hearing for May
17, ''intends to focus solely on the administrative process of the
case assignments and will not make any queries which go to the
substance of these or any other cases.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson's administrative assistant, Joe Alexander, refused to
comment.
</P>
<P>
   The Associated Press reported last summer that Johnson bypassed
the traditional computerized system of randomly assigning cases in
two high-profile Democratic cases involving presidential friend
Webster Hubbell and fund-raiser Charlie Trie.
</P>
<P>
   It was later learned that Johnson also directed four other
Democratic fund-raising cases to Clinton appointees. The cases
stemmed from a Justice Department investigation into Democratic
fund-raising practices during the 1996 presidential election
campaign that uncovered illegal foreign donations to President
Clinton's re-election. Burton's committee also has been
investigating the donations.
</P>
<P>
   Under local court rules, which have since been dropped, Johnson
could assign complex or lengthy cases to other judges instead of
using the random lottery system employed in nearly all cases.
Critics questioned whether the special assignments in the six cases
created the appearance of political favoritism.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson said in a letter to a newspaper last summer that she
made the special assignments in the Hubbell and Trie cases ''to
move the docket as expeditiously as possible'' and that politics
was ''never a factor.'' She hasn't spoken publicly about why she
bypassed the random assignment system in the other four cases.
</P>
<P>
   A special panel began an investigation last month into the six
case assignments on behalf of a judicial body that oversees judges'
conduct.
</P>
<P>
   If Johnson refuses the Burton committee's request, the panel
could issue a subpoena ordering her to testify. ''We haven't even
crossed that bridge, because we hope that she will agree to
testify,'' committee spokesman Mark Corallo said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
