<HEADLINE> Recent Airplane Crashes  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated Press	   Other recent air disasters:
<TEXT>
<P>
   --Jan. 31, 2000: Alaska Airlines Flight 261 plunges into the
ocean off the Southern California coast on a flight from Mexico to
San Francisco. All 88 people aboard the MD-83 jetliner died.
</P>
<P>
   --Jan. 30, 2000: A Kenya Airways A-310 crashes into the Atlantic
Ocean shortly after taking off from Abidjan, Ivory Coast, to Lagos,
Nigeria, killing 169 people. Ten people survive.
</P>
<P>
   --Oct. 31, 1999: An Egypt Air Boeing 767 crashes into the
Atlantic Ocean after taking off from John F. Kennedy Airport in New
York on a flight to Cairo, Egypt, killing all 217 aboard.
</P>
<P>
   --Feb. 24, 1999: A China Southwest Airlines plane crashes in a
field in China's coastal Zhejiang province. All 61 people aboard
the Russian-built TU-154 are killed.
</P>
<P>
   --Dec. 11, 1998: A Thai Airways International A-310 crashes on a
domestic flight during its third landing attempt at Surat Thani,
Thailand, killing 101 people. Forty-five people aboard survive.
</P>
<P>
   --Sept. 2, 1998: A Swissair MD11 crashes in the Atlantic Ocean
off Canada on a flight from New York to Geneva, killing all 229
people aboard.
</P>
<P>
   --Feb. 16, 1998: An Airbus A-300 owned by Taiwan's China Airlines
crashes near Taipei's Chiang Kai-shek airport, where it was trying
to land in fog and rain after a flight from Bali, Indonesia. A
total of 203 people die, including all 196 on board and seven
people on the ground.
</P>
<P>
   --Feb. 2, 1998: A McDonnell Douglas DC-9 aircraft operated by
Cebu Pacific Air crashes into a mountain in the southern
Philippines, killing all 104 people aboard.
</P>
<P>
   --Dec. 19, 1997: A Singapore-owned SilkAir Boeing 737 crashes
into a river on Sumatra Island, Indonesia, killing all 104 people
aboard.
</P>
<P>
   --Sept. 26, 1997: A Garuda Airbus A-300 approaching Medan Airport
in north Sumatra, Indonesia, crashes into a jungle and explodes
while trying to land in thick smoke caused by forest fires. All 234
aboard are killed.
</P>
<P>
   --Sept. 3, 1997: A Vietnam Airlines Tupolev TU-134B trying to
land after a flight from Vietnam to Cambodia crashes into palm
trees and bamboo, skids into a rice paddy and explodes during a
rain storm near Pochentong Airport in Phnom Penh. One passenger
survives, and 65 others are killed.
</P>
<P>
   --Aug. 5, 1997: A Korean Airlines Boeing 747 crashes into a deep
ravine and burns during a rainstorm near its landing destination on
Guam Island. The accident kills 228 people and 26 survive.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-19-00 0232 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000419.0056 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-19 02:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Congress, Clinton Differ on Arms  </HEADLINE>
By BARRY SCHWEID, AP Diplomatic Correspondent
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- A top Pentagon official says sale of advanced
destroyers to Taiwan would be considered if a study showed they
were required to defend the island against mainland China.
</P>
<P>
   Undersecretary of Defense Walter Slocombe went on television
Tuesday night to defend the decision President Clinton made the day
before, on the Pentagon's recommendation, to shelve sale of four
Aegis destroyers and other weapons to Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton approved a package of weapons that Sen. John Kyl,
R-Ariz., said was just enough to assist Taiwan without antagonizing
China.
</P>
<P>
   Slocombe said the weapons approved by Clinton on Monday were
what Taiwan needs now. He acknowledged on the PBS ''NewsHour''
program that China had taken a combative stance toward the island
and said the Clinton administration was ''certainly prepared to
consider'' providing Taiwan with the destroyers if a study showed
they were needed.
</P>
<P>
   Several Republican senators, clashing with the administration,
insisted the study was a dodge to avoid approving sales to Taiwan
that might upset China, which considers the island a renegade
province and not a potentially emerging independent democracy.
</P>
<P>
   Three Republican senators, including Majority Leader Trent Lott
of Mississippi, criticized Clinton's decision on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Their statements suggested a legislative showdown with the White
House loomed. But Lott made no overt move to try to force a vote on
the island's defense requests.
</P>
<P>
   Declaring his disappointment, Lott said the Clinton
administration should have done more to enhance Taiwan's security.
''I hope this latest decision will not be misunderstood by
Beijing's leaders as a green light for further threats against
Taiwan,'' Lott said.
</P>
<P>
   Accusing the administration of misrepresenting a smaller arms
package it approved as robust, Sen. Jesse Helms, R-N.C., said only
one of Taiwan's six major requests, Maverick missiles, was
approved. The package also included sophisticated radar capable of
spotting missile launches deep within China.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the chairman of the Senate Foreign Relations Committee
said the administration has given Beijing ''a veto over Taiwan's
defense request.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Tim Hutchinson, R-Ark., said in a separate statement the
administration had sent the wrong signal to Beijing -- that
intimidation will limit the type and quantity of arms sold to
Taiwan for its defense.
</P>
<P>
   Beijing bitterly resents the U.S. military relationship with
Taiwan. Diplomatically, the United States deals with Taiwan
carefully, avoiding any suggestion it is promoting independence for
the island.
</P>
<P>
   In Beijing, Chinese Foreign Ministry spokesman Sun Yuxi said the
government had ''taken note'' of reports of the Aegis decision. Sun
repeated Beijing's position that the United States should ''stop
all arms sales to Taiwan, including the long-range warning radar
and Aegis, so as not to obstruct the improvement of China-U.S.
relations.''
</P>
<P>
   In Taipei, Taiwan's military spokesman, Kung Fan-ding, said
Taiwan wants ''to acquire any weapons that would help build up its
anti-missile defense.'' He refused to comment specifically on the
U.S. weapons sale until there was an official announcement.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-19-00 0237 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000419.0057 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-19 02:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> White House Thinking Environmentally  </HEADLINE>
By JENNIFER LOVEN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The potential environmental damage caused by
government construction along fragile rivers and coastlines would
play a larger role in the approval of levee, dams and other water
projects under a proposal being circulated by the White House.
</P>
<P>
   The proposed policy changes intended to preserve wetlands were
included in a draft memorandum from President Clinton that was
obtained Tuesday by The Associated Press. The memo was sent late
last month to several top administration officials for their
review.
</P>
<P>
   It is especially aimed at the Army Corps of Engineers, the
beleaguered agency that oversees river construction and flood
control but has recently been buffeted by charges that top
officials rigged data to make a $1 billion Mississippi River
lock-expansion project appear economically justified.
</P>
<P>
   Entitled ''Enhanced Protection of Wetlands and Water
Resources,'' the draft memo calls for environmental impact to
receive as much attention as economic benefit when new projects are
considered, likely meaning fewer would be approved.
</P>
<P>
   Several dozen members of Congress from both parties, most of
them from the upper Mississippi River region, sent a letter to
Clinton objecting to the proposal.
</P>
<P>
   ''The new revisions would make it impossible to build another
port authority, improve another levee or maintain existing drainage
structures,'' Rep. Jo Ann Emerson, R-Mo., said last week at a
Mississippi River Commission hearing.
</P>
<P>
   Though the proposal was in the works long before the allegations
about the Mississippi River project became public, Scott Faber with
the conservation group American Rivers said those charges make the
memo more timely.
</P>
<P>
   ''The rational for these changes is stronger than ever,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   A corps spokesman did not return a call for comment.
</P>
<P>
   A White House official, speaking only on condition of anonymity,
said the document may well change ''before it goes final, if it
does go final.''
</P>
<P>
   The source said the primary intent was to modernize the corps'
review process and to ensure it has the best environmental and
economic analysis possible.
</P>
<P>
   The draft memo called for directing the Army secretary to revise
within 90 days the guidelines for assessing civil works projects,
reversing the policy established under President Reagan which
placed far more emphasis on a project's economic benefits.
</P>
<P>
   Under the new guidelines, federal water project evaluations
would have to take into account all threats to the environment. In
addition, the corps would be required to create new wetlands in
place of those destroyed to the same extent required of private
developers. And the agency would have to coordinate with other
federal agencies working on projects in the same area.
</P>
<P>
   ''Federal agencies would avoid adverse impacts to wetlands, to
water quality, and to wildlife refuges, estuaries, coastal waters
and parks,'' the memo says.
</P>
<P>
   The proposal singles out flood-control efforts along the
Mississippi for particular concern.
</P>
<P>
   ''The benefits of flood damage reduction have come at great
expense to the floodplain and riverine ecosystems associated with
the Mississippi River, which we have come to know as 'America's
River,''' it says.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: Army Corps:
http://www.mvr.usace.army.mil/pdw/nav--study.htm
</P>
<P>
   Environmental Defense:
http://www.edf.org/programs/Ecosystems/mississippi
</P>
<P>
   Industry: http://www.marc2000.org
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
