<SUBHEAD>
Japan Banks Agree on Merger
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- The Bank of Tokyo-Mitsubishi Ltd. and Mitsubishi Trust and
Banking Corp. agreed Wednesday to set up a joint holding company, which would be
the world's fifth-largest financial group. The two banks will form the holding
company and integrate their operations by April next year, officials said. The
alliance would have $837 billion in deposits and other assets. The move will
enable the banks involved to compete against other planned megagroups in the
financial industry. The new firm will also manage $433 billion in pension and
other trusts, since it combines two BOT-Mitsubishi subsidiaries -- Nippon Trust
Bank and Tokyo Trust Bank -- with Mitsubishi Trust.
</P>
