<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-19 02:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tennessee Executes Child Killer  </HEADLINE>
By TOM SHARP, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) -- Tennessee executed child killer Robert
Glen Coe by injection on Wednesday, the first person to be put to
death in the state in 40 years.
</P>
<P>
   Coe, 44, was executed for the 1979 rape and murder of an
8-year-old girl.
</P>
<P>
   Tennessee was the only Southern state that has not executed
anyone since the U.S. Supreme Court reinstated the death penalty in
1976. The last execution in Tennessee was in 1960.
</P>
<P>
   In the last month, Coe had twice come within 16 hours of being
executed. Both times, federal courts blocked his execution so they
could review his mental competence. A federal appeals court found
him mentally competent and the U.S. Supreme Court denied his latest
appeal on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   A state Supreme Court gave the final approval for the execution
early Wednesday, overruling a lower court that had issued a
temporary injunction over the execution method.
</P>
<P>
   Coe's case has been in the legal system for more than 20 years
since he confessed to raping and killing Cary Ann Medlin in
Greenfield in western Tennessee.
</P>
<P>
   He told authorities that he had intended only to rape her, but
then ''she told me that Jesus loves me, and that is when I got so
upset and I decided to kill her.''
</P>
<P>
   The then-23-year-old mechanic was arrested three days later as
he was about to board a bus for Georgia. The black shoe polish he
had used to dye his hair was still dribbling down his face.
</P>
<P>
   His attorneys contend Coe's confession was coerced and driven by
mental illness caused from years of physical and emotional abuse by
his impoverished parents.
</P>
<P>
   Some religious leaders had condemned the Tennessee Supreme Court
for scheduling the execution during the holiest week on the
Christian calendar and at the beginning of the Jewish Passover.
Wednesday is the first evening of Passover and four days before
Easter.
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for the state's high court said the justices chose
the date because it was one week from April 11, when the appeals
court found him competent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-19-00 0247 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000419.0062 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-19 02:48 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NHL Playoffs Roundup  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN WAWROW, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   BUFFALO, N.Y. (AP) -- When the elation of winning an overtime
playoff game subsided, goalie Dominik Hasek began thinking about
the uphill task the Buffalo Sabres still face.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a great feeling to win. It was a relief for a couple of
seconds,'' Hasek said, following Tuesday's 3-2 victory over the
Philadelphia Flyers. ''But one win doesn't mean too much. We have
to win three more.''
</P>
<P>
   Hasek stopped 26 shots and Stu Barnes scored 4:42 into overtime
as the Sabres averted being swept out of the best-of-7
opening-round series. Down 3-1, the Sabres will travel for Game 5
Thursday at Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   ''Our goal was very simple, to win the first game and we go from
here. There's still lots of work left,'' Hasek said.
</P>
<P>
   Only two teams -- the 1975 New York Islanders and the 1942
Toronto Maple Leafs -- have rallied to win from a 3-0 deficit in NHL
playoff history.
</P>
<P>
   In other NHL games, New Jersey grabbed a 3-0 series lead over
Florida with a 2-1 victory over the Panthers. Dallas beat Edmonton
4-3, stretching their series advantage to 3-1.
</P>
<P>
   Buffalo coach Lindy Ruff was hopeful the Sabres found a crack in
the Flyers' defensive curtain.
</P>
<P>
   ''I've always said when you're losing, you never know when
you're going to win again,'' Ruff said. ''And when you win a game,
you think you can win them all again.''
</P>
<P>
   Curtis Brown and Miroslav Satan each had a goal and assist for
the Sabres, who won despite blowing a 2-0 lead and overcame yet
another disputed goal.
</P>
<P>
   Rick Tocchet and Keith Primeau scored and Mark Recchi had two
assists for the Flyers, who have lost eight straight overtime
playoff games. Their last extra session win in the postseason came
in the 1995 conference finals against New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's disappointing anytime you have a chance to win the
series,'' Flyers forward John LeClair said. ''It's not the end of
the world. And nobody said we were going to beat these guys four
straight.''
</P>
<P>
   James Patrick set up the game-winning play when he kept the puck
in at the point. He fed a bouncing pass to Barnes, parked in the
slot. Turning toward the net and falling down, Barnes wristed a
shot that went into the top right corner.
</P>
<P>
   ''You just react at that point,'' Barnes said. ''I can't say I
even picked the corner. I just tried to get it on net, and
fortunately it went where the goalie wasn't.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sabres started strong, and were undeterred when Vladimir
Tsyplakov's goal was disallowed 28 seconds in as referee Dan
Marouelli prematurely blew his whistle.
</P>
<P>
   Overcoming that and memories of LeClair's controversial goal in
Game 2, the Sabres built a 2-0 lead when Satan scored on a
one-timer 1:03 into the second period.
</P>
<P>
   The Flyers responded with a two goals, capped when Primeau
chipped in a shot over Hasek with 1:35 left in the second.
</P>
<P>
   Then the goalies took over.
</P>
<P>
   Flyers rookie Brian Boucher was especially sharp. His biggest
stop was getting his arm up to block Chris Gratton's shot from the
slot five minutes into the third period.
</P>
<P>
   ''They seemed to throw everything. You could tell they were
playing desperate,'' said Boucher, whose Flyers were outshot 34-28.
''This was a game we wanted, but we're still up 3-1 and we need to
gather ourselves, go home and give it our best.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sabres did not play a perfect game. At times, they seemed
intent on being eliminated. Ruff was incensed by the undisciplined
penalties taken by defenseman Alexei Zhitnik.
</P>
<P>
   Along with drawing a double-minor for cracking Daymond Langkow
across the side of the helmet, Zhitnik took a foolish elbowing
penalty with 38.2 seconds left in regulation.
</P>
<P>
   Zhitnik was hooked down from behind by Recchi and retaliated by
striking Primeau with a forearm across the back of his neck.
</P>
<P>
   ''It should have cost us the game,'' Ruff said. ''One thing we
talked about was discipline. No foolish penalties, none. No
retaliation. The series should be over when we do something that
stupid.''
</P>
<P>
   The Flyers' power play has been deadly. Six of Philadelphia's
nine goals in the series have come with the man advantage.
</P>
<P>
   The status of deposed Flyers captain Eric Lindros remains
uncertain because of lingering headaches. Lindros, recovering from
a Grade 2 concussion, was in Philadelphia, where he consulted by
phone with his neurologist, Dr. James Kelly of Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   ''We don't know when he'll return,'' team spokesman Zack Hill
said. ''He's supposed to go to Chicago when he's symptom free. And
he is not symptom free.''
</P>
<P>
Devils 2, Panthers 1
</P>
<P>
   Brian Rafalski had a goal and an assist and New Jersey closed on
advancing to the second round for the first time in three years
after winning at Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Game 4 in the Eastern Conference series is Thursday at Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Martin Brodeur stopped 21 shots, including 15 in the third
period. Mike Vernon made 38 saves for the Panthers, who got a goal
from Ray Whitney.
</P>
<P>
   Panthers star Pavel Bure, the NHL's regular-season leader with
58 goals, has yet to score in the series.
</P>
<P>
Stars 4, Oilers 3
</P>
<P>
   Guy Carbonneau scored on a long wrist shot early in the third
period, lifting visiting Dallas over Edmonton, despite Bill
Guerin's hat trick.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars can advance to the second round with a home victory
Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   Brett Hull, Richard Matvichuk and Mike Modano also scored for
the defending Stanley Cup champions.
</P>
<P>
   Guerin was the second Oilers player to score three goals in a
game this series. Doug Weight did it in Edmonton's victory in Game
3.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
