<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 3 a.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   Wednesday, April 19, 2000 
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
131 Feared Dead in Philippine Jet Crash
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   MANILA, Philippines (AP) -- An Air Philippines jetliner carrying 131 people
crashed in the southern Philippines Wednesday and rescuers said there were no
signs of survivors. The Boeing 737-200, which began its flight in Manila,
circled its destination city of Davao, 625 miles southeast of Manila, before
going down in a coconut grove on nearby Samal island, officials said. Emergency
crews arriving at the site of the still-smoldering plane said there were no
signs of survivors. If that turns out to be the case, it would the worst plane
crash in Philippine history.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
China Uncovers Trade in Women, Kids
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   BEIJING (AP) -- A police campaign to rescue kidnapped women and children and
punish those who snatch and sell them is shedding light on a massive flesh trade
stretching from remote villages to modern cities, including Beijing and
Shanghai. Some Chinese farmers desperate for brides buy them. Families purchase
sons to carry on the family line because birth control policies restrict many
couples to one child. Speaking to the Communist Party newspaper, People's Daily,
police assistant director of criminal investigation Bai Jingfu said widening
gaps between rich and poor and inadequate law enforcement were partly to blame.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
First 3 Months of Y2K Warmest in 106 Years
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   NEW ORLEANS (AP) -- The first three months of the year were the warmest in
the nation in 106 years, according to the National Oceanic and Atmospheric
Administration. The latest data also shows that June 1999 through March 2000 was
the warmest June through March period ever in the nation, NOAA Administrator D.
James Baker said Tuesday. The January through March average temperature in the
nation was 47.1 degrees. That is 1 degree warmer than the previous record set in
1990. One degree of difference is a "very robust" margin, said Baker, adding
that global data is still being assembled.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Colombian Guerrillas Free Hostages
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   BOGOTA, Colombia (AP) -- In a move the government said will help promote
peace talks, Colombia's second-largest rebel army on Tuesday freed eight
hostages seized a year ago in the hijacking of domestic airliner. Five people
are still being held. "This deed is very important," peace commissioner Victor
G. Ricardo was quoted as saying by the official government news agency ANCOL.
"In this way we are getting closer to promptly initiating the (peace) process"
with the National Liberation Army. The seizure of the Avianca airlines Fokker 50
by guerrillas of the leftist ELN was widely seen as an attempt to pressure
President Andres Pastrana's government into opening a peace dialogue with the
rebel group.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Survey: US Most Competitive Nation
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   LAUSANNE, Switzerland (AP) -- The United States and Singapore kept their
hold on the top spots as the world's most competitive nations, but European
countries formed a solid phalanx behind them, according to an annual survey
released Wednesday. Japan, a previous leader, languished in 17th place in the
poll of business leaders conducted by the International Institute for Management
Development. The U.S. economy has turned in 108 straight months of growth,
surpassing the record of 106 months between February 1961 and December 1969, the
report noted.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
GM Shifts Strategy With New SUV
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) -- In an overhaul of its midsize Oldsmobile Bravada sport
utility vehicle, General Motors Corp. has come up with something a little
larger, a little less gas-thirsty and a little more powerful. The 2002 model
that goes on sale next year represents a major shift in GM's strategy for future
midsize SUVs. By taking old technology and wringing more performance from it, GM
hopes to cut production costs while delivering more of the key traits that SUV
buyers want. The model is to be shown Wednesday at news media previews for the
New York International Automobile Show.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Japanese Stock Prices Close Higher
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   TOKYO (AP) -- The Nikkei gained 117.10 points to close at 19,086.62. 
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Yankees 6, Rangers 3
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   ARLINGTON, Texas (AP) -- Orlando Hernandez pitched an eight-hitter, and
Derek Jeter and Jorge Posada homered as the New York Yankees kept up their
dominance over the Texas Rangers with a 6-3 victory Tuesday night. The Yankees
won their seventh straight game, matching their longest streak from last season.
The streak began last week with two victories over the Rangers.
</P>
<SUBHEAD>
Stars 4, Oilers 3
</SUBHEAD>
<P>
	   EDMONTON, Alberta (AP) -- Guy Carbonneau scored on a long wrist shot early
in the third period Tuesday night, lifting the Dallas Stars to a 4-3 playoff
victory over the Edmonton Oilers, despite Bill Guerin's hat trick. Dallas took a
3-1 lead in the Western Conference series and can advance to the second round
with a win at home Friday night.
</P>
