<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-19 03:51 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bill to clean up Filthy Five doesn't go far enough, critics say  </HEADLINE>
By ADAM GORLICK, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) -- The state's five dirtiest power plants
would be forced to clean up or shut down by 2006 under a bill
passed by the House early this morning, but some lawmakers say the
proposal does not do enough.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is no victory by any stretch of the imagination,'' said
Rep. Christopher Caruso, D-Bridgeport. ''2006 is unacceptable. It's
disgusting to even consider this.''
</P>
<P>
   Caruso had pushed for legislation that would have required the
so-called Filthy Five to reduce their emissions by 2003. Doctors
and environmental advocates say limiting the number of pollutants
being spit into the air will cut childhood asthma and other
breathing problems in the communities surrounding the plants.
</P>
<P>
   The bill, which passed 137-9 at 2 a.m. today, now heads to the
Senate. It would require fossil fuel power plants in Norwalk,
Bridgeport, New Haven, Middletown and Montville to cut their
production levels of nitrogen and sulfur oxides by 2003. If they
couldn't meet that deadline, the plants would be eligible for
extensions through Dec. 31, 2006.
</P>
<P>
   After a similar bill passed last June on a 68-67 vote in the
House of Representatives, it died in a legislative committee.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents of last year's bill said it could have derailed the
electric deregulation law that required the power plants to be
auctioned by the end of the year. They said passing the legislation
would hurt the value of the plants.
</P>
<P>
   NRG Energy Inc. of Minneapolis paid Northeast Utilities $460
million for the Connecticut Light &AMP; Power plants in Montville,
Norwalk and Middletown. The sale also included a CL&AMP;P plant in
Milford.
</P>
<P>
   United Illuminating, which owned the New Haven and Bridgeport
plants, sold its plants to Wisvest Corp. of Milwaukee for $272
million.
</P>
<P>
   The companies say the are already in compliance with standards
set by the federal Clean Air Act. They said reduce their emissions
any more would be too costly and would force them to close, thereby
cutting off power to areas of the state.
</P>
<P>
   ''They can predict the lights will go out, and we believe
them,'' Caruso said. ''Now they'll close their plants in 2006, and
you will not see the benefit of cleaning them up. We gave the
lobbyists what they wanted.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-04-19-00 0351 </TRAILER>
