<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-19 10:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dow Down 54; Nasdaq Off 37  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks opened moderately lower today as
investors took profits from a powerful two-day run.
</P>
<P>
   In the first hour of trading on Wall Street, the Dow Jones
industrial average was down 54.22 at 10,713.20.
</P>
<P>
   Broader stock indicators were also lower. The Nasdaq composite
index was down 37.26 at 3,756.31, and the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500
index was down 6.48 at 1,435.13.
</P>
<P>
   In the past two sessions, the Nasdaq has risen 472 points and
the Dow average has gained 461, wiping out big chunks of the
crushing losses sustained last week. Financial markets will be
closed Friday for the observance of Good Friday, and with a long
string of volatile sessions behind them, some investors were taking
a pause ahead of the long weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Once again, earnings reports drove the market. Companies are
nearing the peak of the reporting season, and while most companies
have reported very strong profit growth, investors have punished
those that have shown any hint of weakness.
</P>
<P>
   Today, IBM fell 8{ to 106|. The company said late Tuesday that
while earnings beat analysts' expectations, sales slumped 5 percent
in the first quarter, dragged down by a broad decline in products
ranging from desktop computers to mainframes to hard disk drives.
</P>
<P>
   Intel, a bellwether technology stock, fell 6 1/64 to 122 63/64
after reporting first-quarter profits rose 37 percent. Intel
executives also predicted unusually high sales for the
traditionally sluggish second quarter, followed by accelerating
revenue and profit during the last half of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Intel stock had risen sharply in advance of the report,
prompting investors to take profits today. Also, some analysts were
looking for higher revenue growth in the coming quarters.
</P>
<P>
   The market was little affected by a report that the U.S. trade
deficit shot up to a record $29.2 billion in February as Americans'
demand for foreign oil hit an all-time monthly high while sales of
exports dipped.
</P>
<P>
   The Commerce Department said today the deficit widened by 6.5
percent in February. The deficit was bigger than the $28.9 billion
imbalance many analysts were forecasting.
</P>
<P>
   Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a 6-to-5 margin on the
New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 125.88 million
shares, slightly behind Tuesday's early pace.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies fell 0.20 to 485.89
</P>
<P>
   Overseas, Japan's Nikkei stock average rose 0.6 percent. In
afternoon trading, Germany's DAX index was up 0.3 percent,
Britain's FT-SE 100 was up 1.4 percent, and France's CAC-40 was up
0.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
