<BODY>
<HEADLINE> State senator sued for not coming through with state money  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   SYRACUSE, N.Y. (AP) -- Organizers of a first-time music festival
are suing state Sen. Nancy Larraine Hoffmann for failing to deliver
$30,000 in state money they say she promised.
</P>
<P>
   As a result of losing the money, the Great Northeast Blues
Festival had to cut back from three days to two, festival lawyer
Stephen Lance Cimino said today.
</P>
<P>
   According to a Jan. 3 letter to festival director Kyle Shirley,
Hoffmann's office agreed to provide $30,000, Cimino said.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are happy to inform your agency that you have been awarded
$30,000 from this year's New York State Legislative Memorandum
Item. Funds awarded to you are to be used for the 1999 music
festival. These funds have been appropriated to you via Senator
Nancy Larraine Hoffmann's efforts in obtaining moneys in her
district,'' the letter read.
</P>
<P>
   Sarkis Harootunian, Hoffmann's spokesman, said the letter was a
mistake.
</P>
<P>
   A Feb. 4 follow-up letter to Shirley said the festival would not
receive any money because it declined the grant.
</P>
<P>
   Cimino said the festival never declined the money.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Cimino said, Hoffmann offered $6,000 but said the money
had to be spent on certain items. She also demanded that a member
of her staff be placed on the festival board, Cimino said.
</P>
<P>
   Harootunian said Hoffmann offered $10,000 in state and private
money with no strings attached but the festival board declined it.
</P>
<P>
   The dispute began in February when The Smith Advertising Group
Inc. filed a complaint against the festival and Hoffmann seeking
$5,395 it had not been paid for designing the festival logo and
other advertisements.
</P>
<P>
   In late March, the festival filed a cross-complaint against
Hoffmann, saying the senator alone was responsible for any money
owed to the advertising agency. The complaint also asked the court
to issue a judgment ordering Hoffmann to pay the $30,000.
</P>
<P>
   Harootunian said Hoffmann will be represented by a lawyer from
the state attorney general's office because she is being sued as a
state official, not as an individual.
</P>
<P>
   Harootunian said the case is no big deal.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's in City Court, not even in Supreme Court,'' he said. ''In
the legal world, it's a small item.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
