<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton returns questionable soft money; unclear if Giuliani will  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   NEW YORK (AP) -- Hillary Rodham Clinton's U.S. Senate campaign
will return $22,000 from a businesswoman linked to a drug
trafficker but it was unclear if Mayor Rudolph Giuliani's campaign
will return questionable money from another source.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani's Washington-based fund-raising arm received a $100,000
donation from a firm that owns a company identified in 1998
documents as the nation's top dumper of toxic chemicals.
</P>
<P>
   The donation to the Clinton campaign was made by Vivian
Mannerud, whose Airline Brokers Co. runs charter flights between
Cuba and Miami.
</P>
<P>
   Mannerud has been linked by congressional investigators to Jorge
Cabrera, who made a $20,000 contribution to the Democratic National
Committee in 1995 from a bank account in which he kept profits from
drug trafficking.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are returning the money because the contribution was
inappropriate,'' Clinton campaign spokesman Howard Wolfson said
today and urged the Giuliani campaign to do the same with money it
received from the Renco Group.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, Mannerud reportedly promised Cabrera an invitation to a
Miami fund-raising dinner honoring Vice President Al Gore if he
gave the money. The DNC eventually returned the donation.
</P>
<P>
   Three weeks after attending the party, Cabrera was charged with
smuggling 6,000 pounds of cocaine into the United States. He
pleaded guilty last year and was sentenced to 19 years in prison
and fined $1.5 million. Mannerud was never charged with any
wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the mayor's Washington-based Giuliani Victory
Committee, set up to accept soft money donations which legally
bypass federal fund raising restrictions, received a $100,000 check
from the Renco Group.
</P>
<P>
   Among Renco's holdings is the Utah-based Magnesium Corporation
of America, which was cited in a 1998 federal Environmental
Protection Agency report as the nation's top dumper of toxic
chemicals.
</P>
<P>
   Renco is run by Ira Rennert, who has angered neighbors on
eastern Long Island by building the largest house in the Hamptons --
a 100,000-square foot beachfront complex in Sagaponack, complete
with 29 bedrooms, 40 bathrooms, two bowling alleys and a movie
theater.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents have speculated that Rennert, a strong supporter of
Orthodox Jewish causes, plans to convert the structure into a
religious center, but his lawyer has insisted it's just a really
big, single-family house.
</P>
<P>
   The Renco donation, found in campaign reports filed in
Washington, was transferred to the National Republican Senatorial
Committee, where The New York Times said today it would likely be
used to finance direct mailings for Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   Kim Serafin, a spokeswoman for Giuliani's campaign, declined
comment, saying, ''The contribution was given to the NRSC and
you'll have to call them for comment.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the national Senate fund-raising committee,
Stuart Roy, said because it was a corporate contribution it was
immediately transferred from the Giuliani Victory Committee to the
NRSC. He said the committee was ''looking into'' the toxic dumping
report about the Utah company and he couldn't immediately comment.
As for returning the money, Roy said, ''I don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the Giuliani Victory campaign no longer has the Renco
money, Wolfson urged Giuliani to return it. ''As Hillary Clinton
travels the state offering real proposals to clean up the
environment, Rudy Giuliani takes more than $100,000 from one of the
nation's worst polluters,'' Wolfson said. ''Rudy Giuliani should do
the right thing and return this toxic contribution.''
</P>
<P>
   During an appearance Tuesday, Clinton also questioned the
mayor's campaign payments of $1 million to conservative direct-mail
fund-raising guru Richard Viguerie. With Viguerie's help, Giuliani
has out-fundraised Clinton $19 million to $12 million.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani campaign spokeswoman Juleanna Glover Weiss dismissed
criticism of Viguerie by saying, ''when the Clintons get in trouble
or need a scapegoat, they always blame the vast right wing
conspiracy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
