<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-19 12:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Houston Expands Museum of Fine Arts  </HEADLINE>
By MEGAN K. STACK, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON (AP) -- A museum hailed as the most significant step the
Texas art world has taken in decades welcomes visitors with the
broken sarcophagi and mythological torsos of ancient Rome, glowing
white and low in long columns of light.
</P>
<P>
   The sculptures throw shadows, while screened skylights filter
cool daylight and rowdy paintings call to each other across the
silent rooms of the new $83 million expansion building of the
Museum of Fine Arts, Houston.
</P>
<P>
   The newly polished oak, granite and limestone Audrey Jones Beck
Building, designed by Pritzker Prize-winning architect Rafael
Moneo, opened its doors to the public last month.
</P>
<P>
   Its 39 new galleries give the century-old MFAH an exhibition
space that is among the six largest in the country, museum
officials say. Twentieth-century painting and sculpture, along with
Oceanic, African, Asian and pre-Columbian art, will continue to be
displayed directly across the street in the original museum
building.
</P>
<P>
   The Beck Building houses more than 40,000 works of European art,
from the Roman figures in the lobby and to the post-impressionist
paintings upstairs, and American art to 1945.
</P>
<P>
   In a downstairs hall, wings and robes of bronze statues are
frozen in air, the gleaming heads hung low or tossed back, cutting
ancient silhouettes against the limestone walls. The sight was
enough to halt the architect's steps at first sight.
</P>
<P>
   ''I was in reverence for the art,'' the 62-year-old Moneo said.
''I thought, 'I helped build this house for the Roman bronze.'''
</P>
<P>
   Wandering the stream of galleries after the scaffolding came
down, museum director Peter Marzio imagined himself inside a canvas
painted by 17th-century Dutch painter Jan Vermeer. ''It's light
that's there and not there,'' Marzio said. ''You can't describe it;
you can just feel it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Americans are there: Robert Frank, Jackson Pollock, the
sensuous explosions of Georgia O'Keeffe. Panes of Tiffany glass
gleam in a dim gallery.
</P>
<P>
   Standing beside the stained-glass mural, Texas Association of
Museums President Jack Nokes nodded in satisfaction.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is the most significant addition to the state's visual
arts in decades,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And finished not a moment too soon, according to MFAH curators
and trustees. In the older museum, the electrical lighting system
blinked, the roof leaked and the air conditioning was flawed.
</P>
<P>
   Worst of all, though, was the tremendous overcrowding plaguing
the museum: canvases and statues were herded out of sight, in
storage, for lack of space.
</P>
<P>
   ''We've been very strong, very deep,'' Marzio said. ''But now we
can finally show, in public view, that our collections are
extraordinary.''
</P>
<P>
   The two buildings loom across the street from one another in
Houston's oak-shaded Museum District. The new and old structures
are linked by an underground tunnel.
</P>
<P>
   The shape of the original building was born when International
style architect Mies van der Rohe designed a glass addition to a
neoclassical marble base. The two sides of the shell back into one
another; solid, opaque walls collide with the transparency and
sheen of glass.
</P>
<P>
   That museum space, with its crazy-quilt jumble of styles and
materials, has delighted some critics, exasperated others. When
Moneo set about creating the Beck Building, plenty of observers
wondered what kind of relationship would be born between the two
exhibition halls.
</P>
<P>
   The winner of the 1996 Pritzker Prize for architecture, Moneo
was asked to design a new Houston exhibit space in 1992. Moneo
created the Museum of Modern Art in Stockholm, Sweden, the Miro
Museum in Palma de Mallorca, Spain, and the Thyssen-Bornemisza
Collection in Madrid. He now is working on the new addition for the
Prado in Madrid.
</P>
<P>
   His task in Houston was to free the existing museum. ''It was
jammed and crowded and spoiled and wasted,'' Moneo said. ''We had
to liberate it from its duties.''
</P>
<P>
   As far as exteriors go, the design stayed simple. Moneo's
Spanish-style reply to van der Rohe gives a stiff upper lip to the
street. Attention is pulled to the interior, and outside light is
limited.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think it's a bit retrograde in that the galleries are
essentially 19th-century galleries,'' said Rice University
architect professor Fares el-Dahdah. ''But (Moneo) goes for the
counter strategy, and on those terms I like it very much.''
</P>
<P>
   Shortly before the gallery opened, Moneo took in the sketches,
paintings and statues decorating the rooms he designed. Upstairs,
in the midst of the Impressionists, a single window frames the
skyline, throwing pale daylight across the floor. Underfoot, oak
that was stained an ashy hue laces into triangles and diamonds.
</P>
<P>
   A ring of intimate rooms, walls painted in ethereal blues and
greens, tug visitors down a path of European arts. The clean brows
of Botticelli give way to the brilliant brush jabs of pointillism.
</P>
<P>
   One thing was missing at the time, though, Moneo said. People.
</P>
<P>
   ''The hanging paintings are asking for people to be there,''
Moneo said. ''The way they are, they are asking for visitors.''
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: http://www.mfah.org
</P>
</TEXT>
