<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-19 12:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Landmark Play Still Potent  </HEADLINE>
By BENNIE M. CURRIE, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO (AP) -- Like many families in the 1950s, the Youngers had
their sights set on the American Dream.
</P>
<P>
   Walter Lee Younger longed for his own business. His mother,
Lena, wanted a new home and his sister, Beneatha, planned to go to
medical school.
</P>
<P>
   While these goals seem simple enough, this was a time when such
dreams were hard to come by for black families like the Youngers.
Theirs is a fictional story, but it was depicted in stunningly
realistic detail in Lorraine Hansberry's ''A Raisin in the Sun,''
the first play written by a black woman to be produced on Broadway.
</P>
<P>
   Chicago's Goodman Theater opens its version of ''Raisin'' Friday
(April 21) to commemorate the play's 40th anniversary -- which
actually was last year -- and re-introduce the Youngers to
Hansberry's home town, the city in which her history-making saga is
set.
</P>
<P>
   Using personal experiences, including those leading up to a
pivotal Supreme Court decision involving her family, Hansberry
explored social and family themes in a way never before seen on the
Great White Way -- from a black perspective. Her examination of race
relations and a working-class family's strife are as relevant today
as they were when ''Raisin'' made its debut in 1959.
</P>
<P>
   ''Lorraine had insight into both human need and human
frustration,'' says Lloyd Richards, who directed the original
''Raisin'' production. ''The problems of the people in her play are
not just problems of black Americans. They are problems of people.
That is continually valid.''
</P>
<P>
   For Chuck Smith, an artist-in-residence at Columbia College in
Chicago, the Goodman's production is a chance to come full circle
as the director of the play that sparked his interest in the
theater. His first exposure to Hansberry's drama was the 1961 film
adaptation, which featured Sidney Poitier, Ruby Dee, Claudia McNeil
and Diana Sands, all cast members from the original Broadway
production.
</P>
<P>
   Both versions of ''Raisin'' generated widespread acclaim for
Hansberry, who became the youngest American and the first black
winner of the New York Drama Critic's Circle Award in 1959. The
prize catapulted the then 28-year-old writer into the midst of the
civil rights struggle and made her a catalyst for the black theater
movement.
</P>
<P>
   ''This is the play that put us over the hump,'' Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   After ''Raisin'' emerged, ''people started looking at black
theater seriously, saying 'Oh, you can make money at this stuff,'''
Smith says.
</P>
<P>
   Woodie King Jr., founder and producing director of the New
Federal Theater in New York City, agrees.
</P>
<P>
   ''Lorraine ushered in a new era in America,'' King says. ''Her
play was one of the first to ever deal with blacks in a positive
way and show that we have family values and characters of multiple
dimensions, too.''
</P>
<P>
   The central conflict in the play revolves around Lena Younger's
late husband's insurance money and her desire to use it to move the
family out of their cramped tenement apartment and into a house in
a segregated white neighborhood on Chicago's South Side. She also
wants to pay her daughter's medical school tuition.
</P>
<P>
   But Walter Lee sees the money as a chance to open a liquor store
and a way to be more like the wealthy white men for whom he works
as a chauffeur. He wants to make life better for his son and
pregnant wife. In one poignant scene in the play, he tries to
convince his disbelieving mother that his plan will work:
</P>
<P>
   ''I open and close car doors all day long. I drive a man around
in his limousine and I say, 'Yes, sir; no, sir; very good sir.' ...
Sometimes it's like I can see the future stretched out in front of
me -- just plain as day. ... Hanging over there at the edge of my
days. Just waiting for me -- a big looming blank space -- full of
nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   Walter Lee ultimately gets swindled out of the insurance money
and jeopardizes the Youngers' dreams.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, the family finds other means to buy their home. And
in a defining moment, Walter Lee asserts his manhood and rebuffs a
group of whites who try to buy off the Youngers to keep them out of
their neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   Hansberry's dead-on depiction of the Youngers' struggle to
persevere amid family conflict and the backdrop of bigotry is
perhaps the most enduring quality of ''Raisin.'' And the
generational conflict between Walter Lee and Mama Younger,
especially over his materialism, is another element that gives the
play contemporary appeal, says Margaret B. Wilkerson, who's working
on a Hansberry biography.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was the first major play to deal with cultural ideas
without sacrificing the authenticity of that family,'' says
Wilkerson, a black studies professor at the University of
California at Berkeley. ''That's the genius of it. The play made it
OK and safe in a way to talk about those things that even my white
students were able to talk about.''
</P>
<P>
   In writing about the Youngers' brush with bigots, Hansberry drew
upon her own family's real-life experiences: In 1938, the
Hansberrys moved into an all-white neighborhood near the University
of Chicago and endured flying bricks, court orders and other
hostile attempts to oust them.
</P>
<P>
   But Hansberry's father, Carl, fought back. He took his case all
the way to the U.S. Supreme Court. And in the 1940, the prominent
real-estate broker won a narrow ruling that paved the way for a
repeal of restricted covenants -- laws designed to keep blacks from
buying property in white neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   Young Lorraine also accompanied her father while he made the
rounds collecting rent from families who lived in apartments much
like the Youngers' own. ''It seems that even as a child, she was
very observant and had sympathy and empathy for the people she
encountered,'' Wilkerson says.
</P>
<P>
   Hansberry later attended the University of Wisconsin at Madison
before moving to New York, where she married Robert Nemiroff, a
white Jewish songwriter and intellectual. Before pursuing her
career as a playwright, Hansberry edited Freedom, a radical
newspaper published by Paul Robeson. She died of cancer in 1965 at
age 34.
</P>
<P>
   Although she came from a relatively privileged background,
Hansberry attended segregated public schools with children who were
less fortunate and drew upon those experiences for ''Raisin.''
</P>
<P>
   Hansberry's gift for storytelling, coupled with the fact that
racism and discrimination still endure, are why her play continues
to be widely regarded as a timeless classic.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
