<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Photos Show Madness of Genocide  </HEADLINE>
By ANDREW WELSH-HUGGINS, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) -- The woman in the black-and-white
photograph holds a sleeping baby in her right arm. She stares at
the camera, resigned, defeated. It is May 14, 1978.
</P>
<P>
   The picture will be useful to a high-ranking member of Pol Pot's
Khmer Rouge government. It is proof that these two enemies of the
state have been eliminated.
</P>
<P>
   ''Facing Death: Portraits From Cambodia's Killing Fields,'' a
100-photograph exhibit of Khmer Rouge victims, runs through May 28
at the Columbus Museum of Art. From Columbus, the show goes to the
Center for Documentary Studies at Duke University, June 18-Aug. 14;
the Canadian Museum of Contemporary Photography in Ottawa, Sept.
10-Nov.6; the Weisman Museum in Minneapolis, Dec. 3-Jan. 29, 2001;
and the William Benton Museum of Art in Storrs, Conn., dates to be
announced.
</P>
<P>
   The exhibit coincides with the 25th anniversary of Pol Pot's
genocidal reign over Cambodia, which began April 17, 1975. From
1975 to 1979, at least 1.7 million Cambodians -- one in five -- died
by starvation, disease, overwork or execution.
</P>
<P>
   As Pol Pot's brutal regime intensified, it also turned inward,
devouring its own. More than 30,000 members of the Khmer Rouge --
individuals judged traitors to the cause -- were jailed at Tuol
Sleng, a school-turned-prison in Phnom Penh.
</P>
<P>
   Upon arrival at the prison, known as S-21, prisoners were
numbered and photographed. After interrogation and torture, inmates
were executed. Only seven are known to have survived.
</P>
<P>
   The prison was finally liberated as the invading Vietnamese army
entered Phnom Penh in January 1979 and overthrew the Khmer Rouge.
</P>
<P>
   In March 1993, U.S. photojournalists Chris Riley and Doug Niven
discovered 6,000 surviving negatives from the prison's photo
archive in a rusty drawer in a dusty upstairs room in S-21, now a
genocide museum.
</P>
<P>
   The black-and-white portraits are emotionally overwhelming. The
combination of their austere composition and the viewer's knowledge
of the prisoners' fate -- a fate not always known by the inmates --
draws you in and repulses you in the same moment.
</P>
<P>
   Most faces reflect the hopelessness of the victims' situation.
Sad. Worried. Shocked. Stoic. Defiant. Resigned. Angry. Startled.
</P>
<P>
   One young girl stares calmly at the camera, as if posing for a
school picture.
</P>
<P>
   A boy with a cloth tied around his neck and shoulders as if for
a haircut smiles broadly.
</P>
<P>
   Keo Sarun, an adolescent boy -- one of the few victims identified
-- faces the camera almost nonchalantly. His card -- No. 17 -- is
pinned to his skin just below his left collar bone.
</P>
<P>
   One man -- No. 389 -- is handcuffed to a taller prisoner on his
right. It's not until the second or third glance that you realize
the two doomed men are holding hands.
</P>
<P>
   Victims had numbers pinned to them for the photographs, but the
numbering started over every 24 hours, rendering the numbers
meaningless for identification purposes. Only later were victims
photographed with cards designating the date.
</P>
<P>
   One of those is a woman named Kong Saman, her picture taken May
17, 1978.
</P>
<P>
   From the bottom of the photograph, a child's hand floats
upwards, trying to clutch the woman's right sleeve.
</P>
<P>
   Children ended up in the prison because of a Khmer Rouge policy
of sentencing entire families to death to avoid family members
seeking revenge later.
</P>
<P>
   Niven, 37, now a Bangkok-based free-lance photographer, said he
and Riley decided the 6,000 negatives couldn't be treated as
representative, since at least 30,000 people died in S-21. Instead,
they turned to standard photographic criteria such as composition,
the ''critical moment'' and lighting, among other factors, in
selecting the 100 prints.
</P>
<P>
   They also gave special consideration to photos of women and
children, even though they were only a small percentage of the
prison population.
</P>
<P>
   ''What's so great about these pictures for me is it puts a
personal face on genocide and the tragedy of what happened in
Cambodia,'' Niven said. ''It has much more effect on a person than
just reading a story about what happened in Mitrovica today. When
you look at their faces, they're so clear, their expressions are so
close to our own -- it transforms you, puts you in their seat in a
way.''
</P>
<P>
   Some criticized the exhibit from the beginning, saying the
pictures weren't art. Niven said he understood that criticism, and
never intended to put the photos in a museum.
</P>
<P>
   ''But when we saw the negatives years ago and held them up to
the light before we had a chance to print them, we saw the art in
the negative,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The museum mounted the 100 photographs in a double row running
around an upstairs gallery's three walls. The goal was as neutral a
display as possible, said Catherine Evans, the museum's curator of
photography.
</P>
<P>
   ''To present the work in a context that allows for the
individual people to be recognized, since the majority are
unidentified -- no care was taken at the time to identify or
recognize them as individuals,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Even after 25 years, the United Nations and Cambodia are still
divided over how to convene a joint tribunal to try Khmer Rouge
leaders for the mass killings.
</P>
<P>
   These photographs serve as a reminder of what happened, just as
a trial a quarter-century later would still have value to the
Cambodian people, said John Quigley, a professor of international
law at Ohio State University. Quigley testified as an expert
witness on genocide in Pol Pot's 1979 trial. His book on that
trial, ''Genocide in Cambodia,'' is being published this month.
</P>
<P>
   ''All these events are still traumatic enough that it makes
sense to try to bring some sort of end to it, even if it doesn't
resolve it,'' Quigley said. ''Trials don't make things better for
the people of Cambodia, but it is difficult for people to have to
exist in a situation where others have committed these really
horrible atrocities, are still in their midst and are not subjected
to any kind of penalty for it.''
</P>
<P>
   ----
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: Cambodian Genocide Project site:
http://www.yale.edu/cgp/
</P>
<P>
   Columbus Museum of Art: www.columbusart.mus.oh.us
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
