<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-19 12:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sofia Coppola Adds to Family Success  </HEADLINE>
By DAVID GERMAIN, AP Entertainment Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Sofia Coppola concedes her famous film-making
name helped land her directorial debut in theaters. At least a
little.
</P>
<P>
   The daughter of Francis Ford Coppola enters the family business
with ''The Virgin Suicides,'' a darkly comic tale about five doomed
sisters and the teen-age boys who worship them.
</P>
<P>
   Making the film was a four-year odyssey nudged along just a bit
by her Hollywood pedigree, said Coppola, who appeared as an infant
and child in her father's first two ''Godfather'' movies and
co-starred as Al Pacino's daughter in the third.
</P>
<P>
   ''It opens doors, but you don't just get everything handed to
you,'' said the 28-year-old director.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think this movie would have taken maybe twice as many years
to get made if my last name was Smith,'' she said. ''It's hard for
anyone. Everyone has to do whatever they can to get a movie made. I
get phone calls returned probably faster because of my last name.
But you have to prove yourself, and maybe even work harder to prove
yourself because of your name.''
</P>
<P>
   It may have been inevitable that Coppola would try directing.
One of her earliest memories was being on the set of ''Apocalypse
Now'' when she was 4.
</P>
<P>
   ''Everyone in my family is in the film business. I was talking
to my cousin and we were trying to think if there was anyone who
wasn't,'' Coppola said. ''It's just sort of what I know.''
</P>
<P>
   Her film-making family grew larger last year with her marriage
to Spike Jonze, who earned an Oscar nomination for his directing
debut, ''Being John Malkovich.''
</P>
<P>
   Featured at this year's Sundance Film Festival, ''The Virgin
Suicides'' is based on Jeffrey Eugenides' novel about the five
Lisbon sisters, their severely overprotective mother and hapless
father, and the lingering hold the girls have on the hearts of the
men who loved them in their teens.
</P>
<P>
   Decades after the girls inexplicably kill themselves, their
erstwhile beaus are left to ponder the reasons, waking up each day
to a world devoid of the perfection the Lisbon sisters represented
in their youth.
</P>
<P>
   The melancholy longing for lost innocence moved Coppola when she
read the novel several years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's not often you read something that captures that age in a
really true way,'' she said. ''With all the humor and tragedy,
everything you're sort of experiencing in your first crush, and how
it's so much more intense at that age.''
</P>
<P>
   The big question in the book and the movie was what prompted the
suicides. Coppola offers no easy answers, and did not want the
mother to be so villainous or the household so repressive that it
would drive the girls to kill themselves.
</P>
<P>
   ''Because the point of the book was that there isn't one
reason,'' Coppola said. ''There's a million reasons, and there's no
good reason for something like that to happen.
</P>
<P>
   ''The boys as adults have gone over it 20 years later, over and
over, trying to piece it together, and they still can't figure it
out. They've loved these girls and taken them with them. The girls
... are symbolic of the end of the boys' childhood.''
</P>
<P>
   Coppola began writing the script as an exercise, figuring
nothing would come of it. She did not have the rights to the book
and knew another group of filmmakers planned to produce the movie.
</P>
<P>
   ''I just felt protective of it -- you know how you feel something
belongs to you?'' Coppola said. ''I had envisioned every shot as I
wrote the script, and at the end I wanted to go shoot it. I felt
even more attached to it.''
</P>
<P>
   She got her chance when the other film project fell through.
Kathleen Turner, with whom Coppola had appeared in her father's
film ''Peggy Sue Got Married,'' signed on to play the dowdy,
inhibiting mother even before the financing had been lined up.
</P>
<P>
   James Woods co-stars as the father, a nerdy math teacher who
plays with model airplanes, and Coppola cast Kirsten Dunst as Lux,
the vampish sister whose date to the prom -- siblings in tow -- gives
the girls the only taste of normal life they will ever know.
</P>
<P>
   Coppola's father became one of the producers.
</P>
<P>
   Although he visited the set in Toronto and offered valuable
suggestions, ''he knew I knew what I wanted to make, so he was only
encouraging me to make it in my own way,'' Coppola said. ''A lot of
people ask, 'Was he there the whole time?' But I think it's clearly
my movie.''
</P>
<P>
   Set in the 1970s, ''The Virgin Suicides'' captures the era
through artful depictions of manicured suburbs, and especially
through music by such performers as ELO, Styx, Heart and Gilbert
O'Sullivan. Coppola crafts an evocative musical exchange by
telephone between the cloistered girls and their suitors, played
out entirely through such 45-rpm hits as Todd Rundgren's ''Hello
It's Me.''
</P>
<P>
   Coppola now plans to take a break, then look for another writing
and directing project. She hopes moviegoers will accept her work
independent of her long-famous father and newly famous husband.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't compete with Spike. I think he's brilliant,'' Coppola
said. ''And I hope that people will go see my movie just as
someone's first film. I hope once they see it, they can forget
about my family and all that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
