<HEADLINE> Five Questions With Al Jarreau  </HEADLINE>
By NEKESA MUMBI MOODY, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- It doesn't take much prompting to get Al Jarreau
to belt out a tune.
</P>
<P>
   At recent dinner with several journalists and record executives,
Jarreau was asked to sing something -- anything -- so those present
could get an earful of his rich voice.
</P>
<P>
   He quickly stood up and wowed the crowd with ''Puddit,'' one of
the songs on his new album ''Tomorrow Today'' (GRP/Verve Records).
Then, after receiving a rousing ovation, he smiled and asked,
''Anything else?''
</P>
<P>
   The five-time Grammy Award winner and self-proclaimed
''loudmouth'' isn't shy about performing.
</P>
<P>
   ''That's what I do better than anything, standing up in front of
an audience of 10 or 10,000, and reach inside and deliver a song,''
said Jarreau, whose hits include ''Mornin','' ''After All'' and the
theme song to the '80s comedy-drama ''Moonlighting,'' which starred
Cybill Shepherd and Bruce Willis.
</P>
<P>
   Jarreau has delivered his first new songs in six years with
''Tomorrow Today.'' He co-wrote five of the songs on the album, a
typical Jarreau mixture of jazz, pop and adult rhythm and blues.
</P>
<P>
   He worked with Vanessa L. Williams on the inspirational song
''God's Gift to the World.''
</P>
<P>
   The singer/actress thoroughly charmed Jarreau.
</P>
<P>
   ''Vanessa is wonderful, I mean, as simple and sweet as she is
beautiful, '' he said. ''It was a dream come true. ... It's a
wonderful coming together of two people.''
</P>
<P>
   1. Why did it take you so long to record a new album?
</P>
<P>
   Jarreau: The main thing was that I left Warner-Reprise, where
I'd been since the very first album in 1975, 'We Got By.' I needed
to shop around and find some people. ... who understand that there
are things other than mainstream pop to be said musically and that
are valuable, and if we can begin there, and that if you also think
that what I'm doing is valuable stuff, then we have a beginning.
And that took a search. People whose music resembles mine are not
being signed a lot these days.
</P>
<P>
   2. A few years back, you complained about the lack of new young
jazz artists coming up. Do you think that has changed?
</P>
<P>
   Jarreau: I was talking about the fact that for a couple of
generations, young kids don't want to play instruments. No one that
they know doing music is playing instruments or singing a lot. Most
people are talking or rapping, as well as they're not being jazz
singers who are encouraged by what's on around them musically to
jump in and try some jazz. ... (But) there are some great new
voices on the scene who are doing really well, and those are some
real bright spots.
</P>
<P>
   3. You are constantly on tour. How has that affected your family
life?
</P>
<P>
   Jarreau: It's tough. I'm away a lot, and I realize all the time
that there are lost moments with my son, who is now 16, things I've
missed, lost moments with my wife, and things we've missed
together. But something's lost and something's gained in whatever
you do. This is my life, this is what I do, and it's not new to
either of them. My wife (Susan) was there before I did my first
album, and she's still with me now. It's a long time. (But) I spent
some days in the doghouse naturally!
</P>
<P>
   4. How do you think your approach to music has changed over the
years?
</P>
<P>
   Jarreau: I think I'm getting better at writing, I think I'm
getting better at performing, and I think my message is taking on a
more serious tone than it has before. I have always tried to say
things in music as often as I can about the goodness that we are,
and to present a positive and hopeful kind of view of the world and
mankind in this world, because that's how I feel about it.
</P>
<P>
   5: You just turned 60. Do you see yourself slowing down in the
next few years?
</P>
<P>
   Jarreau: That may come, but I don't see it in any real, near,
close-by, imminent time. ... I have a lot more to do in a very
physical way onstage in front of an audience. I've watched great
examples of people who've maintained health and still perform with
a great deal of vitality and artistry. I'd like to be doing it like
Tony Bennett. I'd like to do it like Frank Sinatra did.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Al Jarreau official Web site: http://www.aljarreau.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
