<HEADLINE> Matthew McConaughey Describes Heroes  </HEADLINE>
By SAMANTHA CRITCHELL, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Matthew McConaughey does not toss around the
word ''hero'' lightly.
</P>
<P>
   It was his desire to play ''a leader of men'' that drew him to
the role of Lt. Andrew Tyler in the new film ''U-571,'' which
follows a group of U.S. Navy submarine sailors on a dangerous high
seas mission against the Germans in 1942.
</P>
<P>
   ''The movie is a great hero's story. It's set in World War II --
'the good war' -- the war where there was a universal enemy,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Does McConaughey have any personal heroes?
</P>
<P>
   ''Growing up, 'The Incredible Hulk' was a hero for a very
specific reason. I loved his three-strike rule. Mess with him once,
he'd say, 'No, thank you.' Mess with him twice and he'd say,
'Really, I'd just rather go about my business, please leave me
alone.' Mess with him a third time and he doesn't just get even, he
wins.
</P>
<P>
   ''I like that.''
</P>
<P>
   He also admires singer John Mellencamp for his words and music
about American pride and honor. It was through Mellencamp's songs
that he learned about patriotism, the Texas native said.
</P>
<P>
   His third hero is himself -- in 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   ''Saying that puts a meter on myself. It helps me keep a
long-term goal.''
</P>
<P>
   The 30-year-old actor knows where he would like to be when he's
40: He wants to have definite philanthropic goals, be more involved
in producing films through his company j.k. livin' (short for
''just keep living'') and possibly move into the director's chair.
</P>
<P>
   Looking back, McConaughey said he never would have predicted his
success in films 10 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm the same guy, but the life that I'm living, I couldn't
even have imagined it,'' said a relaxed McConaughey, his feet
propped up on a table at a Manhattan hotel and his Southern drawl
still intact.
</P>
<P>
   McConaughey was a student at the University of Texas when a
chance meeting with a movie producer at a hotel bar led to his
breakthrough role in ''Dazed and Confused.'' McConaughey played a
dope-smoking slacker in the 1993 film, directed by Richard
Linklater.
</P>
<P>
   ''Lady luck shines on you at certain times, and when she does,
you have to play your cards, lay it down, get in the game. But you
have to know when she's shining,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   His other film roles include ''A Time to Kill'' with Sandra
Bullock, ''Contact'' with Jodie Foster and ''EDtv'' with Jenna
Elfman.
</P>
<P>
   McConaughey said working on ''U-571'' was unlike any movie he
had ever worked on.
</P>
<P>
   The film required the actors to be in confined replicas of a
submarine, which kept them cold and wet for several hours at a
time, he said.
</P>
<P>
   No women were cast in principal roles, and after five months of
working with Bill Paxton, Harvey Keitel and Jon Bon Jovi,
McConaughey joked that he now understands why sailors behaved the
way they did when they went on shore leave.
</P>
<P>
   ''Think of what it was like for those guys. Months at sea, you
get to land and -- ah -- the scent of a woman.''
</P>
<P>
   While on location in Rome and Malta, McConaughey stayed as close
to the set as possible instead of commuting to nicer hotels. The
trip back and forth would have cost him at least an hour a day of
sleep, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''I really respect my sleep. I need my eight hours. ... When I'm
working, I go on a pretty good regimen. I don't play on school
nights.''
</P>
<P>
   Next up for McConaughey is the romantic comedy ''The Wedding
Planner'' with Jennifer Lopez. He said the choice was a deliberate
one after ''U-571.''
</P>
<P>
   When he isn't working, McConaughey enjoys playing golf,
traveling, gardening and listening to music. He splits his time
between Los Angeles and Austin, Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   Universal Studios Web site for ''U-571'': http://www.u571.com
</P>
</TEXT>
