<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fido has a chip in his shoulder  </HEADLINE>
By JONATHAN EWING, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- In an effort to make identifying lost pets
easier, animal shelters across New York have begun injecting tiny
microchips under the skin of animals under their care.
</P>
<P>
   The microchips will eventually enable the shelters to reunite
significantly greater numbers of strays with owners.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was once a select crowd that asked for their animals to be
chipped, but over the past few years, more and more people are
requesting the procedure,'' said Dr. Laurie Coger, with the Mohawk
Hudson River Humane Society.
</P>
<P>
   Several companies manufacture the chip, which has grown steadily
in popularity. California-based Avid Inc. registered 608 pets in
1996, but that grew to 4,414 in 1999, according to company
spokesman Mike Tuttle.
</P>
<P>
   ''We've sold about 7 million microchips to shelter operators and
veterinarians,'' Tuttle said. ''Shelters in big cities like
Phoenix, St. Louis and New York City have all been using the chip
for several years.''
</P>
<P>
   Here's how the technology works:
</P>
<P>
   Each chip stores a nine-digit number. The chips are 14
millimeters long -- about the size of a grain of rice -- and weigh
about 0.25 grams.
</P>
<P>
   Workers use a hypodermic needle to inject a chip just under the
skin of a dog or cat -- usually in the animal's shoulder.
</P>
<P>
   When a lost or abandoned animal is brought to the shelter,
workers use hand-held scanners to emit low-frequency radio waves
that can read the number of the chip inside an animal.
</P>
<P>
   Shelters use a computer database to match the number with the
pet's owners.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's relatively cheap, quick and it's a good way to identify
your animal should they become lost and later found,'' said Dr.
Kenneth Rotondo, a veterinarian with the Animal Health Center in
Clifton Park.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors at the Mohawk Hudson River Humane Society in suburban
Albany do the procedure upon request. Soon, however, they expect
the procedure to become standard for all strays brought to the
shelter.
</P>
<P>
   The Society for the Prevention of Cruelty to Animals of Central
New York has already begun the procedure on all of its animals
awaiting adoption. But according to chairman Bob Habberfield, it
may take three or four years before there are enough chip-carrying
animals in Onondaga County for the technology to become widespread.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, many animal owners have had success with a low-tech
identification system -- either dog tags that identify the animals,
or a tattoo.
</P>
<P>
   Records are kept at the shelter that identify the people who
adopt the tattooed animals.
</P>
<P>
   The process usually helps a shelter return the animal to its
rightful owner if they become lost.
</P>
<P>
   ''The tattoo was not a bad idea, but it was difficult to see if
hair had grown over the tattoo, or if you had an aggressive animal
and had to check their underside,'' Dr. Coger said. ''I would have
to say that scanning is infinitely preferable.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
