<HEADLINE> Snowstorm Closes S.D. Highway  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated Press	   Heavy, wet snow piled up on the western Plains today,
closing a
lengthy section of South Dakota's main east-west highway and
closing schools in the Nebraska Panhandle.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Scattered power outages were reported in the two states as tree
limbs broke under the weight of the snow and wind gusted to 50 mph.
</P>
<P>
   The South Dakota Highway Patrol closed a 150-mile stretch of
Interstate 90 between Kadoka and the Wyoming state line. Highways
in Wyoming remained open.
</P>
<P>
   South Dakota Gov. Bill Janklow said people needed to stay off
the roads for their own safety and the safety of others.
</P>
<P>
   ''If something happens to them we're not going out until the
storm ends because it's too dangerous for rescue workers,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   ''We've got jackknifed trucks and people stranded. It's quite a
mess,'' said Highway Patrol Capt. Greg Ingemunson.
</P>
<P>
   The Rapid City airport was closed and parts of the city were
without power as snowdrifts piled up.
</P>
<P>
   Today's snow followed drenching rain.
</P>
<P>
   ''It rained like crazy last night. Now it's snowing like
crazy,'' said Scott Brewer, assistant manager at the Windmill Truck
Stop on I-90 just northwest of Rapid City.
</P>
<P>
   Brewer said his normally 10-minute drive to work took 45 minutes
this morning.
</P>
<P>
   A blizzard warning for lower elevations across the plains of
western South Dakota called for 8 to 16 inches of snow and north
wind blowing at 25 to 40 mph. At higher elevations of the
mountainous Black Hills, up to 2 feet of snow was possible, the
National Weather Service said.
</P>
<P>
   By 8 a.m., 18 inches of snow had already accumulated near Lead
and Nemo in the higher Black Hills, with 8 to 14 inches on the
plains.
</P>
<P>
   At least 6 inches of snow had fallen at Harrison, Neb., and
visibility was reduced to only two blocks in parts of the area.
</P>
<P>
   Travel was not recommended and schools called off classes in
western Nebraska as wind gusted to 45 mph.
</P>
</TEXT>
