<HEADLINE> Wrongly Prisoned Man Thanks DNA  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BATON ROUGE, La. (AP) -- A man who spent 19 years in one of the
nation's toughest prisons until DNA tests exonerated him -- and
implicated his brother -- says he believes in his brother's claims
of innocence.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm not angry, I'm not bitter, but thank God for DNA,'' Clyde
Charles said Tuesday. ''It beat the rap for me. Modern technology
put my feet back on the ground.''
</P>
<P>
   Charles was sent to the Louisiana State Penitentiary at Angola
for a life sentence after a jury convicted him in June 1982 of
raping a 26-year-old nurse in March 1981.
</P>
<P>
   He was freed in December. Marlo Charles, Clyde's brother, was
arrested for the rape earlier this month in Hampton, Va., after the
DNA tests Charles had requested implicated his brother in the
crime.
</P>
<P>
   During a news conference, Charles, 47, said he has no direct
knowledge of his brother's guilt or innocence but believes
officials are again pursuing the wrong man.
</P>
<P>
   ''They did the same thing to me for 19 years,'' he said. ''Marlo
told me he didn't do this, and I stand with my brother. He hasn't
had his day in court. I love my brother.''
</P>
<P>
   He also said he wouldn't have served the prison time for his
brother. ''I wouldn't spend 19 years in jail for anyone, not in a
hard place like Angola,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Clyde Charles filed a federal lawsuit March 29 against
Terrebonne Parish prosecutors who blocked the DNA testing, alleging
civil rights violations and wrongful imprisonment.
</P>
<P>
   He was age 28 when he was sentenced to life in prison for raping
a 26-year-old nurse near a house where the Charles brothers had
been drinking in Houma, about 40 miles southwest of New Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   A flat tire had stranded the woman, and she said a man came up
behind her, punched her in the face and raped her. The nurse
identified Clyde Charles as her attacker. Authorities say the two
brothers look a lot alike.
</P>
<P>
   DNA testing wasn't available at Clyde Charles' trial and he was
convicted. He later spent nine years trying to persuade authorities
to compare his DNA with the preserved semen evidence.
</P>
<P>
   After he was released, authorities focused on Marlo Charles, 44.
The younger brother's DNA was on file in Virginia because of a 1992
conviction.
</P>
<P>
   Marlo Charles is now imprisoned in Houma under a $1 million bond
and faces a possible life sentence if convicted of aggravated rape.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
