<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-19 14:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Report: Mother killed autistic son to end rapes, abuse  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	   SYRACUSE, N.Y. (AP) -- Exasperated and frightened, a woman says
she decided killing her 13-year-old autistic son was the only way
to stop him from raping and abusing her and her two daughters.
</P>
<P>
   ''When I set the fire I knew I had to end the abuse,'' Michelle
Davis of Fleming told police shortly after her arrest last
September for arson and murder.
</P>
<P>
   ''I just wanted him to sleep and never wake up,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Davis told police that her son, Daniel Leubner, had raped her
and beaten her just a few hours before she set the fire that killed
him. The words in her six-page signed statement were written by a
state police investigator.
</P>
<P>
   Parts of Davis' confession appeared Wednesday in The
Post-Standard of Syracuse, which obtained the statement through a
Freedom of Information request.
</P>
<P>
   Davis, 37, pleaded guilty March 14 to first-degree manslaughter
and second-degree arson, both felony charges punishable by up to 25
years in state prison when she is sentenced April 27. She had faced
more serious charges of first-degree murder and second-degree
murder. If convicted of murder, Davis could have been imprisoned
for life.
</P>
<P>
   She was allowed to use an ''affirmative defense,'' which holds
that she suffered from ''extreme emotional disturbance'' the night
of the fire. Her plea came several days after a four-day closed
hearing on whether to suppress her statement as evidence.
</P>
<P>
   According to the statement, Davis was home alone with her son
earlier on the night of the fire. Davis said her 9-year-old
daughter had gone to a friend's house and her 15-year-old daughter
was at a concert. Davis was estranged from her husband.
</P>
<P>
   Leubner had an outburst earlier that night while Davis's younger
daughter was home. He had punched and kicked Davis and thrown
objects.
</P>
<P>
   Around 8:30 p.m., Leubner, naked, approached her on the back
porch. She screamed when he hit and scratched her.
</P>
<P>
   ''But I ended up giving in. I didn't think I stood a chance,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   She said the rape lasted about five minutes. Afterward, Davis
told him to get dressed, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
   ''He showed no remorse for this act,'' the statement said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Sometimes after he beat me he would say he was sorry. He
seemed to be very dangerous to me at this point,'' the confession
read.
</P>
<P>
   Davis said she agonized over the situation, trying to decide
what to do.
</P>
<P>
   ''I thought of my girls and the danger Danny posed to them. I
didn't think he would beat them, but I thought it wasn't beyond him
to sexually abuse them,'' the confession stated.
</P>
<P>
   The statement said Leubner had ''tried things'' with one of
Davis' daughters and had raped Davis before.
</P>
<P>
   ''I thought a long time about what I could and couldn't do. I
thought I needed to stop it and end it. I couldn't stand it
anymore. I couldn't take another beating or another rape by him,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Davis and her younger daughter slept outside on the porch that
night.
</P>
<P>
   ''I thought the fire would make enough carbon monoxide to put
him asleep, but not burn my house down,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   She said she used nail polish remover, wrapping paper and a
candle to start the fire in a closet under the stairs. She planned
to get up after a short time but instead fell asleep, she said.
</P>
<P>
   The statement describes Davis waking up to her daughter's
coughing and smoke in the air.
</P>
<P>
   ''That's when I realized, my God, what have I done?'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   She sent her daughter to get help and tried to rescue her son.
She said she realized she couldn't go upstairs because of the fire.
She climbed on the roof of the back porch to Daniel's bedroom
window, broke the screen and opened the window but the heat and
smoke drove her back.
</P>
<P>
   Davis said she realized she should have called police to report
the rape but didn't want her son taken away and institutionalized.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
