<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NYC: Standing Water Is Nuisance  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- In an effort to combat virus-carrying
mosquitoes, city leaders have declared standing water to be a
public nuisance.
</P>
<P>
   The Board of Health approved a resolution Tuesday giving city
inspectors the power to enter private property without an owner's
consent and remove any containers with standing water.
</P>
<P>
   Homeowners could be billed for the cleanup and fined up to
$2,000.
</P>
<P>
   The resolution is part of an effort to rid New York of breeding
grounds for mosquitoes carrying the West Nile virus. Last year, the
virus killed seven people and sickened scores more in the
metropolitan region.
</P>
<P>
   Before the resolution, city officials had to declare a puddle on
private property a nuisance and allow the person responsible for it
a chance to clear it. The policy was largely ineffective against
the mosquitoes, which can grow to maturity in a week.
</P>
</TEXT>
