<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-19 15:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 4 Sentenced in Viagra Smuggling Case  </HEADLINE>
By CATHERINE WILSON, AP Business Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI (AP) -- Four businessmen were sentenced Wednesday to a
maximum six months in prison for trying to smuggle 70,000 doses of
Viagra in a sting run by an undercover officer posing as a Russian
mobster.
</P>
<P>
   ''This disrupts the legitimate pharmaceutical industry in a
significant way,'' U.S. District Judge K. Michael Moore said.
''Consumers may not know if they're getting what they believe
they're purchasing.''
</P>
<P>
   Outside the courtroom, Assistant U.S. Attorney Karen Rochlin
welcomed the prison terms.
</P>
<P>
   ''The sentence imposed reflects a recognition that this is a
serious offense with potential to harm innocent consumers,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   A Miami Beach detective assigned to an organized crime task
force targeting Russian mobsters became the nightclub owner known
only as Vladimir in the sting.
</P>
<P>
   Viagra became wildly popular internationally after it was
introduced in 1998. A wholesaler, broker, shipper, lawyer and
middleman got together with Vladimir late that year to put together
the $1.6 million deal. All were convicted of conspiracy to
distribute Viagra without a wholesaler's license, though one of
them has such a license.
</P>
<P>
   Rochlin argued during trial that a second license was needed on
the receiving end and everyone in the conspiracy knew Vladimir
intended to sell the Viagra doses illicitly to his bar patrons.
</P>
<P>
   The Viagra sale went beyond a business deal to unlicensed
distribution with Vladimir calling himself crooked and telling all
what he planned to do with the pills, prosecutors said. Wholesaler
Victor Penafiel suggested concealing the Viagra with vitamin labels
when shipping it out of the country.
</P>
<P>
   Arthur Goodman, who helped organize the group, was the only
defendant to speak on his own behalf before sentencing, apologizing
and saying the case ''was due to my lack of better business
sense.''
</P>
<P>
   Lachman Raichandani, the shipper, Matthew Scott, the broker,
Goodman and Penafiel had no reaction to their sentences. They must
report to prison by June 19.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyer, Jon Freeman, agreed under his guilty plea to
cooperate with the prosecution but was not called as a witness. He
was sentenced earlier to probation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
