<HEADLINE> Dow Down 73; Nasdaq Down 47  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks turned modestly lower today as investors
took some profits from a powerful two-day run and sold stocks that
failed to live up to high expectations for corporate earnings.
</P>
<P>
   With an hour remaining in Wall Street's regular session, the Dow
Jones industrial average was down 73.76 at 10,693.66, having given
up a solid midday gain.
</P>
<P>
   Broader stock indicators were moving between positive and
negative territory. The Nasdaq composite index was down 47.38 at
3,746.19, and the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index was off 7.35 at
1,434.26.
</P>
<P>
   In the past two sessions, the Nasdaq has risen 472 points and
the Dow average has gained 461, wiping out big chunks of the
crushing losses sustained last week. Financial markets will be
closed Friday for the observance of Good Friday, and with a long
string of volatile sessions behind them, some investors were taking
a pause ahead of the long weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Once again, earnings reports drove the market. Companies are
nearing the peak of the reporting season, and while most companies
have reported very strong profit growth, investors have punished
those that have shown any hint of weakness.
</P>
<P>
   Today, IBM fell 9 3/16 to 105 15/16. The company said late
Tuesday that while earnings beat analysts' expectations, sales
slumped 5 percent in the first quarter, dragged down by a broad
decline in products ranging from desktop computers to mainframes to
hard disk drives.
</P>
<P>
   Intel, a bellwether technology stock, fell 8 to 121 after
reporting first-quarter profits rose 37 percent. Intel executives
also predicted unusually high sales for the traditionally sluggish
second quarter, followed by accelerating revenue and profit during
the last half of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Intel stock had risen sharply in advance of the report,
prompting investors to take profits today. Also, some analysts were
looking for higher revenue growth in the coming quarters.
</P>
<P>
   Qualcomm rose 6| to 118 13/16 on the Nasdaq. The maker of mobile
phone technology reported earnings of 25 cents a share, beating
analysts' expectations of 24 cents a share. Qualcomm, one of the
top-performing Nasdaq stocks in 1999, had tumbled about 36 percent
in the year to date as investors took profits.
</P>
<P>
   Drug stocks, which are seen as more stable growth stocks than
the volatile technology group, were mostly higher after
Warner-Lambert reported that operating profits surged 35 percent in
the quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Warner-Lambert rose 5} to 113 and Merck rose 2{ to 68}.
</P>
<P>
   Bristol-Myers Squibb broke the trend, tumbling 18\ to 47 after
the company announced that it will withdraw a new drug application
for hypertension drug Vanlev from the Food and Drug Administration.
The drug was expected to be a blockbuster for Bristol-Myers.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said the renewed focus on earnings is the strongest
legacy of last week's rout. Many attributed the cataclysmic selling
to investors who drove stocks up too high on pure momentum, then
panicked on the fear that earnings wouldn't justify their high
prices.
</P>
<P>
   ''Fundamentals do count, and will probably continue to drive at
least the near-term buying momentum within the marketplace,'' said
Brian G. Belski, chief investment strategist at George K. Baum &AMP;
Co. in Kansas City, Mo.
</P>
<P>
   The market was little affected by a report that the U.S. trade
deficit shot up to a record $29.2 billion in February as Americans'
demand for foreign oil hit an all-time monthly high while sales of
exports dipped.
</P>
<P>
   The Commerce Department said today the deficit widened by 6.5
percent in February. The deficit was bigger than the $28.9 billion
imbalance many analysts were forecasting.
</P>
<P>
   Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a 10-to-9 margin on
the New York Stock Exchange, where volume came to 771.97 million
shares, behind Tuesday's pace.
</P>
<P>
   On the Nasdaq, three stocks rose for every two that fell.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies rose 1.56 to 487.65.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   New York Stock Exchange: http://www.nyse.com
</P>
<P>
   Nasdaq Stock Market: http://www.nasdaq.com
</P>
</TEXT>
