<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-19 15:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Buchanan Launches Texas Ballot Bid  </HEADLINE>
By DAVID KOENIG, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS (AP) -- Reform Party presidential candidate Pat Buchanan
says it plainly: carrying Texas ''is going to be no easy
assignment.'' In fact, just getting on the ballot for November is a
tough task in the home state of George W. Bush and Ross Perot.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan needs 56,000 valid signatures by May 8.
</P>
<P>
   And he's getting no help from Perot, the billionaire founder of
the Reform Party, silent so far.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan came to the state this week to rally his troops in an
effort to win a spot on the Texas ballot. He was speaking again
Wednesday night in Houston.
</P>
<P>
   But Bush won re-election as governor with nearly 70 percent of
the vote two years ago. And Most Texas political observers think
even Vice President Al Gore, the likely Democratic nominee, will
privately concede the state to Bush without a big fight.
</P>
<P>
   ''I can't see any scenario where Buchanan can be competitive.
Bush is solid in this state,'' said Bill Miller, an Austin lobbyist
and former campaign consultant to both Republicans and Democrats.
He said Buchanan, a former Republican who polls in the single
digits, is probably in Texas hoping for an in-your-face boost by
qualifying in Bush's backyard.
</P>
<P>
   By all accounts, Perot could help. But the Dallas billionaire
has kept a low profile in recent weeks. On the rare occasions when
he has appeared in public, he has declined to answer questions
about the party or his own political plans.
</P>
<P>
   ''If Perot pushed for Buchanan it would help him get the
signatures,'' said Bruce Buchanan, a University of Texas political
scientist and no relation to the presidential candidate. But he
noted that in 1994 Perot endorsed Democratic incumbent Ann Richards
for governor over Bush, and she lost.
</P>
<P>
   In the past week, some Reform Party officials have started a
draft-Perot petition drive. However, Russell Verney, a Perot
employee and former party chairman, said, ''It would take a miracle
for Ross Perot to run this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan's bid also comes against a backdrop of ferocious
infighting within the party that he hopes to lead. Former party
officials say hundreds of activists have quit in the aftermath of a
nasty fight over control of the party. Some of those who remain
complain that Buchanan has hijacked the party.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Buchanan is pressing ahead in Texas with volunteers
augmenting 10 of his paid workers who are circulating petitions.
They say they've already gathered 30,000 signatures -- state
political veterans say Buchanan will need 100,000 to withstand
challenges by state election officials.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan told a rally of about 100 volunteers Tuesday night in
Irving that he's running to give voters a choice between Bush and
Democrat Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   ''They're Xerox copies of one another,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Buchanan aimed most of his fire at the Texas governor,
criticizing Bush's recent meeting with gay activists and accusing
him of wavering in his anti-abortion stance.
</P>
<P>
   Pete Geren, a former Democratic congressman from Fort Worth,
said Buchanan isn't a threat to Bush in Texas ''but he's carved out
an interesting niche for himself. He'll appeal to some conservative
Republicans and also some protectionist Democrats.''
</P>
<P>
   Geren predicted, however, that Buchanan's anti-immigration
positions will not play well in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Bush simply dismissed Buchanan, saying Texas
voters will overwhelmingly support the governor.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
