<HEADLINE> FBI holds anti-terrorist exercise in Philadelphia  </HEADLINE>
By RON TODT, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- Crouching behind their shields and a sleek
black vehicle, the black-helmeted FBI tactical team crept toward
the community center where a terrorist was holding a nameless
public official.
</P>
<P>
   Trailing wires from their command post, they tossed a phone
within reach of the open doorway before retreating as carefully as
they came. After a few minutes, the terrorist himself emerged, head
covered by a coat, with a gun next to his female captive.
</P>
<P>
   It was just a drill, but nobody smiled and nobody yelled
''cut.'' The fictional hostage drama being played out over three
days at the old Philadelphia naval base is aimed at making sure any
real event this summer ends as happily.
</P>
<P>
   Several hundred FBI agents and support personnel from
Pennsylvania, New York and New Jersey are taking part in ''Stolen
Liberty,'' a major exercise to prepare for terrorism or other
activities during the Republican National Convention this summer.
</P>
<P>
   ''We try to test all of our equpment, we put our negotiators to
work, we put our tactical teams to work ... so that we can iron out
any problems with equipment or communications before a crisis,''
said Linda Vizi, FBI spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   The annual exercise is usually held in a remote central
Pennsylvania location such as Fort Indiantown Gap, but was moved to
Philadelphia because of the upcoming convention and other events.
</P>
<P>
   For the exercise, the negotiation and tactical posts were set up
in the weed-strewn parking lot of an old airplane hangar. The
''community'' around the center is only vacant naval housing with
fallen siding and empty carports.
</P>
<P>
   The command center in a Holiday Inn banquet room a short drive
away is more realistic, with computers, an aerial photo, and charts
showing a timeline of events and the people involved. Well, almost
realistic. ''We wouldn't have the crystal chandaliers,'' Vizi said.
</P>
<P>
   But on each green tablecloth was a computer linked up to allow
quick sharing of information among all center personnel, who
include a legal team to quickly process search warrants and press
personnel to brief news organizations.
</P>
<P>
   ''We've been planning for the Republican National Convention for
a year and a half,'' said Robert S. Conforti, agent-in-charge of
the Philadelphia office. ''As we get closer the meetings intensify.
We've had people go to Washington, D.C., and Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're planning for the worst-case scenario hoping that we get
the best one.''
</P>
<P>
   For the convention, strategy will be devised by a 16-member
executive committee made up of local and state police and federal
agencies such as the FBI, U.S. Secret Service, and the bureau of
Alcohol Tobacco and Firearms, Conforti said.
</P>
<P>
   Philadelphia police, who will handle street protests, also sent
personnel to Washington. While they praised the handling of
demonstrations there during the meetings of the International
Monetary Fund and World Bank, protest leaders have criticized the
use of pepper spray and police batons to disperse crowds.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities believe the GOP Convention, already expected to
attract 45,000 people from July 31 to Aug. 3, may attract the same
kind of noisy protests seen during the recent world economic
meetings.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have people on the Internet saying they're coming, and
they're going to try to disrupt the Republican National Convention,
so if I had to guess, I would say we're going see some of what you
saw in Washington, D.C., and Seattle,'' Conforti said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
