<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Utah Man Charged With Rape, Bigamy  </HEADLINE>
By C.G. WALLACE, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   SALT LAKE CITY (AP) -- A polygamist who has defended his
lifestyle on national television, arguing that it is his God-given
right, has been charged with child rape, bigamy and failing to pay
child support.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas Arthur Green, 51, who lives in Utah's West Desert with
five wives and an estimated 25 children, was charged Monday after
an investigation that Juab County Attorney David Leavitt said
lasted a year.
</P>
<P>
   ''I only became aware of Mr. Green myself after he appeared on
national television,'' the prosecutor said.
</P>
<P>
   Green's wives -- who include two sets of sisters -- have joined
him on television, including an appearance on NBC's ''Dateline.''
They portrayed themselves as one big happy family, with the women
saying they choose a life of polygamy over any other.
</P>
<P>
   But Leavitt says Green married some of his past or current wives
when they were just 14 and he was in his 30s or 40s.
</P>
<P>
   The child rape charge stems from an alleged relationship he had
with a 13-year-old girl, with whom he had a child, the prosecutor
said.
</P>
<P>
   Green's attorney, John Bucher, said Green has been expecting to
face charges for quite a while. But Bucher was alarmed by the child
rape charge and wondered why other polygamists were not targeted,
suggesting Green was singled out because of his family's public
profile.
</P>
<P>
   The child rape charge carries a maximum sentence of life in
prison. Bigamy and nonsupport could each bring maximum terms of
five years.
</P>
<P>
   Bucher said he advised his client not to speak with the media
for fear he might say too much.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's very much too open. He's too eager to talk, and he's
gotten in trouble for it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Green considers himself a fundamentalist Mormon practicing a
commandment given by God to church founder Joseph Smith.
</P>
<P>
   The Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints officially
abandoned the practice of polygamy in 1890 as a condition of Utah
being recognized as a state.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Morrison, an attorney for Green's five ''spiritual'' wives
and one former wife, said none of the women will testify against
Green.
</P>
<P>
   ''They would rather go to prison than see their husband go to
prison,'' he said. ''I think it's a matter of destroying their
family through auspices of the state, and they won't cooperate in
the least.''
</P>
<P>
   Some former plural wives say the case is a major step toward
abolishing polygamy, which is thought to be practiced by some
30,000 people in the West.
</P>
<P>
   ''The Berlin Wall of polygamy is tumbling down and the Tom Green
case is just the beginning,'' said Vicky Prunty, director of the
anti-polygamy group Tapestry of Polygamy.
</P>
<P>
   Green filed a defamation lawsuit against the group last year
after members criticized him on television. That lawsuit is making
its way though the courts.
</P>
<P>
   Green's television appearances have included a face-off on the
''Jerry Springer Show'' with Tapestry member Rowenna Erickson.
</P>
<P>
   ''He has always been so open about it. I think he was wanting to
be caught,'' Erickson said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
