<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-19 16:26 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Court Examining Miranda Warning  </HEADLINE>
By RICHARD CARELLI, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Supreme Court seemed split Wednesday as it
considered whether police still must warn criminal suspects of
their ''right to remain silent'' when questioned or else risk
getting confessions excluded as evidence.
</P>
<P>
   Two key justices, Sandra Day O'Connor and Anthony M. Kennedy,
wrestled with whether such warnings, required since the court's
landmark 1966 ruling in Miranda vs. Arizona, are constitutionally
mandated.
</P>
<P>
   Their votes appeared to be critical to the court's eventual
decision, expected in late June.
</P>
<P>
   Chief Justice William H. Rehnquist and Justice Antonin Scalia
seemed willing to jettison the Miranda warnings. Justice Clarence
Thomas, who remained silent during the hour-long argument session,
often sides with them in criminal justice cases.
</P>
<P>
   But Justices Stephen G. Breyer, David H. Souter, Ruth Bader
Ginsburg and John Paul Stevens vigorously defended the 34-year-old
ruling and the warnings that Breyer said ''2 billion people
throughout the world probably know.''
</P>
<P>
   A federal appeals court last year threw the warnings' future
into doubt, ruling that Congress effectively overturned the Miranda
decision by enacting a long-ignored 1968 law known as Section 3501.
</P>
<P>
   Solicitor General Seth Waxman, the Clinton administration's
top-ranking courtroom lawyer, told the justices that Section 3501
must be struck down because ''the case has not been made to
overrule Miranda.''
</P>
<P>
   But Paul Cassell, a University of Utah law professor, argued
that police procedures need not necessarily change if the court
were to rule that Miranda's guidelines have been superseded.
''Congress has now stepped in ... (with) a more nuanced approach,''
he said. ''You don't have to satisfy every jot and jiggle in
Miranda.''
</P>
<P>
   But he came under repeated questioning from Ginsburg, who said
she viewed the Miranda ruling as an attempt to protect ''a discrete
right -- a procedural right if you will, but a constitutional
right.''
</P>
<P>
   Far more liberal in 1966 than it is today, the nation's highest
court sought to remedy ''inherently coercive'' police
interrogations by creating a bright-line rule. Courts previously
had used a ''totality-of-the-circumstances'' test to determine
whether a confession or incriminating statement had been given to
police voluntarily.
</P>
<P>
   Waxman said the Supreme Court's efforts to apply that standard
had been a ''profoundly unhappy experience.''
</P>
<P>
   The 1968 law was invoked by the 4th U.S. Circuit Court of
Appeals last year in the case of a Maryland man accused of robbing
banks in Maryland and Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Dickerson of Takoma Park, Md., made several
incriminating statements to FBI agents after being arrested and
charged with seven bank robberies. He says the agents did not give
him a proper Miranda warning.
</P>
<P>
   Neither he nor the federal prosecutors who had opposed his
appeal to the 4th Circuit court focused on the 1968 law. But
Cassell, representing the conservative Washington Legal Foundation
as a friend of the court, successfully resuscitated Section 3501
and persuaded the appeals court to rule against Dickerson, who then
appealed that ruling to the Supreme Court.
</P>
<P>
   As Dickerson looked on, his lawyer, James Hundley of Fairfax,
Va., argued Wednesday that Congress unlawfully ''attempted to roll
the clock back'' and do away with the ''more clear-cut'' test
adopted in Miranda.
</P>
<P>
   Rehnquist quickly challenged Hundley, however, about how
clear-cut the Miranda ruling has proved, referring to the court's
some 50 Miranda-related decisions over the past three decades. ''To
say it is easily applied is just a myth,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Scalia drew a distinction between a police officer who ''used a
rubber hose'' to extract a confession and one who fails to remind a
suspect of his rights before questioning him. The first officer
clearly could be sued for violating someone's rights, Scalia said,
but ''I would be very surprised'' if the second officer could be.
</P>
<P>
   The case has drawn an enormous amount of attention, and people
seeking a place among the some 200 courtroom seats available to the
public began lining up outside the court building 7 p.m. Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Among the friends-of-the-court arguing for the Miranda
decision's continued vitality were the American Civil Liberties
Union, National Association of Criminal Defense Lawyers and House
Democratic Leadership.
</P>
<P>
   Among those urging the justices to uphold the appeals court's
ruling were 17 states: Alabama, Alaska, Colorado, Delaware,
Florida, Hawaii, Idaho, Kansas, Mississippi, Nebraska, Nevada,
Pennsylvania, South Carolina, South Dakota, Tennessee, Utah and
Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   The case is Dickerson vs. U.S., 99-5525.
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: For the appeals court ruling:
http://www.uscourts.gov/links.html and click on 4th Circuit.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-19-00 1626 </TRAILER>
