<DOCNO> APW20000419.0122 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-19 16:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russians Regrouping in Chechnya  </HEADLINE>
By YURI BAGROV, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NAZRAN, Russia (AP) -- Russia is building up troops in Chechnya's
south and launching operations to root out thousands of fighters in
the mountains, officials said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The defense minister insisted the troops coming into the
mountains were being redeployed from elsewhere in Chechnya and that
no reinforcements were being sent in.
</P>
<P>
   Russia has maintained repeatedly that the Chechen rebels are on
the verge of defeat and that no more major military operations
would be needed. But liquidating the rebels in the mountains is a
difficult task because the Chechens are skilled guerrillas who use
the rugged terrain to their advantage.
</P>
<P>
   Although the fierce fighting of the winter months has abated,
small groups of rebels still launch attacks and ambushes.
</P>
<P>
   The federal forces on Wednesday started a ''mopping-up''
operation in one of the roughest areas of the mountains, the Vedeno
Gorge, said Sergei Yastrzhembsky, the Kremlin's top spokesman on
Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   The operation began with Russian artillery pounding suspected
rebel targets in four villages, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The military command also reported clashes near Tsentoroi in the
eastern mountains and Alkhazurovo in central Chechnya, and said
rebels ambushed a Russian post at Dyshne-Vedeno in the southeast.
</P>
<P>
   Also Wednesday, a senior Interior Ministry official said special
forces units will be flown into the Nozhai-Yurt and Vedeno
districts, where up to 1,000 rebels are holed up, the ITAR-Tass
news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
   Other commando units would be sent to Chechnya's eastern border
with the Russian republic of Dagestan, and to the Chechen capital
Grozny, where the Russian military says some 400 rebel fighters
still operate, the official said.
</P>
<P>
   Defense Minister Igor Sergeyev insisted federal forces were just
regrouping for the war's changing demands.
</P>
<P>
   ''There is no reinforcement. A planned regrouping is under
way,'' Sergeyev said in Moscow, Russian news agencies reported.
</P>
<P>
   Russian troops seized about two-thirds of Chechnya in steady
advances across the northern flatlands after moving into the
republic in September. But the offensive has stalled in the
southern mountains, the last major area under rebel control.
</P>
<P>
   Sergeyev denied Russian news reports that as many as 3,000
paratroopers, motorized infantry troops and special police agents
poured into the Shatoi region in the southern mountains on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The region saw intense fighting this winter and scattered
clashes have continued in recent weeks. The reports on new troop
movements said the forces were being sent in to search for rebels
among civilian populations already under Russian control.
</P>
<P>
   While both sides appear to be using the recent relative lull in
fighting to regroup, Moscow also has indicated it is exploring
political solutions.
</P>
<P>
   A top commander, Gen. Viktor Kazanstev, told ITAR-Tass on
Wednesday that ''eliminating surviving small gangs does not depend
exclusively on the military.''
</P>
<P>
   Yastrzhembsky said Tuesday that Moscow is continuing to talk
with Chechen President Aslan Maskhadov through intermediaries.
</P>
<P>
   Russia sent ground troops into Chechnya after weeks of
airstrikes, following an invasion of neighboring Dagestan by
Chechnya-based rebels. The rebels are also blamed for the apartment
bombings in Russia in September that killed about 300 people.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
