<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-19 16:32 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> N. Korea Accepts South's Proposal  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEOUL, South Korea (AP) -- North Korean and South Korean leaders
will meet this weekend to prepare for the first summit between
their leaders, officials from the south said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The officials said the north has accepted a South Korean
proposal for the preparation meeting. The meeting will set up a a
summit of their leaders in the North Korean capital of Pyongyang on
June 12-14 -- a dramatic breakthrough in a half-century of division.
The summit agreement was announced last week.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, South Korea proposed a working meeting with North
Korea in the border village of Panmunjom for Saturday, co-chaired
by vice Cabinet ministers and attended by five assistants from each
side. On Wednesday, North Korea sent a telephone message accepting
the proposal, Seoul's Unification Ministry said.
</P>
<P>
   North Korean acceptance of the border village as a meeting site
was surprising. It so far has shunned official contacts with South
Korea on the border, where it signed an armistice with U.S.-led
U.N. forces at the close of the Korean War in 1953.
</P>
<P>
   The Koreas were divided in 1945.
</P>
<P>
   South Korea hopes to use the summit to discuss economic
cooperation and other measures to ease tension, including the
reunion of millions of separated Korean family members. South
Korean officials believe North Korea was driven to agree to the
summit because of its severe food and energy shortages.
</P>
<P>
   North Korea warned Wednesday that the latest U.S. sanctions
imposed on it would hurt efforts to improve relations between the
Cold War enemies.
</P>
<P>
   As part of deals to normalize relations with North Korea, in
September the United States lifted some sanctions in force since
the 1950-53 Korean War. But last week, the United States imposed
new sanctions on North Korea and Iran for ''knowingly engaging in
the export of military technology.''
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials did not say where the North Korean technology was
exported to, but the hard-line communist government is believed to
have had dealings in such materials with Syria.
</P>
<P>
   North Korea denounced the move as a ''grave challenge'' to the
normalization process.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
