<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US GI's Remains Found in Germany  </HEADLINE>
By GEORGE BOEHMER, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   FRANKFURT, Germany (AP) -- The believed remains of a U.S. soldier
missing in World War II have been found in rural West Germany -- the
fourth time the remains of a GI have turned up in the area in three
years, the Army said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The remains were discovered in an area of fields and dense
forests near the Belgian border that saw heavy fighting between
American troops and Hitler's army in late 1944, Army officials
said.
</P>
<P>
   Military identification tags found at the site were confirmed as
belonging to a soldier listed as missing since Dec. 13, 1944, from
the 311th Infantry Regiment, 78th Infantry Division of the U.S.
Army's 5th Corps, Army spokesman Sgt. Greg Jones said.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, the unit was fighting in the Huertgen Forest, where
the Germans had set up a defensive line. Both sides suffered heavy
casualties.
</P>
<P>
   It was the fourth time since 1997 that remains of a U.S. soldier
were found in the area, said David Roath, head of the Army mortuary
at Landstuhl, Germany. The area is about 15 miles south of the city
of Aachen.
</P>
<P>
   German authorities were to turn over the remains in a ceremony
at Huertgen on Thursday. They will be sent to an Army
identification laboratory in Hawaii for final identification so
next of kin can be notified, Roath said. He said the name of the
soldier would be withheld until the process has been completed.
</P>
<P>
   Some 40,200 Americans are still listed as missing during World
War II in Europe and the Mediterranean.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
