<HEADLINE> NY City Opera Presents 1745 Comedy  </HEADLINE>
V0182-----
r e *1404AP-Opera-Platee     04-19 0475
*1404 AP-Opera-Platee,0474   
NY City Opera Presents 1745 Comedy   
An AP Entertainment Review, 
By MARY CAMPBELL
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- If an opera company intends today to perform
Rameau's really silly 1745 dance comedy-opera ''Platee,'' it's
essential to have a clever, inventive choreographer like Mark
Morris with a strong sense of fun and camp.
</P>
<P>
   Morris, as director and choreographer, and the Mark Morris Dance
Group -- and some of Rameau's best music -- made ''Platee'' a
splendid entertainment by the New York City Opera on Tuesday night.
The production marks the opera's first staging in this city.
</P>
<P>
   The second half seemed long, but laughter kept erupting as the
dancers pranced and cavorted. During the orchestral interludes
between scenes, the dancers capered about as two swamp frogs, three
clumsy graces, four men in bikinis and four women with strippers'
fans. Not everything came from Morris' imagination; two men in
diapers and two wise old men danced to a section in the score
called ''The Dance of the Babies and the Scholars.''
</P>
<P>
   Tenor Jean-Paul Fouchecourt was exceptional as Platee. In 1745,
it was unusual for a female opera part to be written for a man. But
Platee is an ugly, vain marsh nymph who is used for a joke by the
gods. Rameau probably had a man sing her to lessen audience
sympathy for his title character. Fouchecourt was covered in a
green skin with big hands, long fingers, flippers for feet and a
fat orange front.
</P>
<P>
   The prologue is set in a modern bar where an idea is proposed
for the god Jupiter to cure his wife Juno's jealousy. He'll court
Platee, and then Juno will discover how ugly Platee is and realize
it was a mock courtship and Jupiter and Juno will reconcile. It
works.
</P>
<P>
   Amy Burton sang Folly. Dressed as a 1920s blond movie vamp, she
sang Rameau's parodies of Italian coloratura arias. Her voice
soared sweetly in what are coloratura arias, whether they're meant
as parody or not.
</P>
<P>
   Other notable voices were tenor Matthew Chellis, as Mercury,
messenger of the gods, who usually arrived and departed in a basket
from above, and bass-baritone Bernard Deletre as both Momus, god of
ridicule, and Jupiter.
</P>
<P>
   Daniel Beckwith conducted, and the singing chorus was in the New
York State Theater pit with the orchestra.
</P>
<P>
   ''Platee'' was performed for the first time in 1745 during
wedding festivities in Versailles, France, for King Louis XV's son
Prince Louis. Four years later it was performed by the Paris Opera.
But after 1773 it went out of style.
</P>
<P>
   A revival of the opera began in 1901 in Munich and 1917 in Monte
Carlo. Now, with a boom in Baroque opera revivals, this production
has been seen in London and has been traveling. The New York City
Opera is presenting six performances, the last one on Saturday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-19-00 1637 </TRAILER>
