<HEADLINE> Networks Face Columbine Family Pleas  </HEADLINE>
By DAVID BAUDER, AP Television Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Television networks are wrestling with how to
mark Thursday's first anniversary of the Columbine school massacre
while responding to pleas from some families of victims to show
restraint.
</P>
<P>
   ABC, CBS and NBC are all expected to devote much of their
morning news shows to Columbine High School, where two teen gunmen
killed 12 students and a teacher before killing themselves on April
20, 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Students and school officials in Littleton, Colo., have asked
that cameras and all outsiders be kept away from Columbine, where a
private memorial service will be held. Public remembrances are
planned for the adjacent Clement Park and Denver.
</P>
<P>
   Some parents of shooting victims have also asked the news media
to refrain from showing pictures of the attack.
</P>
<P>
   ''When you're sitting in your living room and watching
television, and I know this from personal experience, and you see
flashes of Columbine, and for me, people running past my lifeless
son lying on the sidewalk, it can be very traumatizing,'' said Sue
Petrone, whose son, Daniel Rohrbaugh, died that day.
</P>
<P>
   CNN and ABC's ''Good Morning America'' will have reporters in
Littleton, but both decided not to send anchors.
</P>
<P>
   ''There is a lot of sensitivity and a lot of care and concern
for these families from this show,'' said Shelley Ross, executive
producer of ''Good Morning America.''
</P>
<P>
   School officials in Littleton persuaded a homeowner near
Columbine not to allow ''Good Morning America'' to set up a camera
on his property. Ross said she didn't know about the request.
</P>
<P>
   Some family members affected by the tragedy have simply decided
to leave town rather than mark the anniversary, ABC's Ross said.
</P>
<P>
   NBC's ''Today'' show debated whether to go and decided to send
anchor Katie Couric, said Jeff Zucker, executive producer.
</P>
<P>
   ''We decided that we could be both respectful of the day and the
people and still be there,'' Zucker said.
</P>
<P>
   CBS won't speak to anyone who doesn't want to be on camera, but
it can't ignore the story, said Marcy McGinnis, the network's vice
president of news coverage. Jane Clayson of ''The Early Show'' will
be in Littleton.
</P>
<P>
   Networks were also internally debating how much file footage of
the massacre to show. Fox News Channel, for example, will show
terrified children fleeing the school but won't air footage that
contains dead bodies lying on the ground, said Alicia Acuna, a
correspondent based in Denver.
</P>
<P>
   CNN is ''not trying to wallow in what happened a year ago'' and
decided against a prime-time special on the anniversary, said Sid
Bedingfield, executive producer.
</P>
<P>
   But it is airing an interview with shooting survivor Patrick
Ireland which will include the wrenching footage of his bloody
escape through a school window.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-19-00 1640 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
