<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-19 16:45 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe Squatters Vow Violence End  </HEADLINE>
By ANGUS SHAW, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARARE, Zimbabwe (AP) -- After a week of heightened violence on
white-owned farms across Zimbabwe, a leader of squatters occupying
the farms pledged Wednesday to end hostilities -- but not to leave
the land.
</P>
<P>
   Squatters would remain in place while their leaders peaceably
work toward a negotiated end to the 2-month-old occupations, said
Chenjerai Hunzvi, the militant leader of a group of veterans of
Zimbabwe's independence war who initially led the farm invasions.
</P>
<P>
   ''We have agreed hostilities should cease and we should work
toward a solution,'' Hunzvi said.
</P>
<P>
   The occupations began in February, days after the defeat of a
proposed constitution that would have allowed the government to
seize white-owned farms without paying compensation. However, it
was unclear whether the war veterans still controlled the
squatters, who have become increasingly violent in recent days.
</P>
<P>
   President Robert Mugabe mediated talks Wednesday between Hunzvi
and leaders of the Commercial Farmers Union, which represents most
of the country's 4,000 white farmers.
</P>
<P>
   Subsequent talks would deal with that issue of squatters
withdrawing from the farms, Mugabe said.
</P>
<P>
   Farm leaders were optimistic.
</P>
<P>
   ''I believe in the interest of national unity we will get to a
result,'' said Tim Henwood, head of the farmers' union. ''We will
meet again. We are both determined to reach a solution.''
</P>
<P>
   The occupations have become increasingly violent in the past
week, with two white farmers and two black members of the
opposition Movement for Democratic Change killed. At least six
white farmers were badly beaten.
</P>
<P>
   Fearing a further escalation in violence, farm union officials
advised white farmers to evacuate their families from the western
province of Matabeleland, where farmer Martin Olds was killed
Tuesday, and the neighboring province of Midlands, David Hasluck,
director of the union, said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Eighty more families remained evacuated from the nearby Macheke
area.
</P>
<P>
   After the meeting, Mugabe said those farmers should be able to
return in peace.
</P>
<P>
   ''If the war vets can pledge not to interfere with them, I don't
see any reason why they should not go back,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Mugabe said he considered it unnecessary to deploy extra police
to the area because the squatters had promised to refrain from
violence.
</P>
<P>
   Mugabe has called the occupations a legitimate protest against
the ownership of one-third of the country's productive farmland by
the white farmers. He also said that Britain, the former colonial
ruler, reneged on an agreement to help pay for land reform in
Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
   Britain, which pledged millions of dollars for land reform at
independence, delivered nearly 90 percent of that money before
freezing the fund in 1990 when it said Zimbabwe violated the
agreement by forcing unwilling farmers to sell to the state.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier Wednesday, Hunzvi was found in contempt for disobeying a
High Court order to tell his followers to leave the farms.
</P>
<P>
   Judge David Bartlett ordered Hunzvi to ''actively strive to
assist in the peaceful vacation by veterans of occupied farms.''
Hunzvi, whose group claims to have led the occupations to complete
the ''unfinished business'' of the independence war, was to return
to court May 5 for sentencing.
</P>
<P>
   In London, British Prime Minister Tony Blair said the killings
of the farmers were barbaric but signaled that Britain feared tough
action against Mugabe could backfire.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is a difficult balance to strike,'' Blair said. ''It is
best we are guided by those with most to lose, not those who are
commenting from a safe distance.''
</P>
<P>
   In meetings with British officials last week, opposition leader
Morgan Tsvangirai said that punishing Mugabe by, for example,
seeking to get Zimbabwe suspended from the Commonwealth could help
Zimbabwe's leader portray himself as a martyr.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, White House spokesman Joe Lockhart said the
United States deplores ''the violence and the climate of
lawlessness'' that led to the four deaths.
</P>
<P>
   ''We think the Zimbabwe leadership needs to accept
responsibility to uphold the law and implement the court orders.
That's a view that we have communicated to them. We expect that
they will do that,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Late Tuesday, two white women were raped on a farm south of
Harare, police said Wednesday. Police had no information whether
the rapes were politically motivated, but the husband of one of the
women raped said the attackers demanded to know his family's
political affiliation.
</P>
<P>
   In a television interview on Tuesday, Zimbabwe's 20th
anniversary of independence from white rule, Mugabe called white
farmers enemies of the country.
</P>
<P>
   In London, Tsvangirai said Mugabe was trying to stoke racial
tension to help his party ahead of upcoming parliamentary
elections.
</P>
<P>
   ''There is no rational conclusion to such a statement,'' he said
Wednesday. ''He is just trying to play the race card and so
continue the racial divide.''
</P>
<P>
   Tsvangirai also called on African leaders to condemn
government-orchestrated violence against his supporters.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
