<HEADLINE> Edwards Defense Calls Case 'Gossip'  </HEADLINE>
By NATALIE GOTT, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   BATON ROUGE, La. (AP) -- Prosecutors built their racketeering
case against former Gov. Edwin Edwards on half-truths and lies, his
attorney said in closing arguments Tuesday in federal court.
</P>
<P>
   ''We do not in this country convict someone on gossip,'' defense
attorney Dan Small said in his closing argument.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors have said Edwards tried to extort millions of
dollars from applicants for Louisiana riverboat casino licenses
during and after his fourth and final term, which ended in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Edwards faces 27 counts that could net him life in prison if
convicted. Edwards is 72.
</P>
<P>
   Small wrapped up his argument in two hours but it will be next
week before the jury begins deliberations.
</P>
<P>
   Five of Edwards' co-defendants spent the rest of the day making
their case and a lawyer for Edwards' son and co-defendant Stephen
Edwards will have two hours on Thursday. Prosecutors then will have
two hours of rebuttal arguments and court will recess for the
three-day Easter weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Small said several witnesses in the case told only half the
story or even changed their stories when they did not fit with what
the prosecution wanted.
</P>
<P>
   One such witness, Small said, was former San Francisco 49ers
owner Eddie DeBartolo Jr.
</P>
<P>
   DeBartolo testified that Edwards threatened to cause problems
for his casino license application in 1997 if he did not pay
Edwards $400,000.
</P>
<P>
   However, Small noted, on the government's own undercover
recordings, Edwards is heard expressing nothing but support for
DeBartolo's project.
</P>
<P>
   DeBartolo testified under an agreement with federal prosecutors,
pleading guilty to failure to report the alleged extortion. He drew
no prison time.
</P>
<P>
   ''Eddie DeBartolo made a sweet business deal. That's what
happened,'' Small said, pointing to the prosecution table. ''He
took them for a ride.''
</P>
<P>
   In 40 years of public life Edwards built a reputation as a
quick-witted wheeler-dealer, an unabashed gambler and ladies man
and a populist champion of the underprivileged.
</P>
<P>
   But he also was often tied to scandal and has, by his own count,
been the subject of close to two dozen state and federal
investigations.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
