<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-19 17:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AP Financial News at 5:10 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
Wednesday, April 19, 2000
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dow Ends Down 92; Nasdaq Off 87
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks fell today as investors took some profits
from a powerful two-day run and sold shares that failed to live up
to high expectations for corporate earnings. Mild volume and modest
losses for major market indicators made for one of the calmest
sessions of the year, in sharp contrast to the violent market
swings of recent weeks. the Dow Jones industrial average fell 92.46
to close at 10,674.96, having given up a solid midday gain. The
Nasdaq composite index fell 87.06 to close at 3,706.51. Broader
stock barometers also closed lower. The market's decline reminded
investors that last week's devastating selloff has left the market
vulnerable. Some mixed reports on corporate earnings and a sense
that the rally on Monday and yesterday may have been overdone
sparked selling today, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   Financial Figures
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Financial figures at the close:
Dow Industrials:        10674.96  - 92.46
NYSE Issues:         Advances 1471  Declines 1480  Unchgd  475
NYSE Volume:       1,001,344,060
Most Active NYSE issue:         Brist Myr Sqb46{  - 18}  
S&AMP;P 500:         1427.47 - 14.14
AMEX Mkt Value Index:          886.23  + 8.87
Nasdaq Composite Index        3706.51  - 87.06
Gold(final) -    $280.50    troy oz., NY Comex spot month Wed.
Silver(final) -   UNCH    troy oz., NY Comex spot month Tue.
</P>
<P>
   Feb. Trade Deficit Hit Record $29B
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- A surging foreign oil bill along with
Americans' appetite for foreign computers and telecommunications
equipment helped push the U.S. trade deficit to a monthly record of
$29.2 billion in February. The bigger-than-expected deficit was up
6.5 percent from a January shortfall of $27.4 billion, the Commerce
Department said. Imports jumped 1.5 percent in February to a record
$113.4 billion. U.S. exports fell 0.2 percent to $84.2 billion.
Sales of food fell, as did sales of cars and capital goods,
including airplanes and industrial machines. But economists said
the trade report isn't as bad as it appears. ''When you adjust for
oil prices, the deficit narrowed,'' said Northern Trust Co.'s chief
economist, Paul Kasriel.
</P>
<P>
   European Stocks Close Mostly Higher
</P>
<P>
   LONDON (AP) -- Most European markets rallied to an upbeat close
today on the heels of strong gains in the United States the
previous day. The Dow Jones Stoxx Index of shares in European
companies rose 5.61 points to 378.53. Technology and media shares
led gains, with the subindexes up 4.8 percent and 3.0 percent,
respectively. The Dow Jones Euro Stoxx Index ended up 2.97 points
at 422.82. In domestic markets, the FTSE 100 closed down 1.8
percent, at 6,184.9. Frankfurt's Xetra DAX Index ended up 0.3
percent to 7,216.71. Milan's MIBtel Index ended down 0.1 percent to
29,842.
</P>
<P>
   Toymaker Mattel Narrows Losses
</P>
<P>
   EL SEGUNDO, Calif. (AP) -- Troubled toymaker Mattel Inc. narrowed
its losses in the first quarter, benefiting from a jump in Barbie
sales and strength in its Fisher-Price business. But Wall Street
still wasn't satisfied with the financial results reported today,
and analysts said that more work was needed to revive the world's
biggest manufacturer of toys. Mattel reported a loss of $6.2
million, or 1 cent a share, from continuing operations for the
quarter, compared with $12.6 million, or 3 cents per share, in the
same period a year ago. Analysts had forecast a 3-cent loss per
share. Nattel stock was down 1/16 at 11 11/16 today.
</P>
<P>
   Willamette To Close Plywood Plant
</P>
<P>
   DALLAS, Ore. (AP) -- Willamette Industries will close its plywood
plant here, laying off 170 workers. The plant, which makes plywood
for underlayment and sheathing, faces stiff competition from
oriented strand board and is no longer competitive, according to
Tom Arlint, general manager of western manufacturing for
Willamette's Building Materials Group. The plant also faces costs
of adding expensive environmental controls, Arlint said.
</P>
<P>
   Paper Strike Ends in Finland
</P>
<P>
   HELSINKI, Finland (AP) -- Union leaders accepted a new labor
agreement today, ending a weeklong strike by 30,000 workers that
shut down most of Finland's pulp and paper industry. Employers
yesterday had already approved the mediation proposal by
government-appointed National Conciliator Juhani Salonius for a
three-year agreement that increases wages and gives workers one
extra day of paid holiday a year.
</P>
<P>
   New American Files Chapter 11
</P>
<P>
   NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) -- New American Healthcare Corp. has filed
for Chapter 11 bankruptcy protection for itself and its hospitals.
The company's eight hospitals will continue operating under the
terms of an agreement with banks for enough financing to pay
employees and pay costs during the bankruptcy process. New American
plans to sell its eight hospitals in six states with two in Oregon
and Texas and one each in Mississippi, Georgia, Wyoming and
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Boeing Profits Fall 11 Percent
</P>
<P>
   SEATTLE (AP) -- Boeing Co.'s profits fell 11 percent in the first
quarter of 2000, the company said today, blaming a 40-day strike by
engineers and technical workers for fewer aircraft deliveries and
lower revenues. Boeing made $418 million, 48 cents per share, on
revenues of $9.91 billion. In the same period last year, Boeing
made $469 million, or 50 cents per share, on sales of $14.39
billion -- a 31 percent drop in revenue. Despite the lower profits,
Boeing surpassed Wall Street's expectations. Analysts surveyed by
First Call/Thomson Financial had expected earnings of 35 cents per
share.
</P>
<P>
   Colgate's 1Q Profit Rises 15 Pct.
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Colgate-Palmolive Co.'s first-quarter profit
rose 15 percent as each of the consumer products company's
divisions around the world showed improvement. The maker of Colgate
toothpaste, Irish Spring soap, Mennen deodorant and Ajax cleanser
earned $239.9 million, or 38 cents a share, in the three months
ended March 31, up from $208.9 million, or 32 cents a share, a year
earlier. That was a penny a share better than analysts expected.
Colgate stock was up 7/16 at 55 11/16.
</P>
<P>
   Chase's 1Q Profits Rise 16 Percent
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Chase Manhattan Corp. said today that profits
rose 16 percent in the first quarter as the nation's third-largest
bank posted higher investment banking fees and gains in its
venture-capital portfolio. Chase earned $1.36 billion, or $1.59 a
share, topping Wall Street's estimate by 4 cents, according to a
survey by First Call/Thomson Financial. Chase Manhattan stock was
down 2{ at 78.
</P>
<P>
   Fuel Costs Hit Airlines Earnings
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Higher fuel costs dragged down earnings at major
air carriers in the first quarter, but UAL Corp. reported a 2
percent increase in operating profits on a 10 percent jump in
passenger revenue. Excluding one-time charges and certain
compensation expenses, the world's largest airline earned $191
million, or $1.61 per share, up from $187 million, or $1.54 per
share, in the year-earlier period. Trans World Airlines had a wider
first-quarter net loss: $76.1 million or $1.16 a share. But
passenger revenue, which accounts for the vast majority of the
company's revenue, rose to $723.6 million from $681.1 million.
America West reported a 44 percent drop in first-quarter earnings
due to higher fuel prices and operating problems early in the year.
Earnings were $14.6 million, or 40 cents.
</P>
<P>
   Tack Data Founder Is $45M in Debt
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- The founder of an online stock trading firm at
the forefront of the risky world of active day trading is $45
million in debt as a result of his own risky investment strategy --
buying stock on margin. Barry Hertz, the founder of Track Data
Corp., a Brooklyn, N.Y., firm that caters to investors who disdain
professional advice in favor of instant access to the markets, owes
the money to four brokerage firms from whom Hertz borrowed money to
speculate in the stock markets. The company said in a statement
earlier this week that Hertz was forced to put up half of the 45
million shares he owns of Track Data as collateral against his
debts.
</P>
<P>
   Economic Reports
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Economic reports:
</P>
<P>
   Monthly Trade deficit: up 6.5 percent
</P>
<P>
   Tomorrow: Jobless claims
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
