<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-19 17:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bosnian Woman Describes Rapes  </HEADLINE>
By JEROME SOCOLOVSKY, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   THE HAGUE, Netherlands (AP) -- The Muslim woman's ordeal began on
her 19th birthday when Serb soldiers overran her village and an
invader gave her to a soldier, who raped her, paraded her around
town as a sex conquest and eventually sold her for $250 and a truck
of laundry soap.
</P>
<P>
   ''They destroyed everything in me,'' the victim, identified as
A.S., testified Wednesday from behind a screen to a U.N. tribunal
on how her descent into terror began April 7, 1992, when the Serbs
took the Bosnian town of Foca.
</P>
<P>
   She said the Serb paramilitary Radomir Kovac, one of the
defendants, imprisoned her at an apartment in town and forced her
to serve as a sex slave for his roommate, a soldier, Jagos Kostic.
</P>
<P>
   Kostic, she said, forced her to have sexual intercourse in the
children's room of the apartment and paraded her around town as his
sexual conquest.
</P>
<P>
   ''He took me out and put a knife against my neck and beat me
with his fists and legs. With his knife he threatened to slit my
throat,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   When asked asked how often she was raped by Kostic, she said:
''Whenever he wanted to.''
</P>
<P>
   At another apartment, she said she was raped ''perhaps 50, 60
times. I don't know.''
</P>
<P>
   When the Serbs were finished with her, she said, they sold A.S.
and another girl as chattel to a pair of Montenegrins for ''500
German marks ($250) and a truck full of washing powder.'
</P>
<P>
   The woman, who wept during the testimony, said the two were
raped and forced to work as barmaids in cafes for a while, and then
put on a passenger bus headed for a Muslim area of Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
   The ordeal lasted a year, she said, and in the years since, the
witness has suffered back and kidney problems, serious infections,
and underwent surgery for polyps.
</P>
<P>
   The American prosecuting attorney, Peggy Kuo, asked her to
describe the emotional pain she still feels.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's difficult,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ''Are you able to try?'' Kuo gently asked.
</P>
<P>
   ''I have pills, sedatives, and I also take pills for rheumatism
and for everything else.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Do those pills affect ability to recall the events that
happened to you?'' Kuo asked.
</P>
<P>
   ''No,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The witness was the fifth rape victim to testify in the Foca
rape trial, the first international prosecution of the sexual
enslavement of women in wartime.
</P>
<P>
   It has produced horrifying tales of women and girls, some as
young as 12, assaulted in rape camps and soldiers apartments in the
early part of the 1992-95 Bosnian war.
</P>
<P>
   The woman said she had never talked about the ordeal with
anyone, not even her mother, until last month, when she responded
to a request she had received from tribunal investigators.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors contend the systematic rapes were not only for the
soldiers' own gratification, but also represented one of the most
vicious components of the Serb strategy of ''ethnic cleansing.''
</P>
<P>
   The proceeding began March 20 at the U.N. tribunal, set up in
1993 to bring those responsible for atrocities in the Balkans to
justice.
</P>
<P>
   Former Bosnian Serb paramilitaries Dragoljub Kunarac, Kovac and
Zoran Vukovic have pleaded innocent to charges of war crimes and
crimes against humanity. If convicted, they face a maximum life in
prison.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-19-00 1717 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000419.0147 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-19 17:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Turkish Cops Storm Rebel Hide-out  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   BATMAN, Turkey (AP) -- Police on Wednesday stormed a suspected
Kurdish rebel hide-out in this southeastern city, killing one
alleged militant who refused to surrender, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Police also detained four people -- two of them women -- who were
in the house at the time of the raid, the first reported on a rebel
hide-out since guerrillas of the Kurdistan Workers' Party, or PKK,
announced an end to their armed struggle last year.
</P>
<P>
   Turkey has ignored the PKK's cease-fire and has vowed to
continue its fight until all surrender or are killed.
</P>
<P>
   Police charged into a house after the suspected rebel ignored
calls to turn himself in and fired shots at officers, said Police
Chief Muzaffer Erkan.
</P>
<P>
   ''We tried to catch him, but he responded to our calls to
surrender with a gun,'' Erkan said.
</P>
<P>
   Erkan said police had been watching the suspected militant's
moves for some time. His identity was not released, but the
semiofficial Anatolia news agency said the man was in his thirties.
</P>
<P>
   Most PKK rebels have withdrawn from southeastern Turkey under
orders from their imprisoned leader, Abdullah Ocalan, who now wants
to struggle for Kurdish rights using political means. Turkey
dismisses the group as a terrorist organization and says it will
never negotiate with its members.
</P>
<P>
   Turkey does not recognize Kurds as a minority and bans teaching
and broadcasts in the Kurdish language.
</P>
<P>
   Some 37,000 people, mostly Kurds, have been killed in clashes in
the southeast since the rebels took up arms in 1984.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-19-00 1719 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000419.0148 </DOCNO>
