<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-19 17:24 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 26 Killed in Kenya Cop, Bandit Clash  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NAIROBI, Kenya (AP) -- An attack by a gang of suspected cattle
rustlers and an ensuing gun battle with police claimed 26 lives
Wednesday in north central Kenya, police said.
</P>
<P>
   The suspected rustlers, believed to be members of Kenya's Pokot
tribe, had attacked a homestead belonging to the Turkana tribe,
killing nine people, police spokesman Peter Kimanthi said in a
statement.
</P>
<P>
   Police pursued the gang and caught up with them at Soito Kikuyu
village in Samburu district, about 132 miles north of Nairobi and a
heavy gun battle and police shot 17 members of the gang to death,
arresting four others, the statement said. Police suffered no
causalities, it said.
</P>
<P>
   Police recovered 852 head of cattle, 240 camels and 470 goats,
the statement said.
</P>
<P>
   Cattle-rustling is endemic among the herding communities that
straddle the region that crosses the borders of Kenya, Uganda,
Sudan and Ethiopia. Easy access to modern weapons has made the
traditional raids increasingly deadly.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
