<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Feb. Trade Deficit Hit Record $29B  </HEADLINE>
By JEANNINE AVERSA, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- A surging foreign oil bill along with
Americans' appetite for foreign computers and telecommunications
equipment helped push the U.S. trade deficit to a monthly record of
$29.2 billion in February.
</P>
<P>
   That bigger-than-expected deficit was up 6.5 percent from a
January shortfall of $27.4 billion, the previous record, the
Commerce Department said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Imports jumped 1.5 percent in February to a record $113.4
billion as sales of crude petroleum, industrial supplies including
chemicals and capital goods such as computers and
telecommunications equipment rose to records.
</P>
<P>
   Through the first two months of this year, the U.S. trade
deficit was running at an annual rate of $340 billion, compared
with $268 billion for all of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ''About half of the increase in the deficit thus far this year
can be traced to higher petroleum prices,'' said Commerce Secretary
William Daley.
</P>
<P>
   The price of crude oil hit $25.01 per barrel in February, the
highest since $25.75 in December 1990 on the eve of the Persian
Gulf War. Imports of foreign oil, meanwhile, hit an all-time
monthly high of $6.5 billion in February.
</P>
<P>
   Production limits by oil-producing nations pushed crude-oil
prices to a nine-year high in early March of $34 a barrel, but
prices have fallen since then. A decision by the Organization of
Petroleum Exporting Countries to boost production should provide
additional relief.
</P>
<P>
   America's deficit with OPEC countries widened to a record $3.2
billion in February, a 21.4 percent increase.
</P>
<P>
   Economists said the trade report isn't as bad as it appears.
''When you adjust for oil prices, the deficit narrowed,'' said
Northern Trust Co.'s chief economist, Paul Kasriel. National
Association of Manufacturers' economist Gordon Richards said:
''outside of oil, imports showed a small decrease.''
</P>
<P>
   On Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial average and the Nasdaq
closed down as investors took some profits from a powerful two-day
run and sold shares that failed to live up to high expectations for
corporate earnings. The market was little affected by the trade
report.
</P>
<P>
   For the second straight month, U.S. exports dipped in February.
They fell 0.2 percent to $84.2 billion. Sales of food such as fish,
corn and fruits fell, as did sales of cars and capital goods,
including airplanes and industrial machines.
</P>
<P>
   The widening trade deficit is the one bit of tarnish on an
otherwise sterling, record-breaking economy, which is in its ninth
year of uninterrupted growth.
</P>
<P>
   Economists said the bloated deficit is actually a testimony to
the robust state of the U.S. economy compared with other countries,
particularly foreign economies that are continuing to recover from
a global financial crisis that struck in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Prosperous consumers are helping the United States gobble up
imported goods as demand from overseas' economies for U.S. exports,
while picking up, continues to lag.
</P>
<P>
   ''The U.S economy is surging at a pace so much faster than the
rest of the world that exports just cannot hope to keep up with
imports,'' said economist Joel Naroff of Naroff Economic Advisors.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. economy could face dangers at some point, economists
warn, if the huge increases in the trade deficit continue and
foreigners suddenly decide they no longer want to hold
dollar-denominated assets. A sudden rush for the exits could send
American stock prices and the value of the dollar plunging.
</P>
<P>
   On the political front, the deficit could present the Clinton
administration with political problems as it tries to sell a
landmark trade agreement to Congress that would clear the way for
China to become a member of the 135-nation World Trade
Organization.
</P>
<P>
   America's deficit with China narrowed by 6.8 percent in February
to $5.6 billion. But that deficit is running $2.2 billion higher in
the first two months of this year than the same period last year.
The administration argues that the market-opening trade deal with
China would mean billions of dollars in increased sales for
American exporters.
</P>
<P>
   The politically sensitive deficit with Japan shot up 20.7
percent to $6.7 billion.
</P>
<P>
   There was at least one bright spot in the report for U.S.
exporters. Sales of U.S. consumer goods, such as household
appliances, rose by $253 million to a record monthly high of $7.3
billion in February.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: Highlights of the trade report:
</P>
<P>
   http://www.census.gov/indicator/www/ustrade.html
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
