<BODY>
<HEADLINE> AM-CT--Phone Slamming, 1st Ld-Writethru,379  </HEADLINE>
AT&AMP;T settles complaint over switching unknowing customers
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW BRITAIN, Conn. (AP) -- AT&AMP;T Corp. on Wednesday said it will
pay for a consumer education campaign in Connecticut to settle a
3-year-old dispute over the practice of switching long-distance
service without the customer's knowledge.
</P>
<P>
   The phone company has agreed to produce 1,000 brochures against
''phone slamming'' to be distributed by the state Department of
Utility Control and the Office of Consumer Counsel. AT&AMP;T also will
pay up to $10,000 to produce a public service radio announcement --
in English and Spanish -- to educate consumers on slamming.
</P>
<P>
   It is essentially the same agreement the company and the DPUC
tentatively reached in 1998, but was opposed by state Attorney
General Richard Blumenthal. He argued the agreement does nothing to
deter future unlawful conduct by AT&AMP;T and recommended any
settlement signed by the DPUC include a commitment from AT&AMP;T not to
engage in specific unlawful conduct.
</P>
<P>
   But the DPUC said Wednesday that AT&AMP;T has demonstrated a
''willingness and ability'' to curb slamming complaints and has
improved its response to those complaints.
</P>
<P>
   Under the agreement, AT&AMP;T representatives will begin meeting
with state regulators at least once a month for three months to
discuss the how the company handles complaints. After the first
three months, a new meeting schedule will be negotiated.
</P>
<P>
   The DPUC began investigating the New York-based AT&AMP;T in 1997
after fielding complaints from more than 150 consumers who said
they were victims of phone slamming.
</P>
<P>
   Utility officials said slamming complaints involving AT&AMP;T
increased by more than 300 percent in 1997 over the year before.
The number of slamming complaints against AT&AMP;T also was much higher
than other phone service providers in the state, according to the
DPUC.
</P>
<P>
   Blumenthal called the action a slap on the wrist.
</P>
<P>
   ''This serious anti-consumer misconduct merited a significant
fine and other penalties to deter and punish slamming,'' he said.
''We will continue to battle abuses of consumer rights that harm
them financially by misusing technology in slamming and similar
practices.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
