<HEADLINE> Dow Ends Down 92; Nasdaq Off 87  </HEADLINE>
By EILEEN GLANTON, AP Business Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Stocks fell Wednesday as investors took some
profits from a powerful two-day run and sold shares that failed to
live up to high expectations for corporate earnings.
</P>
<P>
   Mild volume and modest losses for major market indicators made
for one of the calmest sessions of the year, in sharp contrast to
the violent market swings of recent weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow Jones industrial average fell 92.46 to close at
10,674.96, having given up a solid midday gain.
</P>
<P>
   The Nasdaq composite index fell 87.16 to close at 3,706.41.
Broader stock barometers also closed lower. The Standard &AMP; Poor's
500 fell 14.14 to 1,427.47.
</P>
<P>
   The decline reminded investors that last week's devastating
selloff has left the market vulnerable. Some mixed reports on
corporate earnings and a sense that the rally on Monday and Tuesday
may have been overdone sparked selling on Wednesday, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   ''More than anything else, we had a negative reaction to the two
strong days that came before,'' said Ricky Harrington, technical
analyst at Wachovia Securities in Charlotte, N.C. ''The market has
had a strong technical rally but it might not yet be sustainable.''
</P>
<P>
   In the first two sessions of this week, the Nasdaq rose 472
points, with record point gains each day, and the Dow average
gained 461, wiping out big chunks of the crushing losses sustained
last week. Financial markets will be closed Friday for the
observance of Good Friday, and with a long string of volatile
sessions behind them, some investors took a pause ahead of the long
weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Once again, earnings reports drove the market. Companies are
nearing the peak of the reporting season, and while most companies
have reported very strong profit growth, investors have punished
those that have shown any hint of weakness.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, IBM fell 7 to 104{. The company said late Tuesday
that while earnings beat analysts' expectations, sales slumped 5
percent in the first quarter, dragged down by a broad decline in
products ranging from desktop computers to mainframes to hard disk
drives.
</P>
<P>
   Intel, a bellwether technology stock, fell 9 15/16 to 119 1/16,
accounting for the largest share of the Dow's decline. Intel said
first-quarter profits rose 37 percent, and executives also
predicted unusually high sales for the traditionally sluggish
second quarter.
</P>
<P>
   However, some analysts were looking for higher revenue growth in
the coming quarters. Also, Intel stock had risen sharply in advance
of the report, prompting investors to take profits.
</P>
<P>
   Qualcomm rose 2 9/16 to 114} on the Nasdaq. The maker of mobile
phone technology reported earnings of 25 cents a share, beating
analysts' expectations of 24 cents a share. Before Wednesday's
session, Qualcomm -- one of the top-performing Nasdaq stocks in 1999
-- had tumbled about 36 percent in the year to date as investors
took profits.
</P>
<P>
   Drug stocks, which are seen as more stable growth stocks than
the volatile technology group, were mostly higher after
Warner-Lambert reported that operating profits surged 35 percent in
the quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Warner-Lambert rose 7 7/64 to 114] and Merck rose 2} to 69.
</P>
<P>
   Late in the session, however, Bristol-Myers Squibb broke the
trend, tumbling 14{ to 50| after the company announced that it will
withdraw a new drug application for hypertension drug Vanlev from
the Food and Drug Administration. The drug was expected to be a
blockbuster for Bristol-Myers.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts said the renewed focus on earnings is the strongest
legacy of last week's rout. Many attributed the cataclysmic selling
to investors who drove stocks up too high on pure momentum, then
panicked on the fear that earnings wouldn't justify their high
prices.
</P>
<P>
   ''Fundamentals do count, and will probably continue to drive at
least the near-term buying momentum within the marketplace,'' said
Brian G. Belski, chief investment strategist at George K. Baum &AMP;
Co. in Kansas City, Mo.
</P>
<P>
   The market was little affected by a report that the U.S. trade
deficit shot up to a record $29.2 billion in February as Americans'
demand for foreign oil hit an all-time monthly high while sales of
exports dipped.
</P>
<P>
   The Commerce Department said the deficit widened by 6.5 percent
in February. The deficit was bigger than the $28.9 billion
imbalance many analysts were forecasting.
</P>
<P>
   Declining issues outnumbered advancers by an extremely narrow
margin on the New York Stock Exchange. On the Nasdaq, advancers led
by a 5-to-4 margin.
</P>
<P>
   NYSE volume totaled 1.20 billion shares, compared with 1.33
billion in the previous session.
</P>
<P>
   The Russell 2000 index of smaller companies rose 0.15 to 486.23.
</P>
<P>
   Overseas, Japan's Nikkei stock average rose 0.6 percent.
Germany's DAX index rose 0.3 percent, Britain's FT-SE 100 gained
1.8 percent, and France's CAC-40 rose 0.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net:
</P>
<P>
   New York Stock Exchange: http://www.nyse.com
</P>
<P>
   Nasdaq Stock Market: http://www.nasdaq.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
