<HEADLINE> World Bank Protesters Hold Vigil  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- About 50 World Bank and International Monetary
Fund protesters are holding a quiet vigil outside a District of
Columbia jail, vowing to stay until their fellow protesters are
released.
</P>
<P>
   The estimated 150 protesters jailed are required to identify
themselves and post $50 fines before they can leave but are
refusing to do, protester Fraf Wheaton of Texas said Wednesday.
They believe they should not be in jail and ''won't be forced to
submit to the system,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In a grassy spot outside the jail, two green tarps cover duffel
bags, clothes and blankets. Food is available, thanks in part to a
friendly woman down the road who has delivered soy milk, chicken,
juice and bagels, Wheaton said.
</P>
<P>
   Those camped out cooked over a gas stove Tuesday night -- making
stew with lentils, potatoes and cabbage.
</P>
<P>
   D.C. police estimated as many as 10,000 protesters were in town
Sunday and Monday to protest and try to stop the World Bank and IMF
meetings, which proceeded as scheduled.
</P>
<P>
   Arrests throughout the week topped 1,300.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
