<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Euro Sinks To New Low Against Dollar  </HEADLINE>
By SKIP WOLLENBERG, AP Business Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- The euro fell to a new low against the dollar
Wednesday before recovering a bit, its decline fueled by doubts
that Europe will be taking steps anytime soon to stimulate growth
and investment opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   The single currency adopted by 11 European currencies at the
start of 1999 sank as low as 93.57 cents in midday trading in New
York. Its previous low had been 93.90 cents reached Feb. 28.
</P>
<P>
   In late New York trading, the euro had recovered somewhat to
94.04 cents, still down from 94.80 cents late Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   In other trading, the dollar was quoted at 104.78 Japanese yen,
up from 104.75 yen late Tuesday; 1.6688 Swiss francs, up from
1.6623, and 1.4742 Canadian dollars, down from 1.4828. The British
pound rose to $1.5813 from $1.5790.
</P>
<P>
   The euro came under pressure this week after it was unable to
stage a recovery during last week's late rout in U.S. stock prices.
</P>
<P>
   Some traders has been expecting the euro would benefit a sharp
decline in U.S. stocks on the theory that traders would pull funds
from America to invest elsewhere. But Wall Street's woes didn't
spark demand for the European currency. U.S. stock prices bounced
higher on Monday and Tuesday before giving some ground Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Greg Anderson, who follows foreign exchange developments at
Fleet in Boston, said the euro's weakness reflects the ''low
confidence'' that European authorities will enact ''the type of
economic programs and reforms that are going to lead to growth
rates there similar to those in the U.S.''
</P>
<P>
   He said investors ''are looking for clarity and vision in
long-term policies'' such as on taxes to convince them to commit
money to Europe but are not seeing it.
</P>
<P>
   Eric Nickerson, currency strategist in New York for Bank of
America, said the dollar is benefitting from a perception that last
week's stock selloff was simply a correction rather than an end to
the bull market of most of the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   ''Domestic demand still strong. There is not much reason to
sell,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He said European authorities, meanwhile, have appeared ''not
particularly concerned about the euro's weakness.''
</P>
<P>
   Currencies of the 11 countries participating in the euro are no
longer traded separately and are tied to the euro by a fixed rate.
Based on Wednesday's euro rate, the dollar was worth: 2.0796 German
marks, up from 2.0629; 6.9749 French francs, up from 6.9186; and
2,058.86 Italian lire, up from 2,042.26.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
