<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-19 17:57 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Drugmakers Report Earnings Growth  </HEADLINE>
By PHIL GALEWITZ, AP Business Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- American Home Products Corp. and Warner-Lambert
Co., two of the nation's largest drugmakers, posted strong
first-quarter operating earnings growth on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The two companies had planned to merge until Pfizer Inc. became
involved in a messy three-way takeover battle that ultimately led
to the pending combination between Pfizer and Warner-Lambert.
</P>
<P>
   For Warner-Lambert, fast growth has become commonplace in the
past several quarters due mostly to explosive sales of its
cholesterol-lowering drug Lipitor.
</P>
<P>
   American Home's higher net income stands in contrast to its
sluggish 1999 performance.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   American Home Products
</P>
<P>
   Rebounding from slugglish growth in the past year, American Home
Products first-quarter profits rose 18 percent, fueled by strong
sales of its estrogen-replacement pill Premarin.
</P>
<P>
   Including special items, American Home's net income was $276.4
million or 21 cents per share, compared to $654 million or 49 cents
per share a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   The first-quarter results included a $1.8 billion fee the
company received from Warner-Lambert for breaking off its merger
with American Home. Warner-Lambert terminated the deal to merge
with Pfizer, a pact expected to be completed later this spring.
</P>
<P>
   Excluding one-time items, American Home earned $634.9 million or
48 cents per share in the three months ended March 31, up from
$538.1 million or 40 cents per share in the year-ago period.
Results matched Wall Street forecasts, which had been lowered in
the past few days, according to First Call/Thomson Financial.
</P>
<P>
   Sales from continuing operations increased 16 percent in the
first quarter to $3.34 billion from $2.86 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The Madison, N.J.-based-company's drug sales rose 16 percent to
$2.7 billion. Sales of Premarin rose 8 percent to $542 million, its
antidepressant Effexor rose 54 percent to $252 million and Enbrel,
a rheumatoid arthritis drug doubled to $136 million.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, American Home only made a tiny profit after the
company had to fend off thousands of lawsuits related to its diet
drugs and recall some drugs due to safety concerns.
</P>
<P>
   American Home's results were negatively affected by a loss of
$1.57 billion from the sale of its agricultural business, which it
sold for $3.8 billion to European chemical concern BASF AG.
</P>
<P>
   The company's consumer health sales rose 6 percent to $595.9
million in the quarter on the strength of its Centrum vitamins and
Advil pain reliever.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of American Home rose $2.75, or nearly 5 percent, to
$59.12{ at 5:15 p.m. EST on the New York Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Warner-Lambert
</P>
<P>
   Warner-Lambert's first quarter operating profit surged 35
percent, but the drugmaker reported a $1.4 billion net loss, or
$1.61 a share, because of the large breakup fee it had to pay for
terminating its merger deal with American Home Products.
</P>
<P>
   Excluding the breakup fee and other unusual items,
Warner-Lambert made $516 million or 58 cents per share in the three
months ended March 31, compared to $382 million or 43 cents per
share in the year-ago period. Results topped Wall Street
expectations by 2 cents, according to First Call/Thomson Financial.
</P>
<P>
   The Morris Plains, N.J.-based company attributed its strong
operating earnings to fast rising sales of Lipitor and the
anticonvulsant drug Neurontin.
</P>
<P>
   Lipitor sales rose 46 percent to $1.1 billion. The drug now
controls half of the U.S. market share for cholesterol pills. Sales
of Neurontin rose 71 percent to $301 million.
</P>
<P>
   The company's consumer products, which include Benadryl allergy
products and Schick razors, posted a 2 percent increase in sales to
$748 million.
</P>
<P>
   Sales of the firm's confectionary products, such as Trident gum
and Halls cough tablets, rose 9 percent to $500 million.
</P>
<P>
   The company's first quarter results were also hurt by a $91
million charge from the recall of its diabetes drug Rezulin, which
has been linked to several dozen deaths since it was introduced in
1997.
</P>
<P>
   Shares of Warner-Lambert rose $7.73 7/16, or more than 7
percent, to $115 at 5:15 p.m. EST on the New York Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   On the Net: http://www.ahp.com
</P>
<P>
   http://www.warnerlambert.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
