<HEADLINE> Crude, Heating Oil Futures Soar  </HEADLINE>
By BENNIE M. CURRIE, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   Heating oil and crude futures rose sharply Wednesday on the New
York Mercantile Exchange amid growing concern about shrinking fuel
supplies, which are at their lowest level in at least seven years.
</P>
<P>
   In other markets, cattle and grain futures climbed higher.
</P>
<P>
   Inventories for distillate fuel, which includes heating oil and
diesel fuel, fell again last week, according to newly released data
from the Department of Energy and the American Petroleum Institute.
That prompted a nearly 9 percent surge in heating oil prices, also
leading other energy commodities higher.
</P>
<P>
   Heating oil for May delivery rose 6.07 cents to 76.85 cents a
gallon, while May intermediate crude jumped $1.24 to $27.35 a
barrel.
</P>
<P>
   May unleaded gasoline followed suit, rising 2.47 cents to 85.33
cents a gallon, while May natural gas fell 4.3 cents to $3.055 per
1,000 cubic feet.
</P>
<P>
   In London, June Brent crude from the North Sea rose 72 cents to
$23.77 a barrel on the International Petroleum Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   The Energy Department data released early Wednesday confirmed
what API figures had shown late the day before -- that distillate
and gasoline stocks both dropped.
</P>
<P>
   Bill O'Grady, energy futures analyst for A.G. Edwards &AMP; Sons
Inc. in St. Louis, said falling inventories, coming at a time of
year when stockpiles usually are building, are heightening fears
about the possibility of summer shortages.
</P>
<P>
   Inventories are shrinking partly because of truck drivers
tanking up to keep pace with the booming economy, according to
analysts.
</P>
<P>
   ''You also have a significant need for diesel fuel for crop
equipment, combines, tractors and planting,'' O'Grady said, noting
that spring planting has been accelerated due to unusually dry
Midwestern conditions.
</P>
<P>
   Heating oil inventories are about 15 million barrels lower than
their five-year average, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere, cattle prices pushed to three-week highs on the
Chicago Mercantile Exchange as beef demand continued to soar in the
runup to America's beloved summer barbecue season.
</P>
<P>
   Despite prices that are at seven-year highs, supermarkets and
other retailers are stocking up on beef with confidence that
consumers will soon start snapping up beef for warm-weather
cookouts.
</P>
<P>
   June live cattle rose .25 cents to 69.52 cents a pound after
hitting a three-week high of 69.90 cents a pound.
</P>
<P>
   Grain and soybean futures resumed their rise on investors'
lingering concerns about dry soil conditions in the Midwest.
</P>
<P>
   Even though many growing regions took a soaking Wednesday,
market watchers said the dry weather pattern that has depleted soil
moisture in recent months would continue, leaving moisture levels
below normal.
</P>
<P>
   May corn rose 3\ cents to $2.27} a bushel; July oats rose 2{
cents to $1.22\ a bushel; July wheat rose 1 cent to $2.65\ a
bushel; July soybeans rose 3} cents to $5.50} a bushel.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
