<HEADLINE> Toymaker Mattel Narrows Losses  </HEADLINE>
By MICHAEL WHITE, AP Business Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   EL SEGUNDO, Calif. (AP) -- Troubled toymaker Mattel Inc. narrowed
its losses in the first quarter, benefiting from a jump in Barbie
sales and strength in its Fisher-Price business.
</P>
<P>
   But Wall Street still wasn't satisfied with the financial
results reported Wednesday, and analysts said that more work was
needed to revive the world's biggest manufacturer of toys.
</P>
<P>
   Mattel's stock fell 6\ cents to $11.68} in trading at 4:30 p.m.
on the New York Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   ''I don't think the income statement was particularly
optimistic,'' said Joe Kinnison, an analyst with American Express
Financial Advisers. ''I need to see some progress on the
fundamentals before I would get our investors to purchase it.''
</P>
<P>
   Mattel reported a loss of $6.2 million, or 1 cent a share, from
continuing operations for the quarter ended March 31, compared with
a loss of $12.6 million, or 3 cents per share, in the same period a
year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Mattel beat a 3-cents-per-share loss forecast by analysts
surveyed by First Call/Thompson Financial. The results, however,
did not reflect a $127 million loss in the company's interactive
toys division, which for reporting purposes was considered a
discontinued operation.
</P>
<P>
   The results also did not include $38.4 million in severance
payments to former chief executive Jill E. Barad and other senior
officers.
</P>
<P>
   Quarterly sales rose 1 percent to $693.3 million.
</P>
<P>
   Barbie sales in the United States rose 14 percent, but overseas
fell 5 percent despite a concerted campaign to boost the doll's
international appeal. Sales in the core Fisher-Price pre-school
division rose 29 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ''Barbie in the U.S. is turning around,'' Kinnison said. ''Their
inventory was in much better shape going into the first quarter
this year. Sales are robust. Barbie international, however, is
disappointing.''
</P>
<P>
   Problems in Mattel's interactive division were rooted in its
acquisition last year of software maker The Learning Company for
$3.6 billion. The company was expected to immediately add to
Mattel's revenues, but instead lost millions of dollars.
</P>
<P>
   Barad resigned in February after Mattel reported a loss for the
fourth consecutive quarter. A string of executive departures began
in November, when Learning Company founders Kevin O'Leary and
Michael Perik resigned in the wake of big losses in the division.
Mattel President Ned Mansour resigned last month.
</P>
<P>
   Mattel has not said how much money individual executives,
including Barad, were being paid after they left the company. In a
news release on Wednesday, Mattel said the $38.4 million in
severance included the forgiveness of unspecified loans.
</P>
<P>
   Since Barad left, board member William Rollnick has served as
Mattel's acting chairman and Ronald Loeb as acting CEO. The company
is looking for a new chief executive.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
