<HEADLINE> DaimlerChrysler Earns Up, Stock Down  </HEADLINE>
By HANS GREIMEL, AP Business Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   BERLIN (AP) -- DaimlerChrysler AG surpassed Wall Street
expectations Wednesday with a 3 percent increase in first-quarter
earnings, but excitement was tempered by declining profit margins
in North America and an ever-shrinking stock price.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking at the company's annual shareholder meeting, Chairman
Juergen Schrempp said DaimlerChrysler was feeling the squeeze of
competitors slashing prices in the United States to snag customers
for high-profit minivans and sport utility vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   The problem -- rolling out rebates, discounts and other
incentives in order to compete -- has cut into DaimlerChrysler's
bottom line, triggering a 7 percent drop in the operating profit at
Chrysler division.
</P>
<P>
   Investors didn't like the news, and DaimlerChrysler stock closed
down 1.96 euros, or 2.9 percent, to 66.75 euros ($63.41) in
Frankfurt trading. On the New York Stock Exchange, shares fared
slightly better, falling 75 cents to $63.87{.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's declines come after disheartened shareholders have
already watched the price steadily erode over the past year, down
almost 30 percent from its 52-week high.
</P>
<P>
   ''Where's my shareholder value?'' demanded Evelyn Y. Davis, a
shareholder activist from Washington who traveled to Wednesday's
meeting to confront the DaimlerChrysler board. She said her shares
in Chrysler Corp. were worth $32,000 before the 1998 merger, but
are only worth $18,000 today.
</P>
<P>
   More than 8,000 shareholders attended Wednesday's annual
meeting, and Davis wasn't alone in lining up at the podium to air
their angst about DaimlerChrysler's precipitous slide.
</P>
<P>
   The auditorium erupted in applause when Schrempp said, ''There
is one point on which I am as dissatisfied you are. That is the
trend in share prices over the past 12 month.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Schrempp remained upbeat about the first quarter, saying
last month's deal to acquire a 34 percent stake in Mitsubishi
Motors seals DaimlerChrysler's role as a global powerhouse ready to
take on No. 1 General Motors Corp. and No. 2 Ford Motor Co.
</P>
<P>
   ''The new millennium is off to a great start for
DaimlerChrysler,'' Schrempp said. ''No company has such a
well-balanced spread across all world markets and is so
well-positioned as we are.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite declining profit margins at the German-American company,
it said overall net income was up 3 percent in the first three
months of 2000 to 1.69 billion euros ($1.62 billion), or 1.69 euros
($1.62) a share. That compares to 1.64 billion euros ($1.6
billion), or 1.64 euros ($1.57) a share, in the same period a year
ago.
</P>
<P>
   The results edged out Wall Street estimates of $1.58 a share for
the quarter, as surveyed by First Call/Thomson Financial. Schrempp
said the company expects earnings per share to increase for the
full year.
</P>
<P>
   Revenues for the quarter also rose 17 percent, to 40.9 billion
euros ($39.2 billion) from 34.9 billion ($33.5 billion).
</P>
<P>
   The Chrysler division had revenues of 18.9 billion euros ($18.2
billion) for the first quarter, an increase of 24 percent over last
year. That was driven by a 10 percent increase in the number of
vehicles sold.
</P>
<P>
   The Mercedes-Benz and Smart car division had revenues of $9.9
billion euros ($9.5 billion), a 17 percent increase over last year.
Sales of Mercedes-Benz passengers cars were up 7 percent in the
quarter. Sales of the micro-mini Smart car, available only in
Europe, totaled 18,500 for the quarter, more than doubling the
figures from last year.
</P>
<P>
   At the meeting, shareholders approved a proposed dividend for
1999 of 2.35 euros ($2.25), unchanged from the previous year. That
was a sore point for some who complained that the dividend --
relatively small by U.S. standards -- added insult to sinking stock
price.
</P>
<P>
   DaimlerChrysler shareholders also approved a share buyback and a
new stock option plan for DaimlerChrysler management.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
