<HEADLINE> General Dynamics Earnings, Sales Up  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   FALLS CHURCH, Va. (AP) -- General Dynamics reported a 17 percent
rise in first-quarter earnings on increased sales in the military
contractor's aerospace, combat, shipbuilding and technology
divisions.
</P>
<P>
   The Falls Church-based company earned $184 million, or 91 cents
per share, in the three months that ended April 2. That compares
with $158 million, or 78 cents per share, in the same period of
1999, excluding one-time gains.
</P>
<P>
   Revenues for the quarter were $2.55 billion, compared with $2
billion in the same period a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Chairman and chief executive Nicholas Chabraja attributed the
gains to a 17 percent increase in sales in the aerospace division,
combined with more efficient operations in the Gulfstream corporate
jet division.
</P>
<P>
   Sales in the information systems and technology division were up
160 percent, primarily due to the acquisition of several technology
companies. Sales in the marine division also rose.
</P>
<P>
   During the quarter, the Navy began a $435 million contract with
General Dynamics for the construction of the first of four
amphibious transport ships to be built at Bath Iron Works in Maine.
</P>
<P>
   General Dynamics hopes to compete for more European arms
contracts following the announcement last week that it would buy
ENSB, a Spanish maker of combat vehicles and munitions that has a
contract to provide a battle tank for Spain's military.
</P>
<P>
   The company's shares were priced at $52 at 5:15 p.m. EST on the
New York Stock Exchange, up $1.75 or nearly 3.5 percent.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
