<HEADLINE> PepsiCo Profits Rise 10.4 Percent  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- PepsiCo Inc.'s first-quarter earnings rose 10.4
percent as growth in profits at its snack food, juice and
international beverage businesses more than offset a decline in the
domestic soft drink division blamed on higher prices.
</P>
<P>
   The results were slightly above Wall Street forecasts but
PepsiCo shares fell 62{ cents to $35.31\ a share in trading on the
New York Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   The food and beverage concern from Purchase, N.Y., earned $422
million, or 29 cents a share, in the three months ended March 18
compared with $333 million, or 22 cents a share, reported a year
earlier.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts surveyed by First Call/Thomson Financial expected
earnings of 28 cents a share.
</P>
<P>
   Revenue fell to $4.19 billion from $5.11 billion a year ago, but
the decline was due to PepsiCo's public offering of a 60 percent
stake in its bottling operations. Its revenue was up 8 percent if
last year's figures are adjusted to exclude the bottling revenue.
</P>
<P>
   Frito-Lay's operating profit rose 10 percent in North America
and 27 percent overseas.
</P>
<P>
   Double-digit growth in the Ruffles and Cheetos brands and new
product introductions helped boost North American revenue by 6
percent as favorable commodity costs and higher volume helped lift
profits.
</P>
<P>
   Pepsi-Cola North America, the second biggest soft drink company,
posted an 8 percent decline in its operating profit as higher
retail prices depressed volume for the quarter. The company said
shipments began to improve in March.
</P>
<P>
   Operating profit rose 30 percent in the Pepsi-Cola International
operations and 70 percent at the Tropicana juice business.
</P>
</TEXT>
