<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Oscar-Winning Actress Kedrova Dies  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAULT STE. MARIE, Ontario (AP) -- Lila Kedrova Howard, who won an
Oscar and a Tony for her role as Madame Hortense in the film and
stage version of ''Zorba the Greek,'' has died of heart failure.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian-born actress' birth records were lost years ago, but
her husband, Richard Howard, said she was believed to be in her 80s
when she died on Feb. 16 in Sault Ste. Marie, across the border
from northern Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   Known professionally as Lila Kedrova, she won the Academy Award
for best supporting actress in 1964 for her portrayal of the dying
French prostitute in the film version of ''Zorba the Greek'' that
featured Anthony Quinn, Alan Bates and Irene Papas.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty years later, Kedrova and Quinn also starred on Broadway
in the musical based on the Nikos Kazantzakis novel, and she
received a Tony award.
</P>
<P>
   Known for her smoky, sensuous singing voice, Kedrova acted in
scores of other movies and stage shows in a career that began in
the 1930s and ended in the early 1990s, according to Howard.
</P>
<P>
   Born in Leningrad, Kedrova and her family fled the former Soviet
Union for Paris in the 1930s and she began performing at age 14,
she said in a 1984 interview.
</P>
<P>
   She met Howard in London in 1968 while she was appearing in a
production of Anton Chekhov's The Cherry Orchard. They were married
in Sault Ste. Marie on New Year's Eve 1968.
</P>
<P>
   The couple had no children, and Kedrova suffered from congestive
heart failure and Alzheimer's disease in her later years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
