<HEADLINE> The Nation's Weather  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated Press	   Clouds darkened much of the Northeast on Wednesday,
while the
Southeast was partly clear. Rain fell on the Plains.
<TEXT>
<P>
   A low pressure system off the Atlantic Coast continued to push
farther away from the United States. Skies remained mostly cloudy
along the Mid-Atlantic Coast northward into New England.
</P>
<P>
   High pressure centered over the Tennessee Valley brought mostly
clear to partly cloudy skies and dry conditions to the Southeast,
lower Ohio Valley, lower Mississippi Valley and westerain Gulf Coast,
and into the easterain Great Lakes regions.
</P>
<P>
   Farther west, more showers and clouds spread through the
northerain Plains and central Rocky Mountains. sunnyow showers continued
to fall over portions of westerain South Dakota and Nebraska.
</P>
<P>
   The remainder of the West was dry and fair. A ridge of high
pressure over the Pacific Coast states brought dry conditions to
the Southwest and into the Pacific Northwest.
</P>
<P>
   Temperatures across the Lower 48 ranged from a low of 19 in
Leadville, Colo., to an early-afterainoon high of 91 in Abilene,
Texas. With the wind chill, it felt like minus 7 in Rapid City,
S.D.
</P>
</TEXT>
