<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-19 18:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Passage rate high, turnout low in 2000 New Jersey school elections  </HEADLINE>
By KATHLEEN CANNON, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON (AP) -- Voters, at least those who showed up, approved a
record rate of school budgets, state education officials said
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday's passage rate was its highest ever, but voter turnout
continued to lag around New Jersey, according to statistics
released by the Department of Education.
</P>
<P>
   This year's 88 percent pass rate surpassed the previous high of
86.5 percent in 1985, and represents the highest rate since records
were first kept in 1977.
</P>
<P>
   But only 12.5 percent of registered voters turned out to select
school board members and decide the fate of 553 school budgets that
carry an estimated total value of $14 billion, according to
education officials.
</P>
<P>
   Education Commissioner David Hespe attributed the high pass rate
to the state's strong economy and to an increase in state aid for
New Jersey's public schools.
</P>
<P>
   But he was disappointed at the low turnout, which may have been
dampened by Tuesday's rainy weather.
</P>
<P>
   He said voter turnout was at an ''unacceptably low level.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Too many citizens choose each year not to participate in the
annual school elections. When more people vote, we have a sharper
view of how they wish to spend local taxes on their schools.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the base budgets, voters approved 74.3 percent,
or 81 of 109, of so-called second ballot questions. The questions
ask voters to approve appropriations for specific items whose costs
exceed state growth limits.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Belluscio, a spokesman for the New Jersey School Boards
Association agreed with Hespe that the healthy economy led most
voters to pull ''yes'' levers.
</P>
<P>
   ''Undeniably the economy played a role. The whole climate makes
people open to public spending,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Voters also responded to tighter budgets, Belluscio said. About
83 percent of the budgets were proposed below state spending
limits, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''School boards learned a lot during the lean years of the early
1990s when taxpayers were feeling the pinch,'' he said. ''Districts
are holding the line and voters realized that.''
</P>
<P>
   Hespe and Gov. Christie Whitman renewed their call for school
elections to be moved to November, at the same time as the general
election. Supporters say such a move would generate greater voter
interest and participation.
</P>
<P>
   ''Local tax rates and the quality of education are too important
to be left up to a tiny minority of voters,'' Whitman said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
