<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-19 18:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bush Won't Attend N.Y. Fund Raiser  </HEADLINE>
By MARC HUMBERT, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) -- The head of New York's Conservative Party
said Wednesday that George W. Bush will not attend its May 17
fund-raiser where he was to have been the main speaker.
</P>
<P>
   Party Chairman Michael Long blamed the change on a scheduling
conflict. He had announced last month that Bush would attend the
annual dinner.
</P>
<P>
   Long also said the change was unrelated to a rift between him
and New York Mayor Rudolph Giuliani, Bush's favored candidate in
the New York Senate race with Hillary Rodham Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   He said Karl Rove, a top Bush adviser, had assured him that
Bush, the presumptive Republican presidential nominee, would attend
a Conservative Party event in June or July.
</P>
<P>
   ''We are considering a later date. We're taking a look at the
schedule,'' said Bush campaign spokeswoman Mindy Tucker.
</P>
<P>
   Long is courting alternatives to Giuliani to run on the
Conservative Party line in large part because of the mayor's
support for abortion rights. No Republican has won statewide office
in New York without Conservative Party backing since 1974. Unlike
other states, New York allows major party candidates to also run on
third-party ballot lines and add all of the votes.
</P>
<P>
   But the Conservative Party dinner presents several problems for
Bush.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to helping raise money that the party could use to
back another candidate over Giuliani, the dinner comes as Bush is
seeking to move toward the political middle in preparation for the
general election against Vice President Al Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Long said none of that would keep Bush away.
</P>
<P>
   Not having the Conservative Party line could complicate things
for Bush in the state. Democrats enjoy a 5-to-3 edge in enrollment
and no GOP presidential candidate has carried the state since
Ronald Reagan in 1980 and 1984.
</P>
</TEXT>
