<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fuel Costs Hit Airlines Earnings  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated Press	   Higher fuel costs dragged down earnings at major air
carriers in
the first quarter, but UAL Corp. reported a slight increase in
operating profits on a jump in passenger traffic. Trans World
Airlines reported a wider operating loss and America West had lower
earnings. Meanwhile, American Airlines bounced back from a
troubling quarter a year ago that was hurt by a pilot job action.
UAL Corp.:
<TEXT>
<P>
   A surge of passengers last month enabled United Airlines' parent
company, UAL Corp., to post a 2 percent increase in operating
profits in the first quarter despite a jump in fuel costs.
</P>
<P>
   The 10 percent jump in passenger revenue in March compared with
a year ago resulted in earnings that exceeded Wall Street
expectations. Shares in the Chicago-based carrier rose 2 percent,
$1.37{ a share, to $58.12{ in trading at 4:30 p.m. on the New York
Stock Exchange.
</P>
<P>
   Excluding one-time charges and certain compensation expenses,
the world's largest airline earned $191 million, or $1.61 per
share, up from $187 million, or $1.54 per share, in the
year-earlier period. Analysts surveyed by First Call/Thomson
Financial had pegged earnings at $1.37 a share.
</P>
<P>
   Revenues grew 9 percent to $4.55 billion from $4.16 billion
thanks to the late-quarter rise in passengers and higher fares, an
industrywide move aimed at compensating for fuel costs that rose 37
percent due to higher crude oil prices.
</P>
<P>
   Counting the effects of a $209 million accounting charge and
other one-off items, UAL posted a net loss of $99 million or $1.18
a share. In the same period a year ago, the company reported net
earnings of $78 million, or 44 cents a share.
</P>
<P>
   Candace Browning, an analyst for Merrill Lynch, called UAL's
showing ''spectacular.''
</P>
<P>
   ''The revenue growth was stronger than anyone expected,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   United does face some daunting challenges in the near future,
however. Separate negotiations with both its pilots and machinists
are expected to result in sharply higher wages and mean United is
likely to have significantly greater labor costs than its
competitors this year.
</P>
<P>
   United also finished last in a recent annual ranking of airline
quality based on consumer complaints to the U.S. Department of
Transportation.
Trans World Airlines Inc.:
</P>
<P>
   Light traffic over the New Year's period and rising fuel costs
resulted in a wider first-quarter loss at TWA.
</P>
<P>
   TWA posted a net loss of $76.1 million or $1.16 a share versus
$21.6 million or 42 cents a share in the same period a year ago.
Revenues rose to $809 million from $765 million.
</P>
<P>
   ''Like our competitors, TWA also was heavily impacted by
increased fuel costs in the quarter,'' president William F. Compton
said. ''However, we recently have seen improvement in our revenue,
including improved yield, largely due to more efficient utilization
of our revitalized fleet and changes in our route structure.''
</P>
<P>
   Passenger revenue, which accounts for the vast majority of the
company's revenue, rose to $723.6 million, up from $681.1 million
in the first quarter last year. But TWA's fuel costs rose to $140.4
million, up from $72.6 million last year.
</P>
<P>
   The airline, with hubs in St. Louis and at New York's Kennedy
Airport, has not turned an annual profit since 1988. In 1999, TWA
lost $353.4 million, or $5.58 per share.
</P>
<P>
   TWA shares were unchanged at $1.87{ at 4:30 p.m. on the American
Stock Exchange.
America West Holdings Corp.:
</P>
<P>
   America West reported a 44 percent drop in first-quarter
earnings due to higher fuel prices and operating problems early in
the year.
</P>
<P>
   The Tempe, Ariz.-based America West Holdings Corp., parent
company of the airline and a travel package arm called The Leisure
Co., reported earnings of $14.6 million, or 40 cents a share, in
the three months ending March 31, compared with $25.9 million, or
63 cents a share, during the same period in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the 71 percent increase in fuel costs, America West
Airlines also suffered two major problems that forced flight
cancelations and other delays.
</P>
<P>
   The airline was forced to cancel more than 280 flights on Feb.
17 and Feb. 18 and stranded hundreds of passengers after its
automated flight management system shut down for five hours. The
computer system provides flight plans, weather reports and other
information for flight crews.
</P>
<P>
   Passengers stuck at airports overnight also complained about the
treatment they received from airline employees. The airline
eventually took out full page ads to apologize to its customers.
</P>
<P>
   In the first week of March, unusually severe storms in Phoenix,
one of the airline's hubs, and bad weather in other key markets
forced the cancelation of another 270 flights and additional
delays.
</P>
<P>
   Revenues rose to $563 million compared with $520 million.
</P>
<P>
   America West shares rose 50 cents to $15 in trading at 4:30 p.m.
on the New York Stock Exchange.
US Airways Group:
</P>
<P>
   Higher fuel costs coupled with labor problems with flight
attendants led to a $218 million net loss at US Airways in the
first quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Excluding a one-time charge related to accounting for revenues
from frequent flyer partners, the Arlington, Va.-based carrier lost
$115 million, or $1.72 per share. US Airways earned $46 million, or
56 cents per share, in the same period a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Revenues edged up 1.7 percent to $2.1 billion from $2.07
billion.
</P>
<P>
   President and chief executive Rakesh Gangwal said the company
had put its problems ''largely behind us.''
</P>
<P>
   The cost of aviation fuel during the first quarter rose from
43.27 cents per gallon last year to 88.81 cents per gallon this
year, causing fuel costs for the quarter to shoot up to $274
million from $129 million.
</P>
<P>
   The airline, the nation's sixth-largest, concluded a lengthy
labor dispute with its 10,000 flight attendants last month,
averting a strike and potential shutdown. The number of passengers
dropped 1.5 percent for the quarter, largely because of uncertainty
over whether the airline would shut down.
</P>
<P>
   Negotiators agreed to a five-year contract on March 25. Flight
attendants vote May 1 on the agreement, which would guarantee
raises totaling 10 percent. The airline said the agreement would
bring labor costs in line with major competitors.
</P>
<P>
   Company shares rose $2.06\, or 8 percent, to $27.62{ in trading
at 4:30 p.m. on the New York Stock Exchange.
AMR Corp.:
</P>
<P>
   AMR Corp., parent of American Airlines, said Wednesday that
stronger ticket sales and higher prices raised first-quarter
profits from continuing operations.
</P>
<P>
   The Fort Worth-based airline indicated that its jet fuel costs
soared 58.5 percent to $553 million from a year ago, but officials
said they avoided even greater increases by buying fuel at lower
prices under advance-purchase deals.
</P>
<P>
   Profit figures looked especially good by comparison with losses
a year ago, when American lost an estimated $225 million in the
first quarter last year when a sickout by disgruntled pilots caused
the cancellation of about 6,600 flights.
</P>
<P>
   AMR said it earned $89 million, or 57 cents a share, from
continuing operations in the first quarter, beating the 40 cents
per share expected by analysts surveyed by First Call/Thomson
Financial.
</P>
<P>
   The company restated its year-ago earnings to exclude earnings
from Sabre Holdings Corp., a travel-reservation system that AMR
spun off to shareholders on March 15. The restated year-ago
earnings showed a loss of $2 million, or 1 cent per share, on
continuing operations.
</P>
<P>
   Including discontinued operations and one-time items, AMR earned
$132 million, or 89 cents per share, down from $158 million, or 99
cents per share in the year-ago period.
</P>
<P>
   AMR, which also operates the American Eagle commuter carrier,
said revenues were $4.58 billion, up 14.2 percent from $4 billion a
year ago.
</P>
<P>
   ''What you're really seeing in the numbers is just better
fundamentals from a strong economy, which has led to strong demand
for our product, and a relatively healthy pricing environment,''
said Tom Horton, AMR's chief financial officer and a senior vice
president.
</P>
<P>
   AMR shares were up 62{ cents to $34.50 on the NYSE.
</P>
</TEXT>
