<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-19 19:07 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> DiFrancesco seeks faster preservation on threatened land  </HEADLINE>
By JOHN P. McALPIN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) -- With $5 million on hand, the state could
swoop in and save environmentally sensitive lands that might be
lost in the time it now takes to acquire open space, Senate
President Donald T. DiFrancesco said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   So DiFrancesco proposed a ''quick strike'' fund to cut around
routine procedures and purchase sensitive forests, meadows and
wildlife areas that are facing an immediate threat of being
developed.
</P>
<P>
   DiFrancesco's plan would allow the Department of Environmental
Protection to buy the land without prior approval from the
Legislature. To get that approval now takes six to 18 months,
according to DiFrancesco.
</P>
<P>
   Environmental groups from across the state praised the measure
and joined DiFrancesco, R-Union, at a statehouse news conference to
detail his bill creating the Conservation Action Fund.
</P>
<P>
   ''Not only will this bill save open space and allow government
to work quicker to buy land, it will also save taxpayers money,''
said Jeff Tittle, director of the New Jersey chapter of the Sierra
Club.
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1990s, approximately 6,000 acres of ''critical''
lands went up for sale in the Highlands in the northern part of the
state, and in central New Jersey, Tittle said. But many of the
parcels were sold off before they could be preserved, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Some land was bought by the state and other groups, but by then
property costs were ''two to three times'' the earlier lots, Tittle
said. This fund would allow land to be bought while prices are
still low, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''We need to go out there and buy land to save open space for
future generations,'' Tittle said.
</P>
<P>
   The fund could also be used to enable the state to seize
discount opportunities because of tax auctions or mortgage
forfeiture sales.
</P>
<P>
   ''The only way New Jersey will win the open space race is by
moving forward quickly using the Garden State Preservation Trust
Fund and by adopting new and creative tools like the Conservation
Action Fund,'' said Michele Byers, director of the New Jersey
Conservation Foundation, in a prepared statement.
</P>
<P>
   All lands acquired through this fund must be approved first by
the Garden State Preservation Trust. The trust must also notify
municipalities to collect local input on the purchase, under the
terms of the bill.
</P>
<P>
   Money for the fund comes from the same act that created the
preservation trust.
</P>
<P>
   DiFrancesco said the state must ''maximize, not miss, the
opportunity to conserve and protect our dwindling open space
resources.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-04-19-00 1907 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000419.0193 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-19 19:19 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Reno Back in Hot Seat With Elian  </HEADLINE>
By MICHAEL J. SNIFFEN, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON (AP) -- It was April 19, and Janet Reno was back in
the hot seat Wednesday as a federal appeals court dumped the tough
issue of who cares for 6-year-old Elian Gonzalez back into her lap.
</P>
<P>
   On her first April 19 as attorney general, in 1993, the Branch
Davidian compound near Waco, Texas, burned after an FBI tear gas
assault she ordered; some 80 people died there. Two years later on
the same date, two men angered by Waco bombed the Oklahoma City
federal building, killing 168 in the most deadly terrorist attack
in U.S. history.
</P>
<P>
   Reno was flying to help dedicate a memorial to the Oklahoma City
dead on Wednesday when the 11th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals
ordered her Justice Department to keep Elian in this country while
it considers an appeal by his Miami relatives.
</P>
<P>
   Those relatives are Cuban exiles who fled Fidel Castro. They
have cared for Elian since he was found in the Atlantic last
Thanksgiving after the ship on which his mother escaped from Cuba
sank, carrying her and 10 others to their deaths. Now, the
relatives are defying Reno's order to turn him over to his father,
Juan Miguel Gonzalez, who came to this country to take his son back
to Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   On landing at Oklahoma City, Reno noted that the Justice
Department and Juan Miguel had earlier agreed to keep Elian here
until the appeals court ruled. But the court in Atlanta did not
address the separate, more immediately volatile issue of who has
custody on Elian in the meantime.
</P>
<P>
   ''The court order does not preclude me from placing Elian in his
father's care while he stays in the United States,'' Reno said.
''It does not disagree with my determination; it does not say that
the boy cannot be reunited with his father.''
</P>
<P>
   She and Justice officials ''are still reviewing the court's
decision. ... We are going to consider all our options and take the
course of action that we deem appropriate under the
circumstances.''
</P>
<P>
   There are several options open to Reno, but she gave some clues
to her thinking at her weekly news conference in Washington earlier
in the day.
</P>
<P>
   ''Our major focus has got to be to see that the law is enforced
and that he is returned and reunited'' with his father,'' Reno
said. ''I am dead set and determined to do it the right way, the
safest way, the least violent way and the soonest way I possibly
can under the law.''
</P>
<P>
   She said she was willing to use force to extract the boy from
his great-uncle Lazaro Gonzalez's house and the crowd of hundreds
of angry Cuban exiles surrounding it but only ''when there is no
other alternative.''
</P>
<P>
   Juan Miguel's attorney, Gregory Craig, demanded Wednesday
afternoon that she act immediately to end Elian's stay in what
Craig and a pediatrician working for the government called an
abusive environment.
</P>
<P>
   She could do that now. Aides have described a sketchy plan to
use U.S. marshals and immigration agents in minimum force and
civilian clothes, with no drawn guns to go to the house to get
Elian. But the crowd of exiles motivated by hatred of Castro has
vowed to form a human chain to stop them.
</P>
<P>
   She also could appeal the injunction issued by the three 11th
Circuit judges to the full circuit panel or to the Supreme Court,
but she and Juan Miguel have already agreed to it.
</P>
<P>
   Reno could ask a federal court to reinforce her order to Lazaro
to give up the boy, but she already asked the 11th Circuit to do
that and those three judges declined to get into that question at
this time. Justice officials say her order has the force of law
anyway.
</P>
<P>
   She could also delay acting as she did when Lazaro refused to
obey her order to turn the boy over to immigration officers at 2
p.m. last Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The 11th Circuit encouraged Reno and the Miami relatives to
voluntarily submit their dispute to the court's mediation service.
She could do that or just wait in the hope that time, circumstances
or even a ruling in May by the appeals court change the atmosphere
in the streets around Lazaro's house or persuade Lazaro and his
family to voluntarily relinquish the boy or to negotiate a peaceful
transfer.
</P>
<P>
   She bristled Wednesday when a reporter asked if memory of the
Waco deaths had stayed her hand too long in this case.
</P>
<P>
   ''Each case is different,'' Reno said. ''In Waco, you had people
who had killed federal officers and who had injured others. There's
a lot of difference.''
</P>
<P>
   She also said: ''If the criticism of me is that I'm trying to
avoid that little boy being hurt or being snatched in a way that
can scar him further, I plead guilty. But at the same time ... I'm
going to enforce the law.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
