<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-19 19:44 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Calls Memorial Site 'Sacred'  </HEADLINE>
By TERENCE HUNT, AP White House Correspondent
<TEXT>
<P>
   OKLAHOMA CITY (AP) -- On a day of sad memories, President Clinton
knelt among 168 empty chairs Wednesday memorializing each victim of
the Oklahoma City bombing and declared the site ''sacred ground''
in the soul of America.
</P>
<P>
   ''America is still with you,'' the president said. ''With this
memorial, you can know that America will never forget.''
</P>
<P>
   Five years after the deadliest terrorist attack in U.S. history,
Clinton helped dedicate the Oklahoma City National Memorial at the
site where a bomb ripped off the face of the Alfred P. Murrah
Federal Building and killed 19 children and 149 men and women.
</P>
<P>
   Attorney General Janet Reno, speaking before the president,
said: ''To all the people of Oklahoma City, thank you for showing
America how to stand up to evil, to the evil that spawned that
blast from hell. You have helped us renew our spirit and our love
of this country.''
</P>
<P>
   Where the nine-story building once stood, 168 bronze and stone
chairs stand on glass bases on a grassy slope. Each base is etched
with the name of a victim. The chairs of the 19 children are
smaller than the others.
</P>
<P>
   The memorial is anchored on opposite ends by four-story Gates of
Time, one emblazoned ''9:01'' and the other ''9:03'' for the
moments immediately before and after the 9:02 a.m. bombing. Clinton
gazed across a long, black granite reflecting pool to the 9:03
gateway and knelt to wet his fingers in the water.
</P>
<P>
   He walked among the chairs with relatives of the victims. The
chairs were piled high with flowers, balloons and American flags.
Clinton paused with Jeannine Gist at the chair memorializing her
daughter, Karen Gist Carr. He knelt at another chair and fixed a
toppled bucket of flowers. He also stopped with Doris Jones and
stroked the bronze back of a chair honoring her daughter, Carrie
Anne Lenz and her unborn child.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd assembled at the memorial ceremony cheered when
Clinton arrived but the mood of the event was somber. Police
officers turned down the volume of their radios. The invocation,
however, was interrupted by a siren from a nearby street that
blared like those that sounded for hours the day of the bombing.
</P>
<P>
   ''There are places in our national landscape so scarred by
freedom's sacrifice that they shape forever the soul of America,''
the president said. ''Valley Forge. Gettysburg. Selma. This place
is such sacred ground.''
</P>
<P>
   Remembering the victims, Clinton said, ''Five years ago, the
cowards who killed them made a choice -- a choice to attack this
building and the people in it because they wanted to strike a blow
at America's heartland -- at the core of our nation's being. This
was an attack on all America and every American.''
</P>
<P>
   Timothy McVeigh and Terry Nichols were convicted in federal
court in the attack. McVeigh has been sentenced to death; Nichols
is serving a life sentence.
</P>
<P>
   ''Five years later,'' Clinton said, ''we are here because you
made a choice -- a choice to choose hope and love over despair and
hatred. ... I know there are still days when the old anger wells up
inside you, still days when tears fill your eyes, when you think
your heart will surely break.
</P>
<P>
   ''On those days in the future, I hope you can come here and find
solace in the memory of your loved ones and the honor of your
fellow citizens,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ''I hope you can find the strength to live a full and loving
life, free of hatred which only cripples. I believe your loved ones
would want you to have that life,'' the president said. ''And
though you have given too much, you still have so much to give.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said that ''we may never have all the answers to what
happened here. But as we continue our journey toward understanding,
one truth is clear: What was meant to break (us) has made you
stronger.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
