<BODY>
<HEADLINE> State cracks down on campaign accounts for omitting keyinformation  </HEADLINE>
By RALPH SIEGEL, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. (AP) -- In campaign fund-raising, the big money is
the soft money. The big money also is the area ripest for abuse.
</P>
<P>
   And in the past 10 months, the state agency charged with
monitoring fund-raising and the integrity of public reports on soft
money has started to crack down on the political committees that
collect it, fining them $35,900 for failing to give complete
information about what their donors do for a living.
</P>
<P>
   Soft money contributions are given to a political party rather
than to an individual candidate, and the normal limit of $1,800 a
year does not apply.
</P>
<P>
   A 1993 New Jersey law made an attempt to at least control soft
money, which at the federal level flows without limit or
accountability. The state law allowed the political parties to each
form three fund-raising committees, six total, and it capped
donations on a scale that currently is $30,000 a year.
</P>
<P>
   But this cap is more of a loophole than a rule. Someone wishing
to donate to the GOP, for instance, has three committees to choose
from and can give $30,000 to each. Then the person's spouse and
children can donate.
</P>
<P>
   It is legally possible for a single donor with the help of a
spouse and child to give $180,000 a year -- and then create a
political fund that gives even more to the same committees. That's
not even including business partners or employees.
</P>
<P>
   So far no one has needed all that many loopholes. ELEC's recent
penalties covered donations received in 1995 and 1996, a period
when the most generous donor, financier Finn Casperson and his
family, gave $148,000 to Republicans over two years.
</P>
<P>
   The committee fined most recently is the most affluent of them
all, the campaign account operated by the Republican State
Committee, ordered last week to pay $10,950. By agreeing to pay
early and not to appeal, they got a $2,175 discount.
</P>
<P>
   The largest fine to be handed down came in October when the
Democratic State Committee was fined $15,175. ELEC forgave $3,160
for settlement and early payment.
</P>
<P>
   All of the violations were for essentially the same thing --
providing partial information that in fact rendered the contributor
reports relatively meaningless. The parties' lawyers called them
all trivial oversights not worth the cost or bother to file an
appeal, but ELEC director Frederick Herrmann and other experts on
campaign finance did not agree.
</P>
<P>
   ''It is important for the public to understand where the money
is coming from and where it is going,'' Herrmann said. ''They are
bringing money in from private interests and the public has a right
to know that.''
</P>
<P>
   ELEC in the past issued hundreds of fines mainly against small,
local violators for such things as failing to file reports or
filing them late. The agency has been criticized for ignoring the
big soft-money committees even after news organizations, including
The Associated Press, reported on significant patterns of
violations.
</P>
<P>
   On the national scene, no one watches the ebb and flow of
political money more closely than the nonpartisan, nonprofit Center
for Responsive Politics. Its director, Larry Makinson, applauded
the New Jersey agency for taking a step regulators of the Federal
Elections Commission appear reluctant to take.
</P>
<P>
   ''It would be shocking if the FEC ever did something as
aggressive as that,'' Makinson said. ''It brings attention to the
problem. If party committees are not fully identifying their
donors, the people can't track who the politicians are thankful to.
That is absolutely essential.''
</P>
<P>
   Omitting occupational details or employer addresses ''is not
trivial,'' Makinson said. ''If you don't have disclosure, full
disclosure, you don't have anything. ... This money is not given
free and clear. This money is given often with expectation of
something in return.''
</P>
<P>
   Herrmann denied that his agency has been sluggish. ''We have
always paid attention to them. There is a tremendous amount to
review in those committees. We are talking about millions and
millions of dollars,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And while ELEC is traditionally quiet about its investigations
and does not publicize its enforcement actions, Herrmann
acknowledged this scrutiny of these largest of all campaign
committees shall continue. ''In many ways those committees, because
of the amounts of money that are being raised, will be ones the
commission is always looking at,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   This year the state fund-raising issue is secondary as the focus
is on federal elections, although the state committees can do
so-called ''party building'' work and spend money on county and
local candidates in ways that also help congressional candidates.
</P>
<P>
   But in 2001, with the governor and the full Senate and Assembly
up for re-election in new districts adjusted by the census, it is
hard to envision an issue more crucial than this.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
