<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-19 20:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Annan: UN May Fortify Lebanon Force  </HEADLINE>
By EDITH M. LEDERER, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- Secretary-General Kofi Annan said
Wednesday the United Nations may need to strengthen its
peacekeeping force in southern Lebanon to monitor the Israeli
pullout in early July.
</P>
<P>
   He told reporters he is sending his Middle East envoy, Terje
Roed Larsen, to Syria, Lebanon, Jordan, Egypt and Israel next week
to discuss the withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
   The Security Council on Wednesday held private discussions on a
statement which would give Annan the official go-ahead to start
preparing for the pullout.
</P>
<P>
   Israel invaded Lebanon in 1978 and has occupied part of southern
Lebanon since 1985 as a buffer against guerrilla attacks on
northern Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Security Council resolutions call for Israel's withdrawal from
Lebanon and the establishment of a U.N. peacekeeping force to
confirm the pullout. They also call for U.N. troops to restore
peace to the region and help the Lebanese government regain its
authority in southern Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
   Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak has pledged to withdraw
Israeli troops from Lebanon by July, preferably as part of an
agreement with Lebanon and Syria but unilaterally if necessary.
Syria is the main power broker in Lebanon. Talks between Israel and
Syria, however, have stalled since January over Syria's demand for
a total withdrawal from the Golan Heights.
</P>
<P>
   Israel believes the U.N. force, now numbering about 4,500
troops, will be enough to patrol the Israel-Lebanon border if
expanded to its full mandate of 7,000 soldiers, a senior Israeli
official said recently, speaking on condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   But the secretary-general said the United Nations has not
determined how many troops will be needed.
</P>
<P>
   ''We may need to strengthen the force,'' he said. ''We are doing
our contingency planning. We will factor in the information Larsen
brings back and then make proposals to the council.''
</P>
<P>
   Israel officially informed the United Nations of its planned
withdrawal by July 7 on Monday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
