<HEADLINE> Lawmaker Appeals for Innocent Iraqis  </HEADLINE>
By HASSAN ABDULWAHAB, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   BASRA, Iraq (AP) -- A U.S. lawmaker assessing the impact of U.N.
sanctions on Iraq said Wednesday it is important not only to force
Baghdad to give up its weapons of mass destruction but also to do
more to ease the hardships on ordinary Iraqis.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Tony Hall, D-Ohio, did not call for a lifting of sanctions
imposed on Iraq for its 1990 invasion of Kuwait, but said the
United Nations should make sure that sanctions do not hurt innocent
Iraqis.
</P>
<P>
   ''It was very, very important'' to compel Iraq to rid itself of
weapons of mass destruction so that ''it cannot use or export them
to other countries,'' he told Associated Press Television News.
</P>
<P>
   But he insisted the international community can do a much better
job in helping Iraq deal with its economic and health problems.
</P>
<P>
   One way would be to speed up the flow of health supplies and
other urgent commodities to the country under a U.N. humanitarian
program, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Iraq says the United States and Britain hold up delivery of
needed supplies, using their clout in the United Nations. The U.S.
government says it wants to ensure that Iraq is not buying items
that appear to be humanitarian in nature but that could be used for
making weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Iraq claims about 1.2 million people, including 750,000 children
under age 5, have died during the last 10 years, and blames the
deaths on shortages caused by sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   The United States says President Saddam Hussein could have
avoided the hardships by helping U.N. weapons inspectors eliminate
all illegal weapons -- a primary condition laid down by the U.N.
Security Council for lifting the sanctions.
</P>
<P>
   Hall said he agreed that Iraq should give up its weapons of mass
destruction, the global community should ''do a much better (job)
in helping the people here that are hurting.''
</P>
<P>
   ''In the 1970s and 1980s malnutrition was not in this country.
They did not have cholera. They did not have bad water. They had an
infrastructure that was decent,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Hall, who is on a four-day tour of Iraq, spent two days in the
south, visiting several cities including Basra, which bore the
brunt of Iraq's 1980-88 war with Iran and the 1991 Persian Gulf War
over Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
   Visiting a maternity and children's hospital in the southern
city of Babylon on Tuesday, he saw first hand the overcrowding in
the hospital where many beds were shared by two children. Doctors
told him about the rampant malnutrition among the children admitted
at the hospital.
</P>
<P>
   ''The world can do much better with Iraq healthwise, toward the
economy ... with the children. It is very hard to see children that
are malnourished,'' Hall said.
</P>
<P>
   Hall said he will report his findings to Congress. He is
scheduled to leave Thursday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
