<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-19 20:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Gephardt To Oppose China Trade Bill  </HEADLINE>
By DAVID SCOTT, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS (AP) -- House Minority Leader Dick Gephardt said
Wednesday he will speak on the floor and one-on-one with House
members about his opposition to a bill granting permanent
normalized trade relations with China.
</P>
<P>
   ''I have been talking to members about this issue,'' Gephardt,
D-Mo., said in formally announcing his plan to vote against the
measure. ''I've been telling them what I think about the issue and
will continue to do that actively.''
</P>
<P>
   Gephardt's opposition to the bill puts him at odds with the
White House, Republican Congressional leaders hoping for a
bipartisan vote, and the presumptive presidential nominees of both
parties, Vice President Al Gore and Texas Gov. George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   In his 25-minute speech to supporters, Gephardt said the United
States should not trust the Chinese government to improve human
rights practices on its own.
</P>
<P>
   Voting annually to grant China trading rights that the U.S.
extends to almost every other country ''is the best single yearly
spotlight on the behavior of the Chinese government,'' Gephardt
said.
</P>
<P>
   A House vote on the issue is expected to be close when it's
taken next month.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, Commerce Secretary William Daley said the
administration is ''hopeful'' that Gephardt's statements won't
discourage other House Democrats from supporting the trade deal.
</P>
<P>
   ''There should be no sort of litmus test for Democrats on this
issue,'' Daley said.
</P>
<P>
   When word of Gephardt's decision became public earlier in the
week, a Democratic official said Gephardt wasn't expected to join a
full-fledged effort to defeat it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
