<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Seeks to Improve Turkey Ties  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANKARA, Turkey (AP) -- Turkey and China have agreed to fight
terrorism and religious extremists, Chinese President Jiang Zemin
said Wednesday during a visit punctuated by protests over China's
treatment of a minority group related to the Turkish.
</P>
<P>
   ''Both sides ... will oppose every kind of international
terrorism, separatism and extreme religious forces,'' Jiang said
after a meeting with President Suleyman Demirel.
</P>
<P>
   While ultra-nationalist Turks loudly criticized China's
treatment of its Muslim Uighur minority, Turkish leaders eager to
boost trade ties with China, expressed their concerns more demurely
behind closed doors.
</P>
<P>
   Uighurs and Turks share a common cultural root and both practice
Islam. They speak similar languages.
</P>
<P>
   Demirel told Jiang the Uighur minority should be ''a bridge
between Turkey and China,'' the semiofficial Anatolia news agency
reported.
</P>
<P>
   Also Wednesday, Demirel awarded Jiang the country's highest
decoration at a ceremony during which Turkish opera stars sang
famous arias.
</P>
<P>
   As a thank-you gesture, Jiang sang the traditional Neapolitan
song ''O Sole Mio'' to the delight and surprise of Demirel and
other guests who burst into an applause.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, a right-wing party and dozens of civic groups,
including an association of Uigher immigrants from China's
far-northwestern region of Xinjiang protested the government's
hospitality to Jiang.
</P>
<P>
   ''We violently denounce in the name of humanity ... this
government which is putting us through this undeserved shame,''
said Okkes Semdiller, deputy head of the marginal far-right Great
Unity Party. The party laid a black wreath near the prime
minister's office in protest of plans to honor Jiang with the
medal.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, Muslim separatist groups, mostly Uighurs resentful of
Chinese domination, rioted and fought gun battles with Chinese
police in Xinjiang.
</P>
<P>
   Uighur immigrants have held several protests in Turkey to
denounce Chinese crackdowns on Muslims during the riots. Police
increased security for Jiang's visit, with hundreds of policemen
lining the roads to the presidential palace in the capital.
</P>
<P>
   Jiang oversaw the signing of energy and trade agreements for
increased cooperation on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Demirel said they would also seek ways to boost two-way trade
which stands at $930 million a year.
</P>
<P>
   ''The economic and trade ties between the two countries are far
below their economic potentials,'' Demirel said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
