<HEADLINE> Cyclone Buffets Northwest Australia  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   PERTH, Australia (AP) -- Trees were uprooted and roofs blown off
houses in towns in northwestern Australia Thursday as Cyclone
Rosita swept through the region. No injuries were reported.
</P>
<P>
   The Outback town of Broome was buffeted by heavy rain and winds
gusts up to 118 mph as the storm passed early Thursday morning.
</P>
<P>
   The cyclone began to weaken soon after moving inland from the
Indian Ocean.
</P>
<P>
   ''There was a lot of noise, a lot of rain ... we've experienced
a lot of trees being blown around,'' said Graeme Down, a spokesman
for the Western Australia state emergency services in Broome.
</P>
<P>
   Residents reported that a handful of roofs in the town had
either been blown off or damaged by falling trees, Down said.
</P>
<P>
   The Bureau of Meteorology said Rosita was moving east-southeast
at 12 mph and steadily weakening as it headed inland.
</P>
<P>
   Residents in the path of the storm were advised to batten down
and prepare for heavy rain, Down said.
</P>
</TEXT>
