<HEADLINE> Thumbnail Sketches of Elian Judges  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated Press	   Thumbnail sketches of three 11th U.S. Circuit Court
of Appeals
judges who ruled Wednesday in Elian Gonzalez case.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Judge James Larry Edmondson, 52, of Atlanta, was appointed by
President Reagan to the court in 1986. He graduated from Emory
University in 1968 and from law school at the University of Georgia
in 1971. Edmondson taught at the school for nine years and had a
private practice for 13 years. He directed Reagan's 1984
re-election campaign in Gwinnett County.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   Judge Joel F. Dubina, 52, of Montgomery, Ala., was appointed by
President Bush in 1990. He graduated from the University of Alabama
in 1970 and Cumberland School of Law in 1973. Dubina was a clerk
for a federal judge in Alabama until 1974. He was in private
practice until he was appointed a federal magistrate in Alabama in
1983. Reagan appointed him federal judge in 1986.
</P>
<P>
   ------
</P>
<P>
   Judge Charles R. Wilson, 45, of Tampa, Fla., was appointed by
President Clinton in May 1999. He graduated from law school in 1979
at the University of Notre Dame, where he also earned a bachelor's
degree. Wilson worked briefly as an assistant attorney in
Hillsborough County, Fla., then worked for a year for a federal
appeals court judge. He practiced law in Florida until his 1986
appointment to the circuit court bench. In 1990, he was named a
federal magistrate and in 1994, he became U.S. attorney for the
Middle District of Florida.
</P>
</TEXT>
