<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-19 22:22 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Poll: Lima Confident in Fujimori  </HEADLINE>
By RICK VECCHIO, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   LIMA, Peru (AP) -- Residents of this capital city consider
President Alberto Fujimori more capable of creating jobs, improving
education and promoting business than runoff challenger Alejandro
Toledo, a poll showed Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The vision of Fujimori as the man who can deliver undercuts
Toledo's promise to generate employment and combat poverty, the
foundation of a presidential bid that threatens to end Fujimori's
10-year tenure.
</P>
<P>
   The two will face off in an upcoming runoff vote after Fujimori
fell just short of the majority necessary to claim an unprecedented
third term in the April 9 election, which was riddled with
irregularities and accusations of fraud.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Toledo's strong showing, the poll of Lima voters by the
private firm Apoyo showed the 61-year-old president outpacing -- in
most cases by a wide margin -- his 54-year-old challenger in nearly
a dozen categories measuring ability to govern.
</P>
<P>
   The poll surveyed 512 Lima residents between April 14 and 16 and
had a margin of error of 4.5 percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   The Apoyo poll showed 51 percent of those surveyed consider
Fujimori a hard worker, compared to 30 percent for Toledo.
</P>
<P>
   While most Peruvians consider lack of jobs the single most
important campaign issue, 45 percent of those polled said Fujimori
would be capable of generating employment, compared to 39 percent
for Toledo, a former World Bank official.
</P>
<P>
   And 49 percent said Fujimori would be capable of promoting
investment, while only 37 percent said Toledo could reinvigorate
Peru's stagnant business climate.
</P>
<P>
   Fifty-three percent said Fujimori would improve education,
compared to 34 percent for Toledo.
</P>
<P>
   The poll showed Toledo's strongest overall support coming from
the more affluent sectors, with most people listing his
professional work and training as his greatest asset. Among the
middle class he has 60 percent support to Fujimori's 32 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Most of those supporting Fujimori said he had earned their vote
by defeating leftist rebels, building schools, hospitals and roads
and providing economic assistance to the poorest segments of Peru's
society.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
