<BODY>
<HEADLINE> McCain Backs S.C. Flag Removal  </HEADLINE>
By JIM DAVENPORT, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMBIA, S.C. (AP) -- U.S. Sen. John McCain said Wednesday the
Confederate flag should be lowered from South Carolina's
Statehouse, apologizing for not saying so during the Republican
presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ''I feared that if I answered honestly, I could not win the
South Carolina primary. So I chose to compromise my principles. I
broke my promise to always tell the truth,'' the Arizona Republican
said at a South Carolina Policy Council luncheon.
</P>
<P>
   McCain and his rival, Texas Gov. George W. Bush, were questioned
repeatedly on the issue during the campaign in February, and both
said they considered it an issue best decided by South Carolinians.
Bush won the primary with 53 percent of the vote.
</P>
<P>
   A month earlier, the National Association for the Advancement of
Colored People had begun a tourism boycott of the state, saying the
flag was a symbol of hate. Flag supporters say it represents the
state's heritage.
</P>
<P>
   In his speech Wednesday, McCain said the flag ''should be
removed from your Capitol, and I am encouraged that fair-minded
people on both sides of the issue are working hard to define an
honorable compromise.''
</P>
<P>
   At the time of the primary, McCain said his ancestors had
''fought honorably'' on the side of the Confederacy. On Wednesday,
he said they ''fought on the wrong side of American history.''
</P>
<P>
   Reaction among some former McCain supporters was swift.
</P>
<P>
   ''He lied to me,'' said state Rep. Jake Knotts, R-Lexington, a
Confederate flag supporter. Knotts was among the South Carolina
Republicans, along with U.S. Reps. Lindsey Graham and Mark Sanford,
who broke from the party leadership and supported McCain.
</P>
<P>
   But McCain also won praise.
</P>
<P>
   ''He didn't have to come, he didn't have to say it,'' said Sam
Tenenbaum, a prominent Columbia Democrat who contributed to
McCain's campaign.
</P>
<P>
   During the campaign, McCain drew parallels with Arizona's
struggle to adopt a holiday recognizing the Rev. Martin Luther King
Jr. He said he supported the King holiday, but ''didn't like it
when people came in from other states to try and tell us in Arizona
how we would solve our problems and I don't intend to involve
myself in this controversy'' about the flag.
</P>
<P>
   South Carolina's Legislature is debating the flag's fate. A
Senate-passed plan to move it to a monument on Statehouse grounds
is likely to face tougher going in the House.
</P>
<P>
   Graham this week invited McCain and Bush to meet in South
Carolina and resolve their differences over the issue. The meeting
''would be a unifying event for our state party and would send a
good signal nationally,'' Graham said.
</P>
<P>
   McCain accepted the offer. Bush campaign spokesman Scott
McClellan said Bush had just received Graham's letter.
</P>
<P>
   The hope is ''to help heal the wounds of the South Carolina
primary and to show that we're a unified party,'' said Graham
spokesman Kevin Bishop. He said Graham suggested a date sometime
between a scheduled May 9 Bush-McCain meeting in Pittsburgh and the
Republican National Convention that begins July 31 in Philadelphia.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-19-00 2223 </TRAILER>
