<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Quotes From Okla. Bombing Memorial  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated Press	   Some quotes from people who attended the dedication
of the
Oklahoma City National Memorial on Wednesday on the site of the
April 19, 1995, federal building bombing:
<TEXT>
<P>
   ''I just want people to remember what happened here and the 168
people that were killed. If we forget this, we are losing
something.'' -- Richard Williams, former assistant building manager
for the Alfred P. Murrah Federal Building.
</P>
<P>
   ''As the Governor said in alluding to Gettysburg, there are
places in our national landscape so scarred by freedom's sacrifice
that they shape forever the soul of America -- Valley Forge,
Gettysburg, Selma. This place is such sacred ground.'' -- President
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ''This memorial, like this community, will always stand for
justice. Justice is that deep and abiding peace that comes when
wrong is righted and when hurt begins to heal.'' -- Attorney General
Janet Reno.
</P>
<P>
   ''This wouldn't be something we would come to every day. Our
parents tried to teach us to get on with our lives. To me, my
parents aren't there.'' -- Gwen Battle, who lost her parents, Calvin
and Peola Battle, in the bombing.
</P>
<P>
   ''You could have chosen to grieve very privately but instead you
chose to take a stand against terrorism, and to raise a lasting
tribute to those who perished, for the survivors who have suffered
the horror of the last five years and to all the courageous who
came from near and far to our aid.'' -- Robert M. Johnson, chairman
of the Oklahoma City Memorial Trust.
</P>
<P>
   ''In a face of evil that staggers the soul, you've demonstrated
the triumph of the human spirit.'' -- Attorney General Janet Reno.
</P>
<P>
   ''We bring with us our broken hearts and shattered dreams. We
know our hearts would have no rainbows if our eyes had no tears.
... Do not allow us to lose ourselves from the horror of this
terrorist attack on our government.'' -- Jack Poe, Oklahoma City
Police Chaplain.
</P>
<P>
   ''In a time of unspeakable horror and tragedy, where else is
there to turn but to turn to God?'' -- Gov. Frank Keating, following
a noon Mass at St. Joseph's Cathedral, which had its windows blown
out by the bomb. He was speaking about the response of people of
all faiths to the blast.
</P>
<P>
   ''By this memorial, we are saying that evil will not defeat
good. We are saying that good will defeat evil.'' -- Sen. Don
Nickles, R-Okla.
</P>
<P>
   ''When I got down here this morning, the moon was still up, the
clouds were in the sky and it reflected in the water. It was like
heaven was right here.'' -- Marsha Kight, mother of Frankie Merrell
who died in the bombing.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think it is a tribute to all the victims of terrorism. It is
more than just the 168 people here. The memorial stands for the
people in embassies in Beirut and Africa ... Lockerbie, Scotland,
and even the children in Columbine.'' -- Tom Kight, stepfather of
Frankie Merrell, who died in the bombing.
</P>
<P>
   ''I know there are still days when the old anger wells up inside
you; still days when tears fill your eyes, when you think your
heart will surely break. On those days in the future, I hope you
can come here and find solace in the memory of your loved ones, in
the honor of your fellow citizens. -- President Clinton.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
