<HEADLINE> Actors Strike Against Advertisers  </HEADLINE>
By DAVID GERMAIN, AP Entertainment Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES (AP) -- TV and radio audiences may catch more
commercial repeats as actors strike against advertisers, though
negotiators for ad agencies said Wednesday that consumers will
notice little difference in the sales pitches they see and hear.
</P>
<P>
   Board members for the Screen Actors Guild and American
Federation of Television and Radio Artists finalized strike plans
Tuesday night over what the unions say are unfair wage proposals
from advertisers.
</P>
<P>
   The unions, which have a combined membership of 135,000 actors,
authorized a strike beginning 12:01 a.m. May 1. Their commercial
contracts with the American Association of Advertising Agencies and
Association of National Advertisers expired March 31.
</P>
<P>
   John McGuinn, chief negotiator for advertisers, said the
associations plan to continue business as usual during the strike.
</P>
<P>
   Advertisers have an inventory of fresh commercials and probably
will keep some older spots on the air longer while the walkout
continues, McGuinn said.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think the problem they may have is perhaps in a couple
months where consumers who have probably seen the same ad a few
zillion times may get really turned off,'' said Wayne Friedman, who
covers the ad industry for the trade publication Advertising Age.
</P>
<P>
   Some agencies and producers use non-union actors for
commercials, and other advertisers likely will do the same while
the strike lasts. Some union actors also might continue to work
despite the strike.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm not worried about that,'' said William Daniels, actors
guild president. The contract offer from advertisers would cut into
actors' earnings and ''has so galvanized our unions that we have
never had such a unified membership.''
</P>
<P>
   Actors are pushing for a new pay system on cable-TV ads that
would compensate performers for each time their commercials air.
That system would be similar to the setup for network TV ads.
</P>
<P>
   Advertisers want the opposite, expanding flat-rate wages for
cable commercials to network TV because of shrinking audiences for
broadcast networks. Ad agencies say a proposed increase in flat
rates for cable commercials would more than offset money actors
would lose by scrapping the pay system for network ads.
</P>
<P>
   The two sides have been negotiating since February. No new talks
are scheduled before the strike date.
</P>
<P>
   Actors went on strike over commercial contracts for three weeks
in 1988 and for three months in 1978-79. The strike would not
affect production of feature films or TV shows.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-19-00 2230 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW20000419.0223 </DOCNO>
