<HEADLINE> Mets 3, Brewers 1  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK (AP) -- Rick Reed turned in another sharp start and the
New York Mets beat the Milwaukee Brewers for the seventh straight
time, 3-1 Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets ended Jason Bere's nine-game winning streak, dating
back to Sept. 19, 1998, when he pitched Cincinnati over Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   Reed (2-0), who had no-decisions in two of his first three
starts, has now given up just three earned runs in 29 2-3 innings
this season.
</P>
<P>
   Reed allowed seven hits and struck out six, leaving after James
Mouton opened the eighth with a single.
</P>
<P>
   The night got off to an ominous start for Reed. He was hit on
the thumb of his glove hand by Marquis Grissom's line drive to
start the game, but recovered to throw out the leadoff man.
</P>
<P>
   After brief medical attention, Reed grimaced while making a few
warmup tosses before retiring the side in order.
</P>
<P>
   Armando Benitez pitched the ninth for his sixth save in seven
chances.
</P>
<P>
   Bere (2-1), who spent part of last season on the disabled list
and part of it in the minors, gave up three runs in 5 2-3 innings.
His winning streak was tied for the longest in the majors with
Pedro Martinez of the Red Sox and Pat Mahomes of the Mets.
</P>
<P>
   Geoff Jenkins homered on Reed's first pitch of the seventh,
pulling the Brewers within 3-1. It was Jenkins' fourth homer.
</P>
<P>
   New York took a 1-0 lead in the first inning on Mike Piazza's
RBI groundout, but left the bases loaded when Bere got Jay Payton
to ground into a forceout after two walks.
</P>
<P>
   Derek Bell's RBI single and Edgardo Alfonzo's sacrifice fly made
it 3-0 in the second.
</P>
<P>
Notes: The game started with three umpires when Ed Rapuano,
scheduled to work first base, was caught in traffic. He didn't
arrive until the Mets came to bat in the second inning. ... On
Tuesday night, Mike Hampton -- who had two singles and two walks --
became only the fourth Mets pitcher ever to reach base four times
in a game. Tom Seaver (1967) and Jerry Koosman (1974) both had
three hits and a walk. ... Bere had not lost in 20 consecutive
appearances. He was 3-0 with Cincinnati last season and 2-0 with
the Brewers.
</P>
</TEXT>
