<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-19 22:35 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Syria Softens Rhetoric Over Pullback  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAMASCUS, Syria (AP) -- Syria on Wednesday softened its tone over
a planned Israeli pullout from south Lebanon by July, saying it
hopes that the move would be a prelude to a withdrawal from other
occupied Arab lands.
</P>
<P>
   ''There is still ample time and many gleams of light,'' wrote
Fayez Sayegh, head of Syria's official news agency in an article
published in the government's Al-Thawra newspaper. ''Let the
Israeli withdrawal from south Lebanon be a part of an Israeli
pullout from lands captured in 1967.''
</P>
<P>
   The commentary marks a shift in Syria's reaction to Israel's
planned withdrawal, of which the Jewish state formally notified the
United Nations earlier this week.
</P>
<P>
   The move was initially viewed with skepticism by Syria and its
protege and neighbor Lebanon, with newspapers in Damascus, which
reflect the thinking of the Syrian government, claiming that Israel
was insincere in its pledge to pull out.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's reaction also came a day after Lebanese Prime
Minster Salim Hoss departed from previous statements by not
criticizing the Israeli move, instead hailing it as a victory and a
''crushing defeat for Israel.''
</P>
<P>
   In recent months, Lebanon and Syria had said that the pullout
must be part of an overall Mideast peace settlement, a prospect
which now appears unlikely to materialize soon with the
Israel-Syria talks deadlocked.
</P>
<P>
   A withdrawal without an Israel-Syria peace accord is likely to
deprive Syria, which maintains about 30,000 troops in Lebanon, of a
bargaining chip -- in the form of pressure on Israel from Lebanese
guerrillas -- in any future talks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-19-00 2235 </TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
