<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-19 22:36 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Milford police officer found guilty in cruiser fatal case  </HEADLINE>
sdfonsy
<TEXT>
<P>
   LITCHFIELD, Conn. (AP) -- A New Milford police officer whose
cruiser struck another car and killed its teen-age driver was found
guilty Wednesday of negligent homicide with a motor vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   The six-member jury deliberated for about 10 hours over two days
before returning the verdict against Officer William Scribner, 39.
He is scheduled to be sentenced on June 14 and faces up to six
months in prison and a $1,000 fine.
</P>
<P>
   Scribner, who lives in Bethel, was convicted in the June 1998
death of Angela D'Aquila.
</P>
<P>
   D'Aquila was killed when Scribner's cruiser, its lights flashing
and siren screaming, raced through a New Milford intersection and
smashed into her car. Caroline LaVoie, 18, a passenger in
D'Aquila's car, suffered a collapsed lung, broken ribs, a fractured
clavicle and a sprained spine.
</P>
<P>
   ''It's definitely been a long 2{ years,'' LaVoie said outside
Litchfield Superior Court. ''I think we're all happy that this is
done and over with and justice is served.''
</P>
<P>
   Scribner was disappointed by the verdict, said his attorney,
John Kelly.
</P>
<P>
   ''Here's a man with 14 years on the job, with an unblemished
record, legitimately responding to an emergency and a tragic
accident occurs and now he's convicted of a motor vehicle
offense,'' Kelly said. ''So he's very disappointed.''
</P>
<P>
   Jury Foreman Wayne Smith said the jury felt Scribner did not use
reasonable care going through the intersection.
</P>
<P>
   ''He was going way too fast,'' Smith said. ''It was with a very
heavy heart that we reached that verdict.''
</P>
<P>
   Scribner was the first Connecticut police officer to be charged
with negligent homicide in the line of duty. His conviction comes
five weeks after former New Milford police Officer Scott Smith was
convicted of manslaughter for fatally shooting an unarmed suspect.
</P>
<P>
   Smith, who is scheduled to be sentenced May 5, originally was
charged with murder -- the first Connecticut police officer ever to
be so charged for an act in the line of duty.
</P>
<P>
   Scribner was responding to a disturbance call when his cruiser
struck D'Aquila's car. Prosecutors charged him after concluding in
a yearlong investigation that he hadn't slowed down before going
through the intersection.
</P>
<P>
   The defense had maintained Scribner followed police procedure.
Scribner's attorney argued that D'Aquila caused the accident by
making an improper left turn into the path of the cruiser.
</P>
<P>
   Scribner, a 13-year police veteran at the time of the crash,
turned down the state's offer to place him on a special one-year
probation, after which his record would have been wiped clean. He
remains free on a promise to appear pending sentencing.
</P>
<P>
   Acting New Milford Police Chief Colin McCormack issued a
statement after the verdict, expressing the department's sympathy
for the victims, but disappointment with the ruling.
</P>
<P>
   ''While we as citizens are disappointed by the jury's decision
to convict Officer Scribner, we as members of a law enforcement
agency must respect and abide by our system of justice,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   McCormack added: ''As a community, we need to be reminded that
our law enforcement officers are constantly thrust into rapidly
evolving and dangerous situations, placing themselves at great
personal jeopardy. Despite this risk, the New Milford Police
Department will persevere, and continue with its mission to provide
a safe environment for all of our citizens.''
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Arthur Peitler could not be reached for comment. Telephone
messages were left for him and the town attorney at Town Hall.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-ES-04-19-00 2236 </TRAILER>
