<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Wednesday's Canada News Briefs  </HEADLINE>
By The Associated PressNote: All dollars are Canadian unless otherwise noted
<TEXT>
<P>
   ----
Ludwig Jailed After Guilty Verdicts in Alberta Oilpatch Vandalism
Trial
</P>
<P>
   EDMONTON, Alberta (AP) -- Wiebo Ludwig is a cunning man who used
an innocent child in a vengeful crusade against the energy
industry, a judge said Wednesday as he convicted and jailed him on
five charges related to vandalism in the northern Alberta oilpatch.
</P>
<P>
   To a smattering of applause at the end of his presentation,
Justice Sterling Sanderman found Ludwig guilty on five of 14
charges. The most serious was possession of explosives, which
carries a maximum penalty of 14 years in prison.
</P>
<P>
   That charge relates to a 1998 explosion at a Suncor well near
Hinton. Ludwig was later found in the area with explosives residue
on his hands.
</P>
<P>
   Sanderman said he believed Ludwig's motive was revenge for the
stillbirth of his grandson, which he blamed on pollution by the
energy industry near his farm.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Boonstra, Ludwig's friend and co-accused, was convicted
of one mischief charge and acquitted of 12 other charges.
</P>
<P>
   The two men will be sentenced next Wednesday. Boonstra was
released pending sentencing, but Ludwig was remanded in custody.
</P>
<P>
   ---
Alberta Legislature Cancels Question Period as Health Debate Heats
Up
</P>
<P>
   EDMONTON, Alberta (AP) -- The Alberta legislature was battened
down and question period canceled following a late-night protest
that saw police tires slashed, the legislature vandalized and a
security guard roughed up.
</P>
<P>
   ''When there's violence and property damage and a minor injury
occurring . . . that to me is not reasonable protest,'' an angry
Premier Ralph Klein said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Tuesday night rally was another in an escalating series of
public protests against Bill 11, which would expand and regulate
private-sector health care in Alberta.
</P>
<P>
   Klein, who wasn't in the house at the time but watched news
reports of the violence on TV at his Calgary condo, added such
actions won't deter his government from passing the bill.
</P>
<P>
   Speaker Ken Kowalski took the rare step of shutting down debate
in question period Wednesday after tempers flared while Opposition
Liberal Leader Nancy MacBeth hammered on Klein to pull the bill.
</P>
<P>
   Klein accused the Liberals of stirring up the violence.
</P>
<P>
   ---
Feds, Ontario Heat Up Health care Ad Battle
</P>
<P>
   OTTAWA (AP) -- The advertising battle between Ontario and the
federal government over health care is turning into a
multimillion-dollar war of attrition and some people are getting
sick of it.
</P>
<P>
   Ontario's Conservative government will launch a new TV ad Sunday
attacking Ottawa over health care funding. That's in addition to
three ads already aired.
</P>
<P>
   The campaign budget will be boosted to $5 million from $3
million, officials said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Ottawa has moved beyond print advertising to
prime-time television in the Ontario market. Its campaign is
smaller and has cost about $2 million.
</P>
<P>
   Health care activists are not giving either side any points.
</P>
<P>
   ---
Cameras To Watch For Crime Along Canada's Longest Street
</P>
<P>
   TORONTO (AP) -- The long arm of the law will soon be
strengthening its grip along the longest street in Canada.
</P>
<P>
   Toronto's police chief wants to install surveillance cameras on
Yonge Street at the corner of Dundas, a busy intersection in the
heart of Canada's largest city that police say will soon be a
modest version of New York's Times Square.
</P>
<P>
   The cameras are intended to catch criminals in the act, with
their lenses transmitting closed-circuit television images of
robberies, drug deals, shootings, assaults and other street crimes
to police headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   Cameras are already in place in many U.S. cities and they're a
fixture in some parts of Britain, including London, Leeds and
Glasgow.
</P>
<P>
   In Ontario, Sudbury police have been using the cameras for four
years, while the police services board in London, Ontario, approved
a plan last April to install cameras downtown.	   Winnipeg police will be
erecting the monitors on downtown
streets by year end.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
