<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-19 23:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Champagne Flowing in Little Havana  </HEADLINE>
By MILDRADE CHERFILS, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI (AP) -- With cheers, champagne and prayers, Little Havana
erupted in celebration on Wednesday after federal judges issued a
ruling that extends Elian Gonzalez's stay in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Miguel Saavedra, head of the Cuban exile group Vigilia Mambisa,
hefted a bottle of champagne as car horns blared and cheers of
''God Bless America'' and ''Libertad, Libertad'' rang out through
the community.
</P>
<P>
   ''I know the United States is a land of law, a land of
justice,'' Saavedra said. ''I've been telling people 'don't worry'
all along because you are in a land of law.''
</P>
<P>
   The ruling from a three-judge panel of the 11th U.S. Circuit
Court of Appeals in Atlanta extends its order keeping Elian in the
country pending arguments in the custody dispute.
</P>
<P>
   Elian's great-uncle Lazaro Gonzalez reacted by saying the family
respects U.S. laws, and his attorney said they spent the day in
quiet prayer. Elian later played outside the home where he has
lived since his rescue last November.
</P>
<P>
   By early evening, the crowd had swelled to about 600 people,
many of them chanting and singing outside the home. The family had
disappeared inside.
</P>
<P>
   Rolando Houdayer, a 48-year-old maintenance man, was on Calle
Ocho -- the street that is the heart of Little Havana -- when he
heard about the ruling: ''I'm shaking so much I can't talk. I'm so
glad, I'm so glad.''
</P>
<P>
   Barbaro Rodriguez, a 57-year-old butcher, called his wife on his
cellular phone to tell her the news.
</P>
<P>
   ''We defeated Castro one more time,'' he said. ''I have much
joy.''
</P>
<P>
   Miami-Dade Mayor Alex Penelas, who's of Cuban descent, said he
was satisfied that the court ''recognized Elian's need of due
process of law.''
</P>
<P>
   ''It's a victory for all Americans,'' he said at a separate
function at the Miami airport.
</P>
<P>
   Ramon Saul Sanchez, the leader of the anti-Castro Democracy
Movement, stood in front of the cheering and chanting crowd in
Little Havana and waited until they quieted down.
</P>
<P>
   ''We feel that God is with us,'' he said. ''This is the second
miracle of Elian. This is not the end of the battle. We are taking
the right way. This little kid also has a voice.''
</P>
<P>
   Not everyone shared the crowd's enthusiasm for the ruling. A
plane flew over the home with a banner that read: ''Send Elian home
-- the taxpayers.''
</P>
<P>
   In the media frenzy after the ruling, a cameraman for the Miami
NBC affiliate, WTVJ, said he was attacked by a reporter.
</P>
<P>
   Carlos Rigau said he was filming a live interview with Sanchez
when the reporter barged into the shot.
</P>
<P>
   ''I nudged her and she turned and hit me in the back,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He later found that he had been struck with a pen, drawing a
small amount of blood. He sought out police.
</P>
<P>
   The reporter, Maria Alvarez of the New York Post, left the scene
in a police car. She was charged with aggravated battery, a felony,
and simple battery, police spokesman Delrish Moss said. The Post
released a statement saying the newspaper believes the charges are
unfounded and that it is retaining a local lawyer to deal with the
situation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-19-00 2305 </TRAILER>
