<DOCNO> APW20000419.0246 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-19 23:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Affidavit Details Lee Contacts  </HEADLINE>
By RICHARD BENKE, Associated Press Writer
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBUQUERQUE (AP) -- An affidavit filed to secure a search warrant
in the case of fired Los Alamos researcher Wen Ho Lee details
alleged contacts between Lee and scientists in China.
</P>
<P>
   Lee's attorneys have argued that the search warrant, served last
April, was illegally broad, and they have asked a federal judge to
suppress all evidence that resulted from it.
</P>
<P>
   Lee, 60, is charged with 59 counts alleging he breached Los
Alamos National Laboratory security by downloading material from
secured computers to unsecured computers and computer tapes.
</P>
<P>
   He is being held without bail and could spend the rest of his
life in prison if convicted. He is not accused of espionage.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, U.S. District Judge John Conway granted a
prosecution motion to unseal most of the affidavit federal
investigators filed in seeking the search warrant.
</P>
<P>
   The affidavit details contacts Lee had with Chinese scientists
in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   It says Lee passed a polygraph test in 1984 that included his
statement that he did not give classified information to any
foreign government.
</P>
<P>
   However, it says Lee failed to report at least one contact with
Chinese scientists after returning from a 1988 visit to China.
</P>
<P>
   The affidavit says Lee recalled the 1988 contact with Zheng Shao
Tong and Hu Side only last spring, while talking about the visit
with the FBI.
</P>
<P>
   ''Lee stated that he thought Hu Side was an explosives expert,''
the document says, and that Zheng was an administrator with the
Institute of Applied Physics and Computational Mathematics in
China.
</P>
<P>
   Lee said he told the scientists he would not answer questions
involving sensitive information, the court papers say.
</P>
<P>
   The affidavit says Lee also had contacts with Chinese scientists
at an international conference in South Carolina and during a visit
to China in the mid-1980s -- both of which were approved by the lab.
</P>
<P>
   After the visit to China, ''he began to receive cards and
letters from these scientists,'' the affidavit says. It says one of
the scientists, Li De Yuan, was a mathematics specialist like Lee.
</P>
<P>
   The court document also outlined a process by which the FBI says
it suspects China identifies and recruits potential spies.
</P>
<P>
   It says: ''PRC (People's Republic of China) intelligence
operations virtually always target overseas ethnic Chinese with
access to intelligence information sought by the PRC.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Travel to China is an integral element of the Chinese
intelligence collection tradecraft, particularly when it involves
overseas ethnic Chinese,'' the affidavit says.
</P>
<P>
   Lee, a naturalized U.S. citizen, was born in Taiwan.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER> AP-NY-04-19-00 2318 </TRAILER>
