<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-19 23:39 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bush-appointed Police Chief Resigns  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   MARSHALL, Texas (AP) -- A top law enforcement official appointed
by Gov. George W. Bush resigned Wednesday following months of
criticism over racial remarks he made in a 1998 court deposition.
</P>
<P>
   Marshall Police Chief Charles Williams, who took over last year
as presiding officer of the Texas Commission on Law Enforcement
Officers Standards and Education, said in the deposition that the
term ''porch monkey'' was not a racial slur and that blacks didn't
mind being called ''niggers'' 50 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has said he was unaware of the statements when Williams
took over the panel, and called on him to apologize.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday morning, the Texas Rainbow Coalition asked Bush to
demand Williams' resignation.
</P>
<P>
   ''These recent statements by a man who Bush chose for a
leadership position in Texas raise serious questions about the
kinds of appointments he would make as president,'' said Coalition
Chairwoman Hazel Faulke-Obey.
</P>
<P>
   Williams did not indicate Wednesday whether he would resign as
police chief. He did not return calls seeking comment, and his
staff said he is undergoing cancer treatment.
</P>
<P>
   ''After serious consideration, I have decided it is in the best
interest of my personal health and the Texas Commission on Law
Enforcement Officers Standards and Education to step down,''
Williams said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   ''I apologize to those who were offended by my previous comments
and deeply regret not making my points clearer to everyone
concerned,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush spokesman Mike Jones said: ''We have accepted his
resignation. We respect the work that he's done in law enforcement,
and we agree with his decision.''
</P>
<P>
   The deposition was for a race discrimination lawsuit filed
against Williams and his department.
</P>
<P>
   In Marshall, some members of the black community have said they
plan to ask the city commission to fire Williams as police chief.
Several hundred people met at a church Monday night and said they
would send petitions to the City Commission.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
