<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tokyo Stocks Rise  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO (AP) -- Tokyo stocks edged higher Thursday morning on
bargain hunting following an earlier weak start. The dollar was
higher against the yen.
</P>
<P>
   The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average, which was down
some 85 points early in the session, reversed into positive
territory, gaining 81.72 points, or 0.43 percent, to 19,168.34
points at the end of the morning session.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, the average closed up 117.10 points, or 0.62
percent.
</P>
<P>
   The dollar bought 104.67 yen in late morning, up 0.19 yen from
late Wednesday in Tokyo but below its late New York level of 104.78
yen.
</P>
<P>
   On the stock market, the Nikkei index started lower on selling
of high technology issues following a drop in the tech-laden Nasdaq
composite index in New York Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Traders said, however, that investors later in thin trading
bought shares in selected electrical industry companies, reversing
an earlier overall drop in prices.
</P>
<P>
   In New York on Wednesday, the Dow Jones industrial average fell
92.46 points to close at 10,674.96. The Nasdaq composite index
closed at 3,706.41, down 87.16.
</P>
<P>
   The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the
first section was up 1.85 points, or 0.11 percent, to 1,621.67
points. The TOPIX closed up 23.42 points, or 1.42 percent, the day
before.
</P>
<P>
   In currency dealings, the dollar remained relatively steady in
morning Tokyo trading following its strength against the euro in
New York. Trading remained in a narrow range amid a lack of
market-moving news.
</P>
<P>
   In overseas trading, the greenback rose to an all-time high
against the euro before losing some ground Wednesday. The euro's
weakness stemmed from doubts that Europe will take measures anytime
soon to stimulate growth and investment opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, the euro was traded at 98.55 yen, down from 98.94
yen late Wednesday in Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
   The yield on the benchmark 10-year Japanese government bond rose
to 1.7350 percent from Wednesday's finish of 1.7050 percent. Its
price fell 0.26 point to 101.42.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
